[KEEP] The Panjshir conflict[citation needed] is a political dispute between the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and the Taliban which began following the Fall of Kabul (2021). [KEEP] As of August 2021, no military conflict had occurred in Panjshir Province and a negotiated end to the political impasse has been discussed. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The Islamic Republic of Afghanistan is a state that is the notional continuation of the regime that previously governed Afghanistan. [KEEP] It exercises de facto control over the Panjshir Valley, which is largely contiguous with Panjshir Province and according to The Week, as of August 2021 is "the only region out of [the] Taliban's hands". [KEEP] <Background> \c\cPrior to the Fall of Kabul, Panjshiris began moving military equipment from surrounding areas, including helicopters and armored vehicles, into Panjshir Province. [KEEP] There, they were joined by commanders of the Afghan National Army Commando Corps. [KEEP] <History> \c\cOn [KEEP] 17 August 2021, Amrullah Saleh — citing provisions of the Constitution of Afghanistan — declared himself President of Afghanistan from the Panjshir Valley, and vowed to continue military operations against the Taliban from there. [KEEP] His claim to the presidency was endorsed by Ahmad Massoud and Islamic Republic of Afghanistan Minister of Defence Bismillah Mohammadi. [KEEP] At around the same time, remnants of the Afghan National Army began massing in the Panjshir Valley at the urging of Masoud. [KEEP] <History> \c\cAs of 17 August, the Panjshir Valley was — according to one observer — "under siege on all sides" but had not come under direct attack. [KEEP] As of August 2021, no military conflict had occurred in Panjshir Province and a negotiated end to the political impasse has been discussed. [RM] <History> \c\c
[KEEP] The attacks have left 439 people dead and more than 100 others injured. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cSeveral major attacks occurred in Niger during the 2010s and 2020. [KEEP] However, this is the first time that over 100 civilians were killed in single incidents, marking the January attack and 21 March attack as the deadliest against civilians in the country since the insurgency in the Maghreb began. [KEEP] It is the first year in which attacks were carried out with frequency in the country. [KEEP] As of August, attacks were carried out every month of 2021. [KEEP] The previous biggest attack in Niger against civilians was [KEEP] the 12 December 2020 [KEEP] Toumour attack, which resulted in 28 people killed. [KEEP] Both the December 2020 and January 2021 attacks were carried out during Niger's municipal and regional elections, while the February bombing specifically targeted members of the electoral commission. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn the same day as the January attacks, two Algerian soldiers were killed in a shooting in Algeria and two French soldiers were killed in a bombing in Mali. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe January attacks occurred in two villages, Tchombangou (at 14°49′48′′N 01°48′45′′E\ufeff / \ufeff14.83000°N 1.81250°E\ufeff / 14.83000; 1.81250) and Zaroumdareye (at 14°54′21′′N 01°46′36′′E\ufeff / \ufeff14.90583°N 1.77667°E\ufeff / 14.90583; 1.77667), which are seven kilometres apart, and initially left 79 people dead and 75 wounded. [KEEP] Of the deceased victims, 49 were killed in Tchombangou and 30 in Zaroumdareye. [KEEP] A day after the attack, 21 more people were found dead and others succumbed to their injuries on Tchombangou, bringing the total death toll to 100. [KEEP] On 8 January UN’s High Commissioner for Refugees spokesman said that 73 people had been killed in the village of Tchouma Bangou and 32 in Zaroumdareye, making the total death toll 105. [KEEP] The government of Niger dispatched soldiers to the border after the attacks. [KEEP] The attackers are Islamist militants who arrived in the villages while crossing the border from Mali; however, the exact terrorist organization who carried out the attacks is not clear so far. [KEEP] <Attacks - January> \c\cSome time before the massacre, two militants who were seen in the area were killed by the local villagers. [KEEP] Those attacks are suspected to be in retaliation for those killings, according to the country's interior minister. [KEEP] <Attacks - January> \c\cOn [KEEP] 21 February, seven members of the electoral commission were killed and three others wounded in a landmine explosion in Tillabéri. [KEEP] The attack was carried out on the same day of the presidential election's second round. [KEEP] <Attacks - February> \c\cOn [KEEP] 16 March, armed men on motorcycles attacked a convoy returning from a market in Banibangou by the Malian border to a nearby village in Southwestern Niger's Tillabéri Region, killing 58 people. [KEEP] <Attacks - March> \c\cOn [KEEP] The death toll would make the attack the deadliest committed by suspected jihadists in Niger's history. [KEEP] Newly elected President Mohamed Bazoum condemned the attacks and declared three days of national mourning. [KEEP] <Attacks - March> \c\cOn 24 March, at least 10 people were killed during attacks at two villages in the Tillabéri Region. [KEEP] <Attacks - March> \c\cOn [KEEP] 18 April, at least 19 civilians were killed and two wounded when armed men raid a village in Tillabéri Region. [KEEP] <Attacks - April> \c\cOn [KEEP] 3 May, a military patrol was ambushed in the Tahoua Region, resulting in the killing of 16 soldiers and the wounding of six more. [KEEP] It was the first attack against soldiers in the country[citation needed] since the beginning of the year. [KEEP] <Attacks - May> \c\cOn 12 May, five villagers were killed and two more wounded after militants stormed the village of Fantio, in the Tillabéri region, during Eid al-Fitr celebrations. [KEEP] <Attacks - May> \c\cOn [KEEP] 30 May, four civilians and four soldiers were killed during a raid carried out by Boko Haram militants in the town of Diffa, in the Diffa Region. [KEEP] The jihadists attacked the town in the late afternoon, riding in about 15 vehicles, but were pushed back by responding security forces during a long gunfight, in which six attackers were killed. [KEEP] <Attacks - May> \c\cOn 25 June, armed men attacked a village and nearby locations, killing a total of 19 civilians. [KEEP] Initially, the attackers stormed the Danga Zawne village, in the Tillabéri region, killing three people. [KEEP] They then attacked nearby farms, killing the other sixteen people. [KEEP] <Attacks - June> \c\cOn 29 June, Boko Haram fighters opened fire on a bus along the road between Diffa and Maine Soroa, killing three civilians, including the bus driver, two villagers and a village chief; two more were wounded. [KEEP] The fighters then moved on another road and opened fire on a group of soldiers, wounding six of them. [KEEP] A gunfight erupted, and thirteen terrorists were killed. [KEEP] <Attacks - June> \c\cOn [KEEP] 2 July, around 100 heavily armed “terrorists” riding motorcycles attacked the Tchoma Bangou village, killing four civilians. [KEEP] Security forces responded to the attack, starting a gun battle, resulting in the death of five soldiers and 40 terrorists. [KEEP] <Attacks - July> \c\cOn [KEEP] 25 July, fourteen people were killed and one more was wounded as gunmen stormed the village of Wiye. [KEEP] Nine of the victims are killed while working at fields. [KEEP] <Attacks - July> \c\cOn [KEEP] 28 July, 19 civilians were killed and five more wounded as militants stormed the village of Deye Koukou in the Banibangou area, near the border with Mali. [KEEP] <Attacks - July> \c\cOn 1 August, Islamist militants ambushed and opened fire on a group of soldiers in Torodi, Tillabéri Region. [KEEP] As the soldiers were escaping and carried the wounded, a bomb exploded. [KEEP] Fifteen soldiers were killed in the attack, while six more went missing. [KEEP] <Attacks - August> \c\cOn
