2 flights. [KEEP] The Pentagon said it has evacuated about 7,000 people from the country. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 20, approximately 5,700 people were evacuated on 16 flights. [KEEP] The Pentagon said it has evacuated about 12,700 people from the country. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 22, the Department of Defense ordered the activation of the Civil Reserve Air Fleet to assist in the evacuation. [KEEP] The current activation is for 18 planes: four from United Airlines; three each from American Airlines, Atlas Air, Delta Air Lines and Omni Air; and two from Hawaiian Airlines. [KEEP] Commercial airline pilots and crews would help transport thousands of Afghans who are arriving at U.S. bases in Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates. [KEEP] From the bases in the Middle East, the airliners would augment military flights carrying Afghans to Germany, Italy, Spain and other stops in Europe, and then ultimately to the United States. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cBy August 16, at least eight people had been killed at the Kabul International Airport as thousands of people tried to forcibly board planes. [KEEP] At least two people were seen falling to their deaths from the sky after clinging to the landing gear of a departing C-17 cargo plane, while at least three people clinging to the side of an Air Force jet were killed after being run over. [KEEP] Remains of another dead Afghan were found in the landing gear of the American C-17, after the pilots were forced to make an emergency landing in a nearby country because they were unable to retract the landing gear. [KEEP] The Pentagon said that two armed men who fired into a crowd were killed by U.S. troops."} <Casualties> \c\c
