[KEEP] The Panjshir conflict is a conflict between the heavily diminished Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, including the Panjshir resistance, and the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan (controlled by the Taliban) on the other. [KEEP] It began on 17 August 2021 following the Fall of Kabul. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The Islamic Republic of Afghanistan exercises de facto control over the Panjshir Valley, which is largely contiguous with Panjshir Province and according to The Week, as of August 2021 is "the only region out of [the] Taliban's hands". [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe population of the Panjshir valley consists of a majority of ethnic Tajik people, as opposed to the majority of the Taliban, who are Pashtuns. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe valley is well known for its natural defences. [KEEP] Surrounded by the Hindu Kush mountains, Panjshir never fell to the Soviets during the invasion of the 1980's nor to the Taliban during the civil war of the 1990's. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 17 August 2021, Amrullah Saleh—citing provisions of the Constitution of Afghanistan—declared himself President of Afghanistan from the Panjshir Valley, and vowed to continue military operations against the Taliban from there. [KEEP] His claim to the presidency was endorsed by Ahmad Massoud and Islamic Republic of Afghanistan Minister of Defence Bismillah Khan Mohammadi along with the Afghan Embassy in Dushanbe. [KEEP] At around the same time, remnants of the Afghan National Army began massing in the Panjshir Valley at the urging of Massoud. [KEEP] Local civilians also responded to his mobilization calls. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cPrior to the Fall of Kabul, Panjshiris began moving military equipment from surrounding areas, including helicopters and armored vehicles, into Panjshir Province. [KEEP] There, they were joined by commanders and soldiers of the Afghan National Army Commando Corps. [KEEP] Most of them regrouped at Baghlan Province's Andarab District before moving to Panjshir after making their escape from  Kunduz, Badakhshan, Takhar, and Baghlan. [KEEP] According to a Russian estimate, the disparate Anti-Taliban forces had approximately 7,000 personnel under arms as of mid August 2021. [KEEP] Other estimates place this number as low as 2,000, though Saleh himself claims 10,000 men under arms. [KEEP] By 22 August, Ahmad Massoud claimed to have gathered about 9,000 fighters and at least a "handful of armoured humvees" in the valley. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and Anti-Taliban militias> \c\cThere are difference between the forces loyal to Saleh and those loyal to Ahmad Massoud, as the former is hardcore anti-Taliban and anti-Pakistani, whereas the latter maintained good relations with Pakistan which was supportive of the Taliban. [KEEP] As a result, Massoud was more willing to negiotiate with the Taliban. [KEEP] By 22 August, the resistance also confirmed that several local militias had begun to fight the Taliban on their own, independent of the Panjshir-based forces. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and Anti-Taliban militias> \c\cAccording to Yasin Zia, the resistance has already secured access to helicopters formerly used by the Afghan military. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and Anti-Taliban militias> \c\cAn estimate by the Combating Terrorism Center at the U.S. Military Academy made prior to the Fall of Kabul estimated the strength of the Taliban, throughout the whole of Afghanistan, at 60,000 armed cadre supported by up to 200,000 irregulars. [KEEP] Due to the rapid capitulation of the Afghan National Army, the Taliban have since acquired substantial material of US manufacture, including armored vehicles and combat aircraft. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan> \c\cAs of 17 August, the Panjshir Valley was—according to one observer—"under siege on all sides" but had not come under direct attack. [KEEP] On 18 August, the number of admissions for war injuries was increasing at the Emergency Surgical Centre for War Victims in Anabah in Panjshir. [KEEP] By 22 August, Ahmad Massoud's forces were mostly focused on defending Panjshir as well as training. [ADD] <Timeline - Panjshir Province> \c\cOn 22 August In response, the IEA announced "hundreds" of its forces had been dispatched to the Panjshir Valley. [ADD] , the Islamic Emirate gave the opposition forces a four hour ultimatum to surrender. [ADD] In a statement to Al Arabiya, Massoud rejected the ultimatum. [KEEP] The three districts had reportedly experienced a revolt, led by a local police chief, after Taliban had conducted unpopular house-to-house searches. [KEEP] Bismillah Khan Mohammadi announced the operational success of the districts being recaptured via Twitter. [KEEP] <Timeline - Baghlan Province> \c\cAudiovisual reports of the events circulated on social media and were reported by Pajhwok Afghan News. [KEEP] Later on the 20th, it was reported that the forces, led by Abdul Hamid Dadgar, had recaptured Andarab, though the Taliban had not yet commented. [KEEP] <Timeline - Baghlan Province> \c\cA source within the Panjshir resistance consequently confirmed their involvement in the operations in Baghlan Province, and stated that they planned on seizing a northern highway which could allow them to link up with Tajikistan and Uzbekistan. [KEEP] Taliban social media accounts called the counteroffensive a "betrayal" of the amnesty the Taliban had offered. [KEEP] It was reported on 22 August 2021 that Taliban fighters have been sent to the Keshnabad area of Andarab in order to kidnap the children whose parents are a part of anti-Taliban forces. [KEEP] <Timeline - Baghlan Province> \c\cAs of August 2021, a negotiated end to the political impasse has been attempted, with Saleh calling for a "peace deal" with the Taliban. [KEEP] On 18 August, Mohammad Zahir Aghbar, the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan's ambassador to Tajikistan, indicated the possibility of including the Taliban in a coalition government as a means of diffusing the stalemate. [KEEP] <Resolution> \c\cOn 21 August 2021, it was reported that Panjshir representatives were meeting with Abdullah Abdullah and Hamid Karzai, members of the Coordination Council, to "discuss the current situation and ways of providing security to Afghans". [KEEP] <Resolution> \c\cOn [KEEP] 22 August 2021, the Russian Embassy in Afghanistan was reportedly asked by a Taliban representative to reach out to Panjshir-based leaders to possible mediate. [KEEP] Meanwhile, resistance spokesman Ali Maisam Nazary informed the Agence France-Presse that Ahmad Massoud's group would prefer a peaceful resolution of the conflict, under the condition that a future government implemented a system of "decentralisation" and "equal rights" across the country. [KEEP] <Resolution> \c\cThe USA and Western forces are commented as lowly supportive of this movement due to ongoing evacuation of Kabul depending fully on Talibans\' benevolence. [KEEP] Massoud Washington Post op-ed requesting Western support have been analysed as an evidence of the absence of direct communication and support between the resistance and the US government. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\c
[KEEP] U.S. personnel also assisted NATO and regional allies in their respective evacuation efforts at Kabul International Airport. [KEEP] The operation is concurrent with the larger American military withdrawal from Afghanistan. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe operation's name was officially unveiled on July 14 by the Biden administration. [KEEP] <Operational history> \c\cOn [KEEP] July 30, 2021, the first group of 200 Afghan interpreters arrived at Fort Lee, Virginia, for SIV processing with at least 20,000 SIV holders and applicants remaining in the process of being relocated. [KEEP] <Operational history> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 12, following the deterioration of the situation in Afghanistan, the Biden administration announced that 3,000 U.S. troops would be deployed to the Kabul International Airport in order to secure the evacuation of embassy personnel, U.S. nationals and SIV applicants. [KEEP] <Operational history> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 22, President Joe Biden said that American troops may remain in Afghanistan past the August 31 deadline. [KEEP] He also announced that 11,000 people have been evacuated in the past 36 hours. [KEEP] <Operational history> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 15, following the fall of Kabul, the Pentagon and the State Department announced the expansion of the military presence at the airport to nearly 6,000 troops. [KEEP] U.S. military took control over the air traffic control of the airport later in the day. [KEEP] On August 16, a C-17 cargo plane, which usually includes less than 150 paratroopers, safely evacuated roughly 823 people to the Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\c [KEEP] The Pentagon confirmed the head of U.S. Central Command, General Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr., met Taliban leaders based in Qatar's capital Doha. [KEEP] The Taliban officials agreed to terms set by McKenzie for refugees to flee using Kabul Airport. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 17, approximately 1,100 people were evacuated on 13 flights. [KEEP] The White House said more than 3,200 U.S. citizens, permanent residents and refugees were evacuated from the country, and nearly 2,000 Afghan interpreters were flown to the U.S. for SIV processing. [KEEP] On August 18, Deputy Secretary of State Wendy Sherman said U.S. military flights evacuated approximately 2,000 people, and said it has processed more than 4,840 people for evacuation. [KEEP] The State Department said the U.S. military has evacuated nearly 5,000 people from the country. [KEEP] On August 19, more than 2,000 people were evacuated on 12 flights. [KEEP] The Pentagon said it has evacuated about 7,000 people from the country. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 20, approximately 5,700 people were evacuated on 16 flights. [KEEP] The Pentagon said it has evacuated about 12,700 people from the country. [KEEP] On August 21, United States Army major general William D. Taylor announced that 17,000 people have been evacuated in the past few weeks, including 2,500 Americans. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 22, the Department of Defense ordered the activation of the Civil Reserve Air Fleet to assist in the evacuation. [KEEP] The current activation is for 18 planes: four from United Airlines; three each from American Airlines, Atlas Air, Delta Air Lines and Omni Air; and two from Hawaiian Airlines. [KEEP] Commercial airline pilots and crews would help transport thousands of Afghans who are arriving at U.S. bases in Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates. [KEEP] From the bases in the Middle East, the airliners would augment military flights carrying Afghans to Germany, Italy, Spain and other stops in Europe, and then ultimately to the United States.
[KEEP] The attacks have left 508 people dead and more than 100 others injured. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cSeveral major attacks occurred in Niger during the 2010s and 2020. [KEEP] However, this is the first time that over 100 civilians were killed in single incidents, marking the January attack and 21 March attack as the deadliest against civilians in the country since the insurgency in the Maghreb began. [KEEP] It is the first year in which attacks were carried out with frequency in the country. [KEEP] As of August, attacks were carried out every month of 2021. [KEEP] The previous biggest attack in Niger against civilians was [KEEP] the 12 December 2020 [KEEP] Toumour attack, which resulted in 28 people killed. [KEEP] Both the December 2020 and January 2021 attacks were carried out during Niger's municipal and regional elections, while the February bombing specifically targeted members of the electoral commission. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn the same day as the January attacks, two Algerian soldiers were killed in a shooting in Algeria and two French soldiers were killed in a bombing in Mali. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 2 January, the villages of Tchombangou (at 14°49′48′′N 01°48′45′′E\ufeff / \ufeff14.83000°N 1.81250°E\ufeff / 14.83000; 1.81250) and Zaroumdareye (at 14°54′21′′N 01°46′36′′E\ufeff / \ufeff14.90583°N 1.77667°E\ufeff / 14.90583; 1.77667), which are seven kilometres apart, were attacked by several militants. [KEEP] The attack initially left 79 people dead and 75 wounded. [KEEP] Of the deceased victims, 49 were killed in Tchombangou and 30 in Zaroumdareye. [KEEP] A day after the attack, 21 more people were found dead and others succumbed to their injuries on Tchombangou, bringing the total death toll to 100. [KEEP] On 8 January UN’s High Commissioner for Refugees spokesman said that 73 people had been killed in the village of Tchouma Bangou and 32 in Zaroumdareye, making the total death toll 105. [KEEP] The government of Niger dispatched soldiers to the border after the attacks. [KEEP] The attackers are Islamist militants who arrived in the villages while crossing the border from Mali; however, the exact terrorist organization who carried out the attacks is not clear so far. [KEEP] <Attacks - January> \c\cSome time before the massacre, two militants who were seen in the area were killed by the local villagers. [KEEP] Those attacks are suspected to be in retaliation for those killings, according to the country's interior minister. [KEEP] <Attacks - January> \c\cOn [KEEP] 21 February, seven members of the electoral commission were killed and three others wounded in a landmine explosion in Tillabéri. [KEEP] The attack was carried out on the same day of the presidential election's second round. [KEEP] <Attacks - February> \c\cOn [KEEP] 16 March, armed men on motorcycles attacked a convoy returning from a market in Banibangou by the Malian border to a nearby village in Southwestern Niger's Tillabéri Region, killing 58 people. [KEEP] <Attacks - March> \c\cOn [KEEP] The death toll would make the attack the deadliest committed by suspected jihadists in Niger's history. [KEEP] Newly elected President Mohamed Bazoum condemned the attacks and declared three days of national mourning. [KEEP] <Attacks - March> \c\cOn 24 March, at least 10 people were killed during attacks at two villages in the Tillabéri Region. [KEEP] <Attacks - March> \c\cOn [KEEP] 18 April, at least 19 civilians were killed and two wounded when armed men raid a village in Tillabéri Region. [KEEP] <Attacks - April> \c\cOn [KEEP] 3 May, a military patrol was ambushed in the Tahoua Region, resulting in the killing of 16 soldiers and the wounding of six more. [KEEP] It was the first attack against soldiers in the country[citation needed] since the beginning of the year. [KEEP] <Attacks - May> \c\cOn 12 May, five villagers were killed and two more wounded after militants stormed the village of Fantio, in the Tillabéri region, during Eid al-Fitr celebrations. [KEEP] <Attacks - May> \c\cOn [KEEP] 30 May, four civilians and four soldiers were killed during a raid carried out by Boko Haram militants in the town of Diffa, in the Diffa Region. [KEEP] The jihadists attacked the town in the late afternoon, riding in about 15 vehicles, but were pushed back by responding security forces during a long gunfight, in which six attackers were killed. [KEEP] <Attacks - May> \c\cOn 25 June, armed men attacked a village and nearby locations, killing a total of 19 civilians. [KEEP] Initially, the attackers stormed the Danga Zawne village, in the Tillabéri region, killing three people. [KEEP] They then attacked nearby farms, killing the other sixteen people. [KEEP] <Attacks - June> \c\cOn 29 June, Boko Haram fighters opened fire on a bus along the road between Diffa and Maine Soroa, killing three civilians, including the bus driver, two villagers and a village chief; two more were wounded. [KEEP] The fighters then moved on another road and opened fire on a group of soldiers, wounding six of them. [KEEP] A gunfight erupted, and thirteen terrorists were killed. [KEEP] <Attacks - June> \c\cOn [KEEP] 2 July, around 100 heavily armed “terrorists” riding motorcycles attacked the Tchoma Bangou village, killing four civilians. [KEEP] Security forces responded to the attack, starting a gun battle, resulting in the death of five soldiers and 40 terrorists. [KEEP] <Attacks - July> \c\cOn [KEEP] 25 July, fourteen people were killed and one more was wounded as gunmen stormed the village of Wiye. [KEEP] Nine of the victims are killed while working at fields. [KEEP] <Attacks - July> \c\cOn [KEEP] 28 July, 19 civilians were killed and five more wounded as militants stormed the village of Deye Koukou in the Banibangou area, near the border with Mali. [KEEP] <Attacks - July> \c\cOn 1 August, Islamist militants ambushed and opened fire on a group of soldiers in Torodi, Tillabéri Region. [KEEP] As the soldiers were escaping and carried the wounded, a bomb exploded. [KEEP] Fifteen soldiers were killed in the attack, while six more went missing. [KEEP] <Attacks - August> \c\cOn [KEEP] 16 August, gunmen on motorbikes stormed the village of Darey-Daye, Niger, opening fire against civilians while they were tending their fields, killing 37 people, including fourteen children.
[KEEP] On 26 August 2021, two suicide bombings occurred near Abbey Gate at Hamid Karzai International Airport in Kabul, Afghanistan. [KEEP] These attacks came hours after the United States State Department told Americans outside the airport to leave due to a terrorist threat. [KEEP] A second explosion was reported. [KEEP] At least 13 people have been killed by the attacks. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAfter [KEEP] Afghanistan fell to Taliban control on 15 August 2021, Hamid Karzai International Airport became the only secure way out of Afghanistan. [KEEP] Security concerns grew after hundreds of ISIS-K members escaped from jails at Bagram and Pul-e-Charkhi. [KEEP] Hours before the attack, US diplomats in Kabul warned American citizens to leave the airport due to security threats. [KEEP] United Kingdom Armed Forces Minister James Heappey has also warned of a highly credible threat of attack at Kabul airport by Islamic state militants. [KEEP] Embassies from United States, United Kingdom, and Australia have also warned about high security threats on the airport. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cU.S. President Joe Biden also received multiple reports of a possible attack during the week preceding the attack. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe attack was suspected to have been carried out by the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Khorasan Province (ISIS-K) amid the 2021 evacuation of Afghanistan. [KEEP] A crowd of local and foreign civilians had fled to the airport to evacuate. [KEEP] At Abbey Gate, one of the gates entering into the airport, a suicide bomber detonated an explosive. [KEEP] At least 13 people were killed during the attack. [KEEP] The toll was confirmed by both Taliban officials and foreign troops. [KEEP] At least 60 people were injured, including a number of Taliban members and foreign soldiers. [RM] Up to five U.S. personnel were injured, including three U.S. Marines. [ADD] Four US Marines were among those killed, and up to five U.S. personnel were injured, including three U.S. Marines. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\cA second explosion also occurred at Baron Gate, named after the nearby Baron Hotel in Kabul. [KEEP] Baron Hotel has been used in the past as a gathering point for American citizens for rescue and evacuation. [KEEP] The hotel also has served as a processing center for Afghan people fleeing the country to escape Taliban control. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\c [KEEP] The Taliban, through a tweet by their spokesperson, condemned the attack, saying "evil circles will be strictly stopped." [KEEP] Abdullah Abdullah, former Chief Executive of Afghanistan and current National Coalition of Afghanistan leader, also condemned the attack. [KEEP] <Reactions - Domestic> \c\c France: French President Emmanuel Macron has voiced full support for coordinating with "American allies" in response to the explosions. [KEEP] <Reactions - International> \c\c
[KEEP] After the Taliban returned to power in Afghanistan and proclaimed intentions to re-establish the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan after the August 2021 fall of Kabul, there has been one known drone strike against the country. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c27 August 2021: [KEEP] The United States launched an airstrike against an ISIL-KP member in Nangarhar Province. [RM] According to two defense officials, the strike was carried out by an MQ-9 Reaper drone with guided munitions to minimize civilian casualties, and the target was riding in a vehicle with one associate. [RM] CENTCOM said it believes the man planned the 2021 Kabul airport attack, which are attacks against the United States in Kabul, and does not believe any civilians were killed with him. [ADD] Two "high-profiled" ISIS targets were killed and a third person was injured.
[KEEP] A suicide bombing at Hamid Karzai International Airport in Kabul, Afghanistan took place on 26 August 2021 at 17:50 local time (13:20 UTC), during the evacuation from Afghanistan. [KEEP] At least 182 people were killed, including 28 members of the Taliban and 13 members of the United States military, who were the first American military casualties in Afghanistan since February 2020. [KEEP] The Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Khorasan Province (ISIL-KP) claimed responsibility for the attack. [KEEP] On 27 August, the United States launched an airstrike against an ISIL-KP "planner" in Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAfter [KEEP] Afghanistan fell to Taliban control on 15 August 2021, Hamid Karzai International Airport became the only secure way out of Afghanistan. [KEEP] Security concerns grew after hundreds of members of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Khorasan Province (ISIL-KP) escaped from jails at Bagram and Pul-e-Charkhi. [KEEP] On 16 August, the Pentagon warned the US Congress about the increased threat of a terrorist attack from IS following the fall of Kubul the day previous. [KEEP] US President Joe Biden received multiple reports of a possible attack during the week preceding the attack, and warned on 22 August in remarks from the White House that the longer US troops remained in the country, the greater the threat posed by IS became to US personnel and civilians near the Hamid Karzai International Airport. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cHours before the attack, US diplomats in Kabul warned American citizens to leave the airport because of security threats. [KEEP] United Kingdom Armed Forces Minister James Heappey had also warned of a highly credible threat of attack at Kabul airport by Islamic State militants. [KEEP] Embassies from United States, United Kingdom, and Australia also warned about high security threats on the airport. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cAmid the 2021 evacuation of Afghanistan, a crowd of local and foreign civilians had fled to the airport to evacuate. [KEEP] At Abbey Gate, one of the gates leading into the airport, a suicide bomber detonated an explosive. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\cThe explosion occurred by a canal with American forces on one side; checking evacuees passports, visas and other documentation before allowing them inside the airport. [KEEP] An eyewitness stated that the explosion felt as if someone pulled the ground from under his feet, and saw other evacuees thrown in the air by the force of the blast. [KEEP] The following day, it was confirmed that there was no such second explosion. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\cAt least 182 people were killed during the attack, including 169 Afghan civilians and 13 US service members. [KEEP] Two of the killed civilians were British dual-nationals and one was the child of a British national. [KEEP] It was initially reported that 28 Taliban fighters had also been killed in the attack, but this was later denied by Taliban spokesman Zabiullah Mujahid in an interview with Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty. [KEEP] The dead Americans were identified as eleven marines, one soldier, and one Navy corpsman. [KEEP] The US deaths were the first US service deaths in Afghanistan since February 2020 and were the largest single loss of life of US military personnel since the 2011 Afghanistan Boeing Chinook shootdown. [KEEP] <Victims> \c\cAt least 150 more people were injured, including 18 US military personnel and a number of Taliban members. [KEEP] <Victims> \c\c [KEEP] The attack was carried out by ISIL-KP, which released a claim of responsibility and named the bomber as Abdul Rahman al-Logari. [KEEP] <Perpetrators> \c\cThe Taliban and ISIL-KP, despite both being jihadist groups, are enemies and have fought a bloody war among each other. [KEEP] General Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr., head of the US Central Command (CENTCOM), said there was no indication that the Taliban allowed the attacks to happen. [KEEP] <Perpetrators> \c\cThrough a tweet by their spokesperson, the Taliban condemned the attack, saying "evil circles will be strictly stopped". [KEEP] The Taliban later announced that they would take every possible measure to capture ISIL-KP leader Shahab al-Muhajir. [KEEP] <Reactions and responses> \c\cAbdullah [KEEP] Abdullah, former Chief Executive of Afghanistan and current National Coalition of Afghanistan leader, condemned the attack. [KEEP] Some civilians claimed to reporters that the attack had strengthened their resolve to evacuate from the country in fear of more attacks. [KEEP] <Reactions and responses> \c\cUS [KEEP] President Joe Biden made a public address following the attack. [KEEP] He honored the American service members who were killed, calling them "heroes" and saying they lost their lives "in the service of liberty", and stated that the US had evacuated more than 100,000 Americans, Afghans, and others. [KEEP] He expressed deep sorrow for the Afghan victims as well. [KEEP] Biden said to those who wished harm upon the US that "we will hunt you down and make you pay." [KEEP] The government of the United Kingdom also said that they will continue Operation Pitting, the evacuation from Afghanistan. [KEEP] <Reactions and responses> \c\cMany nations expressed condemnation for the Kabul airport attack and solidarity with the victims and troops conducting evacuations at the airport. [KEEP] The European Commission and the United Nations likewise condemned the attack. [KEEP] German Chancellor Angela Merkel cancelled an upcoming trip to Israel, and will stay in Germany to monitor the evacuation of German troops. [KEEP] Biden also rescheduled a meeting with visiting Israeli Prime Minister Naftali Bennett because of the attack. [KEEP] The United Kingdom said civilian evacuations would continue in spite of the attack. [KEEP] <Reactions and responses> \c\cOn [RM] According to two defense officials, the strike was carried out by an MQ-9 Reaper drone with guided munitions to minimize civilian casualties, and the target was riding in a vehicle with one associate. [RM] CENTCOM said it believes the man planned attacks against the United States in Kabul and does not believe any civilians were killed with him.
[KEEP] Relations between the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan and the United States started recently, but not officially, on August 15, 2021, after the Taliban returned to power and proclaimed intentions to re-establish the Islamic Emirate after the August 2021 fall of Kabul. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The United States does not recognize the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as a government, although the US said they could recognize a government that respected basic rights. [KEEP] <2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] August 27, The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan appointed Khalil Haqqani as head of security in Kabul. [KEEP] Haqqani, a veteran of the Soviet–Afghan War and war on terror, is a designated terrorist by the United States, and is currently wanted on a US$5 million bounty. [KEEP] <2021 - August 27> \c\cFollowing the 2021 Kabul airport attack, through a tweet by their spokesperson, the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan condemned the attack, saying "evil circles will be strictly stopped". [KEEP] The Taliban later announced that they would take every possible measure to capture ISIS-K leader Shahab al-Muhajir. [KEEP] The United States also launched an airstrike on the 27th that killed two "high-profiled" ISIS targets and a third person was injured. [KEEP] The two targets killed were "ISIS-K planners and facilitators". [KEEP] <2021 - August 27> \c\cFollowing the airstrike by the US on August 27, Taliban spokesperson Zabiullah Mujahid condemned the attack saying they consider the airstrike a "clear attack on Afghan territory". [KEEP] <2021 - August 28> \c\c
[KEEP] After the Taliban returned to power in Afghanistan and proclaimed intentions to re-establish the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan after the August 2021 fall of Kabul, there have been two known drone strikes against the country. [KEEP] As a result of the airstrikes, there has been at least 12 fatalities and one injury in the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c27 August 2021: [KEEP] The United States launched an airstrike targeting an IS-K member in Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] The target was riding in a vehicle. [KEEP] He was killed alongside another high-profiled member, while a third militant was injured. [KEEP] The two killed were described as a planner and a facilitator. [KEEP] The airstrike was carried out a day after the 2021 Kabul airport attack, which resulted in the death of more than 180 people. [RM] All the occupants of the vehicle were killed, including six children. \c\c [KEEP]
[KEEP] The Panjshir conflict is a conflict between the heavily diminished Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, including the Panjshir resistance, and the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan (controlled by the Taliban). [KEEP] It began on 17 August 2021 following the Fall of Kabul and Amrullah Saleh assuming the Afghan presidency and declaring the resistance. [KEEP] Ten days later, both sides declared a ceasefire and agreed to solve all problems through dialogue. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The former Islamic Republic of Afghanistan exercises de facto control over the Panjshir Valley, which is largely contiguous with Panjshir Province and according to The Week, as of August 2021 is "the only region out of [the] Taliban's hands". [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe population of the Panjshir valley consists of a majority of ethnic Tajik people, while the majority of the Taliban are Pashtuns. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe valley is well known for its natural defences. [KEEP] Surrounded by the Hindu Kush mountains, Panjshir never fell to the Soviets during the invasion of the 1980s nor to the Taliban during the civil war of the 1990s. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 17 August 2021, Saleh—citing provisions of the Constitution of Afghanistan—declared himself President of Afghanistan from the Panjshir Valley, and vowed to continue military operations against the Taliban from there. [KEEP] His claim to the presidency was endorsed by Ahmad Massoud and Islamic Republic of Afghanistan Minister of Defence Bismillah Khan Mohammadi along with the Embassy of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan in Dushanbe. [KEEP] On 23 August 2021, Massoud made contact with unnamed American lawmakers. [KEEP] <Saleh and Massoud announcements> \c\cPrior to the fall of Kabul, Panjshiris began moving military equipment from surrounding areas, including helicopters and armored vehicles, into Panjshir Province. [KEEP] There, they were joined by Afghan National Army commanders and soldiers, including commandos, ex-Mujahideen who had previously served Ahmad Massoud's late father, Ahmad Shah Massoud, and other anti-Taliban activists. [KEEP] Most of them regrouped at Baghlan Province's Andarab District before moving to Panjshir after making their escape from  Kunduz, Badakhshan, Takhar, and Baghlan. [KEEP] According to a Russian estimate, the disparate Anti-Taliban forces had approximately 7,000 personnel under arms as of mid August 2021. [KEEP] Other estimates place this number as low as 2,000, though Saleh himself claims 10,000 men under arms. [KEEP] By 22 August 2021, Ahmad Massoud claimed to have gathered about 9,000 fighters and at least a "handful of armoured humvees" in the valley. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and anti-Taliban militias> \c\cThere are difference between the forces loyal to Saleh and those loyal to Ahmad Massoud, as the former is hardcore anti-Taliban and anti-Pakistani, whereas the latter maintained good relations with Pakistan which was supportive of the Taliban. [KEEP] As a result, Massoud was more willing to negiotiate with the Taliban. [KEEP] By 22 August 2021, the resistance also confirmed that several local militias had begun to fight the Taliban on their own, independent of the Panjshir-based forces. [KEEP] According to Yasin Zia, the resistance has already secured access to five helicopters formerly used by the Afghan military. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and anti-Taliban militias> \c\cOn 23 [KEEP] August 2021, it was reported that BM-21 Grads were acquired as a part of its arsenal. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and anti-Taliban militias> \c\cAn estimate by the Combating Terrorism Center at the US Military Academy made prior to the Fall of Kabul estimated the strength of the Taliban, throughout the whole of Afghanistan, at 60,000 armed cadre supported by up to 200,000 irregulars. [KEEP] Due to the rapid capitulation of the Afghan National Army, the Taliban have since acquired substantial materiel of US manufacture, including armored vehicles and combat aircraft. [KEEP] <Disposition of forces - Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan> \c\cAround 17 August 2021, remnants of the Afghan National Army began massing in the Panjshir Valley at the urging of Massoud, along with local civilians who had responded to his mobilization calls. [KEEP] At the time, the Panjshir Valley was—according to one observer—"under siege on all sides" but had not come under direct attack. [KEEP] On 18 August 2021, the number of admissions for war injuries was increasing at the Emergency Surgical Centre for War Victims in Anabah in Panjshir. [KEEP] By 22 August, Ahmad Massoud's forces were mostly focused on defending Panjshir as well as training. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 18 August 2021, local reports from Parwan Province reported that Saleh's forces had taken Charikar from Taliban fighters stationed in the area. [KEEP] In addition, there are reports of gunfights taking place near Salang Pass. [KEEP] On the following day, videos were released which showcased local fighters with flags of the old, anti-Taliban Northern Alliance parading through the streets of Charikar. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 20 August 2021, anti-Taliban fighters reportedly recaptured Andarab, Puli Hisar and Dih Salah districts in Baghlan Province with the Taliban claiming 15 of its soldiers had been killed, while other sources reported that up to 60 Taliban fighters were killed or injured, and two dozen captured. [KEEP] The three districts had reportedly experienced a revolt, led by a local police chief, after Taliban had conducted unpopular house-to-house searches. [KEEP] Bismillah Khan Mohammadi announced the operational success of the districts being recaptured via Twitter. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cAudiovisual reports of the events circulated on social media and were reported by Pajhwok Afghan News. [KEEP] Later on the 20th, it was reported that the forces, led by Abdul Hamid Dadgar, had recaptured Andarab, though the Taliban had not yet commented. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cA source within the Panjshir resistance consequently confirmed their involvement in the operations in Baghlan Province, and stated that they planned on seizing a northern highway which could allow them to link up with Tajikistan and Uzbekistan. [KEEP] Taliban social media accounts called the counteroffensive a "betrayal" of the amnesty the Taliban had offered. [KEEP] It was reported on 22 August 2021 that Taliban fighters had been sent to the Keshnabad area of Andarab in order to kidnap the children of anti-Taliban forces. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cAlso, the Islamic Emirate gave the opposition forces a four hour ultimatum to surrender. [KEEP] In a statement to Al Arabiya, Massoud rejected the ultimatum. [KEEP] In response, the IEA announced "hundreds" of its forces had been dispatched to the Panjshir Valley. [KEEP] It was reported on 23 August 2021 that talks between Taliban representatives and Panjshir leaders did not work. [KEEP] Ali Maisam Nazary, spokesman for the resistance, said that the Taliban made demands for Massoud to accept no elections with a centralized government, which Massoud rejected as he wanted a future government to be decentralized, which respect civil and semi-autonomy rights. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cAn unidentified Taliban spokesperson proclaimed in a statement that "hundreds of Mujahideen of the Islamic Emirate are heading towards the state of Panjshir to control it, after local state officials refused to hand it over peacefully". [KEEP] It was reported that on 23 August 2021, Taliban commmander Qari Fashihuddin was tasked to lead offensive operations in Panjshir. [KEEP] The Taliban reported that several of their fighters were shot and killed in ambushes in Jabal Siraj with several of them killed and others wounded. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 23 [KEEP] August 2021, the Taliban claimed to have recaptured all 3 districts in Baghlan that fell to the resistance forces a week ago: Dih Salah District, Pul-e-Hisar and Andarab. [KEEP] A Taliban district chief stationed in Andarab was reported to be killed in the fighting. [KEEP] On 24 August 2021, according to Deccan Herald, Panjshir resistance fighters retook control of Banu and Dih Salah districts, while Puli Hisar remained under Taliban control. [KEEP] Saleh publicly warned via Twitter that Taliban fighters in Andarab were blocking humanitarian assistance for civilians trying to escape from the fighting and called it a "humanitarian disaster". [KEEP] On the following day, Massoud's forces claimed to have ambushed a Taliban convoy in Andarab, destroying a critical bridge and inflicting heavy losses on the Islamists. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 24 August 2021, Major Wazir Akbar, an ex-Afghan commando who has joined the Panjshir-based resistance fighters, reported an attempted Taliban incursion at Anjuman Pass through Badakhshan province, which was repelled with heavy Taliban casualties. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 26 August, 2021, a ceasefire was declared with the Taliban and the resistance entering into talks. [KEEP] Taliban spokesman Zabihullah Mujahid said that he was "80 percent confident of a solution without war in the Panjshir Valley". [KEEP] On 29 August 2021, Panjshir representatives stated that there were no Taliban fighters trying to enter Panjshir, refuting information from Anaamullah Samangani, who is a member of the Taliban's Cultural Commission. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 26 August, 2021, according to a video published by Global Defense Corp, heavy fighting broke out between anti-Taliban resistance group in Panjshir Valley and Taliban. [KEEP] More than 200 Taliban fighters were driven out the Panjshir Valley and some were captured by anti-Taliban resistance group. [KEEP] The National Resistance Front (NRF) has also captured Pol-e-Hesar, Deh Salah and Banu districts. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn 28 August 2021, Panjshir fighters have engaged Taliban fighters in Sanjan, Kapisa and in 