Kabul International Airport. [KEEP] <Operational history> \c\cOn [KEEP] 15 August, following the fall of Kabul—in which Afghan security forces fled the capital and thousands of Afghan civilians fled to the airport in hopes of boarding flights, resulting in chaotic scenes of Afghans attempting to force themselves aboard military planes—the Pentagon and the State Department announced the expansion of the military presence at the airport to nearly 6,000 troops. [KEEP] U.S. military took control over the security and air traffic control of the airport later in the day. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn 16 August, a C-17 cargo plane, which usually includes less than Army 150 paratroopers, safely evacuated roughly 640 people to the Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar. [KEEP] The US Air Force later stated they undercounted the passengers due to not counting children sitting in their parents\' laps on the buses and actually airlifted 823 Afghan civilians, setting a new record for the C-17. [KEEP] The Pentagon confirmed the head of U.S. Central Command, General Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr., met Taliban leaders based in Qatar's capital Doha. [KEEP] The Taliban officials agreed to terms set by McKenzie for refugees to flee using Kabul Airport. [KEEP] U.S. Army Maj. General William Taylor said that nine C-17s arrived overnight, bringing equipment and 1,000 more troops. [KEEP] Separately, seven C-17s airlifted 700-800 passengers out of the airport, 165 of which were American citizens while the rest were SIV applicants and third country nationals. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn 17 August, about 1,100 people were evacuated on 13 flights. [KEEP] The White House said more than 3,200 U.S. citizens, permanent residents and refugees were evacuated from the country, and nearly 2,000 Afghan interpreters were flown to the U.S. for SIV processing. [KEEP] On August 18, Deputy Secretary of State Wendy Sherman said U.S. military flights evacuated about 2,000 people, and said it has processed more than 4,840 people for evacuation. [KEEP] The State Department said the U.S. military has evacuated nearly 5,000 people from the country. [KEEP] On August 19, more than 2,000 people were evacuated on 12 flights. [KEEP] The Pentagon said it has evacuated about 7,000 people from the country. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn 20 August, about 5,700 people were evacuated on 16 flights. [KEEP] The Pentagon said it has evacuated about 12,700 people from the country. [KEEP] On 21 August, United States Army Major General William D. Taylor announced that 17,000 people have been evacuated in the past few weeks, including 2,500 Americans. [KEEP] The Taliban has at times blocked evacuation efforts made by the United Kingdom <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] 22 August, President Joe Biden said that American troops may remain in Afghanistan past the August 31 deadline. [KEEP] He also announced that 28,000 people have been evacuated since 15 August, and that 33,000 people have been evacuated since July. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cAlso on 22 August, the Department of Defense ordered the activation of the Civil Reserve Air Fleet to assist in the evacuation. [KEEP] The current activation is for 18 planes: four from United Airlines; three each from American Airlines, Atlas Air, Delta Air Lines and Omni Air; and two from Hawaiian Airlines. [KEEP] Commercial airline pilots and crews would help transport thousands of Afghans who are arriving at U.S. bases in Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates. [KEEP] From the bases in the Middle East, the airliners would augment military flights carrying Afghans to Germany, Italy, Spain and other stops in Europe, and then ultimately to the United States. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn 23 August, United States Army Major General William D. Taylor announced that Joint Base McGuire-Dix-Lakehurst in New Jersey, was ready to receive Afghan evacuees in addition to Fort McCoy, Wisconsin; Fort Bliss, Texas; and Fort Lee, Virginia. [KEEP] Pentagon Press Secretary John F. Kirby said the goal was to be able to receive about 25,000 evacuees in coming weeks. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn 25 August, Blackwater founder Erik Prince says that he is offering to charge $6,500 for anyone who wanted to evacuate from Kabul. [KEEP] That same day, the total amount of evacuations topped 82,300. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cAlthough the Taliban's conquest of the country led to the disintegration of the Afghan Armed Forces, an armed remnant of mostly 500 to 600 Afghan Commandos were at the airport helping U.S. troops provide perimeter security. [KEEP] The Pentagon said these Afghan troops would be evacuated if they desired. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn 27 August, the Department of Defense announced that three more U.S. military bases will be used to house up to 50,000 Afghan nationals who are applying for SIVs or are deemed "at risk" from the Taliban: Fort Pickett, Holloman Air Force Base and Marine Corps Base Quantico. [KEEP] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [KEEP] 5 September, White House Chief of Staff Ron Klain said that around 100 Americans remain in Afghanistan. [KEEP] Klain said that the Biden administration will look for ways to rescue them. [ADD] <Operational history - Kabul airlift> \c\cOn [ADD] 10 September, U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken announced in a statement that 21 Americans and 11 legal citizens have evacuated from the country. [KEEP] <Casualties> \c\cSix people were killed after trying to escape as stowaways: two people were seen falling to their deaths from the sky after clinging to the landing gear of a departing C-17 cargo plane, while three people clinging to the side of an Air Force jet were killed after being run over. [KEEP] Remains of another dead Afghan were found in the landing gear of the American C-17, after the pilots were forced to make an emergency landing in a nearby country because they were unable to retract the landing gear. [KEEP] Eleven more civilians died during stampedes at the airport, seven of whom died in a single incident on August 21. [KEEP] At times, the Taliban has fired crowd control shots at the Kabul airport, with some people reported shot and injured from gunfire. [KEEP] Three more people died during gun incidents, including two armed men who fired into a crowd and were killed by U.S. troops, while the other was an Afghan guard killed during a gunfight between Afghan forces and unknown gunmen. [KEEP] <Casualties> \c\cAt least 182 people were killed and more than 200 others were wounded during a suicide bombing attack at the airport on August 26, when evacuations of locals and foreigners were under way. [KEEP] The attack was carried out by Islamic State militants. [KEEP] At least 169 Afghan civilians and 13 US service members were among the killed. [KEEP] The dead Americans were identified as eleven marines, one soldier, and one Navy corpsman. [KEEP] Several more foreign troops and Taliban members were among the injured. [KEEP] Three of the dead Afghan civilians were also British citizens. [KEEP] <Casualties> \c\cOn 2 September, a nine-month old baby died after arriving at the Philadelphia International Airport in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, making her the first death of a evacuee on American soil. [KEEP] <Casualties> \c\c
[KEEP] Since January 2001, multiple drone strikes have been conducted by the United States government in Afghanistan. [KEEP] These strikes began during the administration of the United States President George W. Bush. [KEEP] During the presidency of Donald Trump, it was estimated that drone strikes had multiplied at a pace of four to five times compared with previous presidency of Barack Obama. [KEEP] In 2016, Obama ordered the CIA to report civilian drone strike deaths, an order which was revoked by Trump. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cBy 2021, there had been a total of at least 13,074 airstrikes conducted by the US government, killing at least 4,138 people, including 310 civilians and 73 children. [KEEP] Besides the US government, the Afghan Air Force (AAF) also carried out air strikes in Afghanistan. [KEEP] Since 1 June 2016, the AAF has conducted at least 41 strike capable operations. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c1 January 2015: [KEEP] One unknown killed in a US drone strike Spera District Khost Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c [KEEP] 3 January 2015: [KEEP] Twenty-five were killed in two separate drone strikes, one at Gayan District Paktika province killing eighteen and the other at Spera District Khost Province killing seven. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c [KEEP] 7 January 2015: Three reported killed in the eastern part of Logar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c [KEEP] 8 January 2015: Six reported killed and three injured in a US air strike at Chikanawr area, Lal Pura District, Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c11 January 2015: Eight killed and three injured at Chikanawr area, Lal Pura District, Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c16 January 2015: [KEEP] Three killed at Nazyan District, Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c17 January 2015: One unknown killed or injured at Lal Pura District, Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c [KEEP] 19 January 2015: [KEEP] One unknown killed or injured at Khogyani District, Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c29 January 2015: [KEEP] Four killed at Nazyan District, Nangarhar Province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015> \c\c2 January 2016: [KEEP] Five former Pakistani Taliban (TTP) fighters who pledged alliance to ISIL, including the former TTP commander in Bajaur tribal agency in Pakistan, Abu Bakr, were killed by a US drone strike, further injuring two militants in the Shaltan Darra area, located in the Shegal district, located in the Kunar province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 5 January 2016: [KEEP] A US Special Forces soldier, Army Staff Sgt. [KEEP] Matthew McClintock, was killed during an hours-long gun battle by Taliban militants, also injuring two other soldiers, in the Marjah district, located in the Helmand province, marking him the first US casualty of 2016. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 6 January 2016: [KEEP] Twelve US air or drone strikes killed an unknown number of people in the Majah district, located in the Helmand province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 8 January 2016: [KEEP] AAF strikes hit and killed 23 ISIL militants in the Achin and Kot districts, located in the Nangarhar province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 8 January 2016: [KEEP] A US air or drone strike killed 17–20 ISIL militants, including four senior commanders, who were executing seven men (six Taliban militants and one Afghan National Army soldier) at the time, with a large number of civilians forced to watch in the Maktab village, located in the Pekha area, located in Achin District, located in the Nangarhar province. [KEEP] Two civilians were injured and there were possible civilian deaths. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 8 January 2016: [KEEP] A US air or drone strike killed an unknown number of people "to eliminate threats to the force" in the Kharkhez district, located in the Kandahar province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 8 January 2016: [KEEP] A US air or drone strike killed an unknown number of people "to eliminate threats to the force" in the Bermal district, located in the Paktika province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 9 January 2016: 20 ISIL militants were killed by a US drone strike in Achin District, located in the Nangarhar province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 9 January 2016: 15 ISIL militants were killed by a US air or drone strike in the Janjal Gondai area, located in the Kot district, located in the  Nangarhar province, further injuring three people, including a woman. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c [KEEP] 9 January 2016: [KEEP] Ten militants from Pakistan were killed by a US air or drone strike in the Shegal district, located in the Kunar province. [KEEP] The victims included Zishan, Haqyar and Sajid Mohammed (aka Attique or Atiqullah), aged 13 to 14, who was the son of Maulvi Faqir Mohammad a former deputy leader of the TTP, who served under the command of Baitullah and Hakimullah Mehsud. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2016> \c\c1 January 2018: [KEEP] At least 61 ISIL militants were killed, including one civilian, in the Nangarhar province by a possible US strike. [KEEP] A further 30 ISIL militants were injured, including 14 civilians. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c1 January 2018: Twenty-six people, including foreigners and prominent ISIL commanders, were killed by a possible US strike in the village of Saradara and Alkhani in the Darzab district. [KEEP] Some victims included famous militant commander Qari Zia aka Shuja, and two other prominent militants, Yaqub and Shaikh, a judge. [KEEP] There were also possible civilian casualties. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c1 January 2018: [KEEP] A possible US strike killed seven Taliban fighters in the Bati Kot district. [KEEP] A second strike killed two members of ISIL's Afghan branch in Achin District. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c [KEEP] 5 January 2018: [KEEP] A possible US strike killed 10 ISIL militants in a training camp in Nangarhar's Haska Mena district while they were in training. [KEEP] Two compounds belonging to ISIL were also destroyed, leaving five militants dead. [KEEP] Another strike killed six militants during ground operations. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c [KEEP] 5 January 2018: [KEEP] A possible US strike killed 14 ISIL militants, including two commanders, in the Nad-e Ali district in the Laghman province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c [KEEP] 6 January 2018: [KEEP] An unnamed key Taliban leader responsible for "financial deals and providing logistics" for militants was killed in the  Helmand province by a possible US strike. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c10 January 2018: Twenty-one militants, including seven foreigners from Pakistan, were killed by a possible US strike in the Khak e Safid district, located in the Farah province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c1 April 2018: Mullah Lal Mohammad, a local Taliban leader in the Kandarhar province, was killed by a AAF strike in the Nish district, injuring 11 other members of his group Also the same day, a US strike killed an unknown number of Taliban fighters in the Nad Ali district <Timeline - [KEEP] 2018> \c\c2 April 2018: Afghan military strike kills at least 70, including 21 terrorists, one of whom was a Taliban commander, and injured 30 others during a religious ceremony at a Mosque in Dasht-e-Archi. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c3 April 2018: [KEEP] US drone strike killed four ISIL militants in Nangarhar. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c5 April 2018: A high-ranking ISIL commander named Qari Hikmatullah (also Hekmat) and his bodyguard were killed in a US drone strike in the northern province of Jowzjan <Timeline - 2018> \c\c [KEEP] 6 April 2018: An AAF strike killed eight militants in Farghamerawi locality of Wardoj district. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\c18 September 2019: A US drone strike intended to hit an Islamic State hideout killed 30 pine-nut farmers in the Nangarhar province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\c1 December 2019: A US drone strike on a car carrying a woman who had just given birth near Khost left five