[KEEP] Sir David Amess, the British Conservative Party Member of Parliament for Southend West, was stabbed to death on 15 October 2021. [KEEP] The attack occurred at a constituency meeting in Leigh-on-Sea. [KEEP] A 25-year-old man was arrested. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cSir David Amess was a long-serving politician who entered Parliament in 1983 as the MP for Basildon. [KEEP] He held no senior positions but was an "instantly recognizable" member of the Conservative Party and had been knighted for his commitment to public service. [KEEP] He is said to have been socially conservative and held relatively centrist views, notably opposing abortion and campaigning in favour of Brexit; for stronger animal welfare protections; and to award Southend-on-Sea city status. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cFollowing the murder of Jo Cox whilst on her way to meet constituents at a constituency surgery in 2016, Amess said in his 2020 autobiography that fears of similar attacks "rather spoilt the great British tradition of the people openly meeting their elected politicians" and that he had faced harassment and insecurity at his home. [KEEP] MPs are protected by armed police when inside Parliament, with security being tightened after the 2017 Westminster attack. [KEEP] However, they are generally not given police protection during surgeries and they are normally accompanied by one member of staff only. [KEEP] After Cox's murder, parliamentary spending on MPs\' personal security rose from under £200,000 to £4.5 million in two years. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 15 October 2021, Amess was at a constituency surgery at Belfairs Methodist Church on Eastwood Road North, Leigh-on-Sea, where he was scheduled to meet with constituents from 10:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. BST. [KEEP] He first met with constituents on the steps of the Church, and entered the building at around 12:05 p.m., to speak with people who had arrived earlier. [KEEP] Inside the Church, his attacker emerged from the group of people waiting to speak with Amess, and stabbed him multiple times. [KEEP] Police were alerted to the attack shortly after it occurred, and armed police, as well as medical and police helicopters, attended. [KEEP] The suspect was arrested inside the Church before being taken away; once the suspect was removed from the scene, a police cordon was set up. [KEEP] An air ambulance landed on a nearby playing field at 2:13 p.m. to take Amess to hospital; the medical team already in attendance decided that his condition was not stable enough to transport Amess and continued to work at the scene instead. [KEEP] He died just before 3:00 p.m., at the age of 69. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\c [KEEP] The motivations of the attacker are unknown. [KEEP] Counter-terrorist police officers are involved in the early stages of the investigation. [KEEP] Essex Police said a "25-year-old man was quickly arrested after officers arrived at the scene on suspicion of murder and a knife was recovered". [KEEP] At around 6:32 p.m. on 15 October, Essex Police announced that the investigation had been handed over to counter-terrorist officers. [KEEP] Later in the day, the BBC reported that a government source said the suspect is a British national who may have Somali heritage. [ADD] <Investigation> \c\cAt about 00:30 a.m. on 16 October, the police declared the stabbing a terrorist incident. [KEEP] Various parliamentary groups and current and former politicians from across the political spectrum expressed shock and offered condolences, as did relatives of Jo Cox. [KEEP] A vigil for Amess was held in his Southend West constituency at 6:00 p.m. on the day he died. [KEEP] The Speaker of the House of Commons, Sir Lindsay Hoyle, announced that the security of MPs will be reviewed. [KEEP] Conservative MP and Chairman Oliver Dowden announced that, in light of Amess's death, campaigning activities on behalf of the Conservative Party would be suspended nationwide until further notice. [KEEP] Stéphane Dujarric,  spokesperson for United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres, said that politicians should be able to undertake their duties without fear of attack. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\cBBC One changed its evening schedule out of respect, replacing topical news satire show Have I Got News for You with a rerun of panel show Would I Lie to You?; crime scene comedy The Cleaner with a rerun of sitcom Miranda; and slasher film Halloween with romance  The Light Between Oceans. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\c
[KEEP] A series of protests by the Kosovo Serbs against the Kosovan government began on 20 September 2021, triggered by the government's decision to ban Serbian license plates, and ended on 2 October 2021. [KEEP] The protests had mostly consisted of blocking traffic near border crossings. [KEEP] The ban meant that people who owned vehicles with Serbian license plates in Kosovo would have had to switch for Kosovar license plates at a government vehicle registration center. [KEEP] The ban intended to mirror the former ban on Kosovar license plates in Serbia. [KEEP] The Republic of Serbia does not recognise the Republic of Kosovo and considers the Kosovo–Serbia border only temporary. [KEEP] The protests have led the relations between Serbia and Kosovo, which had been improving, to worsen. [KEEP] The Serbian Armed Forces are on heightened combat readiness as a result. [KEEP] Both sides have accused each other of great overreach. [KEEP] International powers have called for de–escalation, with Russia criticising Kosovo. [KEEP] On 30 September 2021, an agreement was reached to end the ban starting 4 October 2021, according to which the protests also ended on 2 October 2021. [KEEP] Kosovar license plates in Serbia and Serbian license plates in Kosovo now have their national symbols and country codes covered with a sticker. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cNorth Kosovo is majority Serb and has been a region largely opposed to an independent Kosovo, with frequent protests since Kosovo declared independence. [KEEP] It has not recognised the Government of Kosovo and has acted independently of it until the 2013 Brussels Agreement. [KEEP] According to the Brussels Agreement, by 2016 the Community of Serb Municipalities was to be formed. [KEEP] The Community would be a self–governing association of municipalities with a Serbian majority in Kosovo. [KEEP] As of 2021, it has not yet formed, because of the Government of Kosovo freezing the Brussels Agreement and its Constitutional Court declaring some parts of the agreement to be unconstitutional. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cUp until 2011, Serbia issued Serbian license plates for towns in North Kosovo. [KEEP] In 2011, Serbia agreed to stop issuing these license plates and that they should be changed for Republic of Kosovo (RKS) or the neutral Kosovo (KS) license plates. [KEEP] The KS license plates do not bear any state symbols. [KEEP] Serbia has allowed the KS license plates on its territory, but not the RKS license plates. [KEEP] The agreement lasted 5 years until 2016, when it was expected a better solution would be found. [KEEP] The same terms were renewed on 14 September 2016 and were valid until 14 September 2021. [KEEP] After 14 September 2021 the conditions remained the same, but a ban on Serbian license plates was issued in Kosovo on 20 September 2021. [KEEP] The KS license plates were also declared invalid by the Government of Kosovo which were used by some vehicles in Kosovo, including by owners who often had to travel across the Kosovo–Serbia border. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe motive of the Kosovan government in the ban had been to mirror the former, similar policy of the Serbian Government by which Republic of Kosovo(RKS) license plates had been banned since Kosovo declared independence, and vehicles with RKS license plates in Serbia had to switch them for temporary Serbian plates. [KEEP] Vehicles with Serbian license plates in Kosovo were supposed to, up to the 30 September 2021 Agreement in Brussels, have their Serbian license plates taken off and switched for Kosovar license plates at a government vehicle registration center. [KEEP] Drivers who had visited the country with Serbian license plates had to get temporary plates. [KEEP] The temporary plates costed a 5 euro (2021 value) tax and were valid for 60 days. [KEEP] The ban would have reportedly impacted around 9,500 vehicles with Serbian license plates in North Kosovo which were to have to wear permanent Kosovar license plates. [KEEP] This was originally supposed to be done after the 2011 agreement, but no attempts were made to enforce it. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe protests organised by the Kosovo Serbs against the Kosovan government began on 20 September 2021. [KEEP] On the same day, over 20 vehicles of the Kosovo Police, of which over 10 were armoured, came to the site of the protests. [KEEP] Hundreds of local ethnic Serbs had been protesting daily. [KEEP] They were blocking the roads leading to the two border crossings with Serbia in North Kosovo, near Jarinje and Brnjak, with vehicles and barricades reinforced by gravel. [KEEP] On 23 September 2021 the traffic block consisting of vehicles became 3 kilometres long on the Mitrovica–Raška road in Jarinje. [KEEP] Protesters were sleeping next to the protest sites in improvised tents. [KEEP] Representatives of the Serb List also attended the protests. [KEEP] <Protests> \c\c [KEEP] The protests had been mostly calm. [KEEP] However, on 25 September 2021, two government vehicle registration centers in Zvečan and Zubin Potok were attacked by arson, and allegedly with hand grenades that failed to explode. [KEEP] On 23 September 2021, the Kosovo Police was accused of injuring three people unrelated to the protests, two seriously, who are now in hospital. [KEEP] Kosovo has denied involvement and says that it's "disinformation". [KEEP] <Protests> \c\cAccording to the agreement between Kosovo and Serbia mediated by the European Union (EU) Representative for the Balkan–Pristina Dialogue Miroslav Lajčák in Brussels, reached on 30 September 2021, the Kosovar special police withdrew by 16:00 local time on 2 October 2021. [KEEP] Along with this, the barricades set up by the protesters were removed by local Serbs and the traffic blocks ended, leading to border traffic resuming. [KEEP] KFOR troops replaced the police units and will be present for the next two weeks. [KEEP] <Government responses - Serbia> \c\c [KEEP] The decision to ban Serbian license plates and the ongoing protests prompted Serbian authorities to raise the combat readiness of the Serbian Armed Forces on the border with Kosovo. [KEEP] The army started transporting military equipment to the border area, including its fighter jets and helicopters, and tanks, on 26 September 2021. [KEEP] The President of Serbia Aleksandar Vučić has described Kosovo's license plate ban as a "criminal action". [KEEP] He made the withdrawal of Kosovar special police ROSU a condition for starting EU-mediated negotiations to resolve the dispute. [KEEP] <Government responses - Kosovo> \c\c [KEEP] The Prime Minister of Kosovo Albin Kurti has accused Serbia of "inciting and supporting" the attacks on government buildings. [KEEP] He also accused Serbia of "exploiting Kosovo citizens to provoke a serious international conflict." [KEEP] The attacks were described by the Interior Ministry of Kosovo as "having terrorist elements". [KEEP] The mayors of majority Serbian municipalities on 27 September also requested a withdrawal of the units and more KFOR prsence, citing the incident on 23 September 2021 when 3 Serbs were injured as a concern. [KEEP] The special police units withdrew as part of the 30 September 2021 Agreement in Brussels on 2 October 2021. [KEEP] <Agreement to end the ban> \c\cOn 30 September 2021, an agreement was reached in Brussels that effectively ended the ban on Serbian license plates, starting 08:00 local time, 4 October 2021. [KEEP] The agreement also effectively ended the ban on Kosovar license plates in Serbia. [KEEP] The agreement is intended as a temporary solution. [KEEP] The solution is to cover the national symbols of Kosovo on Kosovar RKS license plates in Serbia, as well as to cover the national symbols of Serbia on Serbian license plates in Kosovo and [KEEP] their country codes RKS and SRB with a sticker. [ADD] Miroslav Lajčák said that "he trusts they will present concrete findings in 6 months", when negotiators and delegations will present their proposals for the permanent solution. [KEEP] Rudnica is a few kilometres away from the Kosovo–Serbia border. [KEEP] Russia will deploy air defense forces to Serbia for joint military exercises which will be held in October. [KEEP] On 27 September 2021, the NATO-led international peacekeeping force in Kosovo, the Kosovo Force, stepped up the amount and duration of its patrols. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\c
[KEEP] On 15 October 2021, Sir David Amess, a British Conservative Party politician and Member of Parliament (MP) for Southend West, died after being stabbed multiple times during a political surgery at the Belfairs Methodist Church Hall in Leigh-on-Sea, Essex. [KEEP] Ali Harbi Ali, a 25-year-old male British citizen, was arrested at the scene and was later charged with murder and the preparation of terrorist acts. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAmess was a long-serving politician who entered Parliament in 1983 as MP for Basildon. [KEEP] He had held no senior positions but was described by Nick Paton Walsh as an "instantly recognisable" member of the Conservative Party and had been knighted for his political and public service. [KEEP] He was a devout Catholic and a socially conservative politician who opposed abortion, supported capital punishment, and campaigned in favour of Brexit. [KEEP] He was a supporter of animal welfare and was one of the few Conservative MPs to support a ban on fox hunting. [KEEP] He also supported a campaign to award city status to Southend-on-Sea, Essex. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cFollowing the murder of MP Jo Cox on her way to a constituency surgery in 2016, Amess wrote in his 2020 autobiography that fears of similar attacks "rather spoilt the great British tradition of the people openly meeting their elected politicians" and that he had faced harassment and insecurity at his home. [KEEP] MPs are protected by armed police when inside Parliament, with security tightened after the 2017 Westminster attack. [KEEP] They are generally not given police protection during surgeries, and they are normally accompanied by one member of staff only. [KEEP] After Cox's murder, parliamentary spending on MPs\' personal security rose from under £200,000 to £4.5 million in two years. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 15 October 2021, Amess was at a one-to-one constituency meeting at the Belfairs Methodist Church Hall on Eastwood Road North in Leigh-on-Sea, Essex, where he was scheduled to meet with constituents from 10 am to 1 pm. [KEEP] He first met with constituents on the steps of the church and entered the hall at around 12:05 pm to speak with people who had arrived earlier. [KEEP] While inside the church hall, a man armed with a knife emerged from the group of constituents and stabbed him multiple times. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\cArmed units and medical and police helicopters arrived at the scene within minutes. [KEEP] The suspect waited inside the church hall, where he was arrested and a police cordon was set up. [KEEP] An air ambulance landed on Belfairs Sports Ground at 2:13 pm to take Amess to hospital, but the medical team decided that his condition was not stable enough to transport him and so continued to work on him at the scene. [KEEP] He was declared dead just before 3 pm. [KEEP] <Attack> \c\cCounter-terrorist police officers were involved in the early stages of the investigation. [KEEP] Essex Police said that a "25-year-old man was quickly arrested after officers arrived at the scene on suspicion of murder and a knife was recovered". [KEEP] At approximately 6:32 pm on 15 October 2021, Essex Police announced that the investigation had been handed over to the Counter Terrorism Command of London's Metropolitan Police Service. [KEEP] <Investigation> \c\cOn the evening of 16 October, the Metropolitan Police Service confirmed the suspect had been detained under Section 41 of the Terrorism Act 2000, and that magistrates had extended the period the suspect could be held in custody for questioning until 22 October 2021. [KEEP] Just after midnight, police identified the stabbing as a terrorist incident potentially motivated by Islamic extremism. [KEEP] Police searched three addresses in London over the weekend following the stabbing. [RM] <Investigation> \c\cOn 21 October 2021, Ali Harbi Ali, a British-born national of Somali heritage was charged with the murder of Amess and the preparation of terrorist acts. [KEEP] In 2014, as a teenager, Ali was referred to the Prevent programme, Britain's voluntary programme for those thought at risk of radicalisation, from which he was referred on to the Channel Programme. [KEEP] He is believed to not have spent long in the programme, and he was not a "subject of interest" to MI5. [ADD] North London. [ADD] He lived in Kentish Town. <Investigation - Accused> \c\cOn [ADD] 21 October 2021, Ali Harbi Ali, a British-born national of Somali heritage was charged with the murder of Amess and the preparation of terrorist acts. [ADD] On 22 October, he appeared at the Old Bailey via video link from Belmarsh, during which he was remanded in custody. [KEEP] The safety of MPs during open, public constituency surgeries was debated by politicians. [KEEP] Calls to enact a law to crack down on online targeting of MPs and end anonymity were made. [KEEP] The Conservatives suspended political campaigning. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\cA Catholic priest reported he was not allowed to enter the crime scene to administer the last rites for Amess. [KEEP] Following Amess's killing, British Catholic policymakers issued statements affirming Amess's commitment to his faith and lauding his achievements. [KEEP] Labour MP Mike Kane also sought to add an "Amess amendment" to the Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Bill that would ensure Catholic priests access to crime scenes in order to administer the last rites. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\cOn 16 October, Boris Johnson and the Leader of the Opposition Sir Keir Starmer, accompanied by Sir Lindsay Hoyle and the home secretary Priti Patel, laid wreaths at the church hall where Amess was killed. [KEEP] On 18 October, a minute's silence was held in the House of Commons before MPs paid tribute to Amess. [KEEP] That evening, a service of remembrance for Amess was held by MPs at St Margaret's Church, Westminster. [KEEP] The service, which included an address by the Archbishop of Canterbury, Justin Welby, was streamed live by the ITV News YouTube channel. [KEEP] MPs paid tribute in a book of condolence that was placed in the House of Commons Library, as well as in Westminster Hall and Portcullis House. [KEEP] Tributes were also laid at Belfairs Methodist Church Hall, where Amess was killed. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\cIn the days following Amess's death, a number of MPs, including Conservative Chris Skidmore and Labour's Charlotte Nichols, voiced their support for a campaign to give Southend-on-Sea city status as a way of honouring Amess's memory; he had frequently spoken on the topic in Parliament. [KEEP] During tributes to Amess on 18 October, the Prime Minister announced that the Queen had agreed to Southend being given city status. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\cAs a result of Amess's death, a by-election was triggered to fill his former seat. [KEEP] Major and minor parties announced they would not stand a candidate to oppose the Conservatives, as a sign of respect, following the precedent set in the 2016 Batley and Spen by-election. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\c
[KEEP] Solar cycle 25 is the current solar cycle pattern of sunspot activity. [KEEP] It began in December 2019, with a smoothed minimum sunspot number of 1.8. [KEEP] It is expected to continue until about 2030. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cWidely varying predictions regarding the strength of cycle 25 ranged from very weak with suggestions of slow slide in to a Maunder minimum like state to a weak cycle similar to previous cycle 24 and even a strong cycle. [KEEP] Upton and Hathaway have predicted that the weakness of cycle 25 would make it part of the Modern Gleissberg Minimum. [KEEP] One published prediction (of a very weak cycle) was retracted due to fundamental errors. [KEEP] <Predictions> \c\c [KEEP] The Solar Cycle 25 Prediction Panel predicted in December 2019 that solar cycle 25 will be similar to solar cycle 24, with the preceding solar cycle minimum in April 2020 (± 6 months), and the number of sunspots reaching a (smoothed) maximum of 115 in July 2025 (± 8 months). [KEEP] This prediction is in line with the current general agreement in the scientific literature, which holds that solar cycle 25 will be weaker than average (i.e. weaker than during the exceptionally strong Modern Maximum). [KEEP] <Predictions> \c\cAs of April 2018, the Sun showed signs of a reverse magnetic polarity sunspot appearing and beginning this solar cycle. [KEEP] It is typical during the transition from one cycle to the next to experience a period where sunspots of both polarities exist (during the solar minimum). [KEEP] The polarward reversed polarity sunspots suggest that a transition to cycle 25 is in process. [KEEP] The first Cycle 25 sunspot may have appeared in early April 2018 or even December 2016. [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\cIn November 2019, two reversed polarity sunspots appeared, possibly signaling the onset of cycle 25. [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\cNandy et al., analyzed the polarity orientation of bipolar magnetic regions observed in December 2019 and concluded that magnetic regions with the underlying orientation of solar cycle 25 toroidal field component were brewing in the solar convection zone, representing early signs of the new cycle. [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\cSupersynoptic (time vs. solar latitude) map of the radial component of the solar magnetic field for Cycles 24-25 based on observations from the Global Oscillations Network Group (GONG) shows magnetic activity of cycle 25 beginning November 2019 at about 30 degree latitudes in both solar hemispheres. [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\cA more recent supersynoptic map is available. [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\cSpotless days by year (Solar cycle 25 vs 24) <Early signs> \c\c [KEEP] 2021 : 43 (18%)  ... (to August 28) <Early signs> \c\c [KEEP] 2020 : 192 (52%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c [KEEP] 2019 : 274 (75%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2018 : 208 (57%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c [KEEP] 2017 : 96 (26%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2016 : 27 (7%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2015 : 0 (0%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2014 : 1 (0%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2013 : 0 (0%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2012 : 0 (0%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2011 : 2 (1%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2010 : 44 (12%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2009 : 262 (72%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2008 : 265 (72%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2007 : 163 (45%) [KEEP] <Early signs> \c\c2006 : 65 (18%) <Events - 2020> \c\cOn 29 May, the first C-class solar flares of Solar Cycle 25 took place, as well as the first M-class flare. [KEEP] Solar activity continued to increase in the following months, especially abruptly in October, with flares taking place on a near-daily basis by November. [KEEP] On November 29, an M4.4 flare, the strongest of the cycle to date, took place, possibly indicating the solar cycle would be more active than initially thought. [KEEP] <Events - 2020> \c\cOn 8 December, a small coronal mass ejection was found heading directly towards Earth shortly after a strong C-class solar flare, hitting the planet on 9/10 December and causing bright aurorae at high l