[KEEP] On 1 November 2021, a high-rise block of flats in Ikoyi, Lagos, Nigeria, collapsed. [KEEP] It was in the process of being built much higher than authorised. [KEEP] A rescue effort is ongoing and the state government is conducting an investigation. [KEEP] Fourscore Homes, a United Kingdom-based private development company commissioned the construction of a trio of highrise buildings at 44BCD Gerrard Road, in the Ikoyi neighborhood of Lagos, Nigeria, called the "360 Degrees Towers". [KEEP] The company is headed by Nigerian Femi Osibona (aka Olufemi Adegoke Osibona). [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOne of the buildings undergoing construction was a 21 story luxury residential high-rise. [KEEP] In February 2020, consultancy firm Prowess Engineering Limited withdrew from the project over concerns regarding the integrity of the building. [KEEP] The Lagos State Building Control Agency had approved only 15 floors, but 21 had been been built. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 1 November 2021, at 2:45 p.m. [KEEP] UTC+01:00, one of the three "360 Degrees Towers", the 21-story building, collapsed. [KEEP] Fifteen people have been confirmed dead, and an uncertain number of people are believed to be trapped in the rubble; an official estimate is that up to 40 workers were on site at the time. [KEEP] <Collapse> \c\cOsibona was inside the building during the collapse and is reportedly missing. [KEEP] <Collapse> \c\cA rescue effort is being conducted by the National Emergency Management Agency in Lagos State (NEMA), and other responders. [KEEP] It is being supervised by the Commissioner for Special Duties and Intergovernmental Relations, and the Lagos State Ministry of Physical Planning and Urban Development. [KEEP] According NEMA, the military is scheduled to "take over operations". [KEEP] <Rescue operations> \c\cAs of 2 November, nine people have been rescued. [KEEP] <Rescue operations> \c\cFemi Hamzat, deputy governor of Lagos, was jeered by crowds who said authorities had been too slow to initiate rescue attempts. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\cGbolahan Oki, the general manager  of the Lagos State Building Control Agency, announced that the owner of the building has been arrested and would be prosecuted. [KEEP] The state government suspended the chief architect, and is conducting an investigation. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\c
