[KEEP] On 5 November 2021 a collision between a petrol fuel tanker and a lorry at a busy junction of Sierra Leone's capital and largest city Freetown resulted in an explosion and a fire that killed at least 101 people, and injured more than 100, overwhelming the city's medical services. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cFreetown is the capital and largest city of Sierra Leone, with a population of more than 1.2 million people. [KEEP] The accident happened at a busy intersection in the Wellington area, Freetown's main industrial district. [KEEP] The intersection where the accident happened is popularly known as "PMB", short for Sierra Leone Produce Marketing Board (SLPMB), a defunct parastatal with its old factory buildings located adjacent the intersection. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cAt approximately 22:00 GMT on 5 November 2021, a fuel tanker carrying petrol attempted to make a turn outside Choithram Supermarket in the Freetown suburb of Wellington. [KEEP] A lorry reported to be carrying granite collided with the tanker at the junction creating a fuel leakage. [KEEP] The two drivers came out of their vehicles and warned community residents to stay off the scene, according to Sierra Leone's National Disaster Management Agency. [KEEP] <Event> \c\cPetrol spilled from the tanker and locals, particularly the "Okada" (motorbike) taxi-riders, attempted to collect this in containers. [KEEP] An explosion led to a huge fireball that engulfed vehicles, people and passengers that were stuck in traffic created by the initial collision. [KEEP] <Event> [KEEP] <Event> \c\cMany of the victims were trapped in vehicles, including a bus full of people which was intensely burnt, killing all inside. [KEEP] Nearby shops and markets caught fire after fuel spilled onto the streets. [KEEP] Footage broadcast by local media outlets showed charred bodies surrounding the tanker. [KEEP] At least 99 people were confirmed to have died in the disaster, and more than 100 others were injured. [KEEP] The death toll rose to 101 three days after the explosion. [KEEP] <Event> \c\cMohamed Lamrane Bah, the director of the National Disaster Management Agency (NDMA), stated that the injured had been transferred to hospitals and the bodies were collected. [KEEP] He added that rescue efforts at the scene had ended by 16:45 GMT 6 November. [KEEP] Several people are in critical condition. [KEEP] According to a staff member of Connaught Hospital's intensive care unit, about 30 severely burned victims are not expected to survive. [KEEP] President Julius Maada Bio, who was attending the United Nations climate talks, offered condolences and promised support to the victims\' families. [KEEP] Vice President Mohamed Juldeh Jalloh visited two hospitals. [KEEP] The journalist Omar Fofana reported that the hospital services have been stretched. [ADD] On 8 November, the victims were buried in a mass ceremony. \c\c [KEEP] The event has been described as first of its kind in the densely populated city of about 1.2 million and follows a number of similar high-casualty fuel tanker explosions across sub-Saharan Africa where fuel spilled was viewed as wasteful in communities where many struggled to afford petrol. [KEEP] Mass casualties from similar events have occurred in the 2018 Mbuba tanker explosion in the Democratic Republic of Congo that killed 50 and the 2019 Morogoro explosion in Tanzania that killed 85. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\c
[KEEP] Israel's COVID-19 vaccination programme, officially named "Give a Shoulder" (Hebrew: לתת כתף), began on 19 December 2020, and has been praised for its speed, having given twenty percent of the Israeli population the first dose of the vaccines\' two dose regimen in the span of three weeks. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAs of June 26, 2021, about 64% of eligible Israelis have received at least one dose (and a world-leading 60% with two doses), making Israel one of the populations with the highest vaccination rates in the world per capita. [KEEP] Coordinated vaccination drives by the country's health authorities, utilizing databases of personal information for Israeli patients, contributed to Israel's success in vaccinating a high proportion of its population in a short period of time, relative to the rest of the world. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cMany factors contributed to the quick distribution of vaccines in the state of Israel. [KEEP] Israel's population is younger on average than many other developed countries, with 12% of its population over the age of 65. [KEEP] (→ Demographics of Israel) <Background> \c\cIsrael is smaller in land area than many other developed nations. [KEEP] It has a comparatively small population of about 9.3 million people and a high population density (424/km2). [KEEP] <Background> \c\cIsrael's organized response in terms of attaining, storing and distributing vaccines was considered to be overall well coordinated. [KEEP] This is in part owed to the centralized nature of Israel's government system, which for example does not defer many health policy decisions to lower state-level bodies of government. [KEEP] The state purchased a substantial amount of Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines relative to its population as early as December 2020. [KEEP] In May 2020, the state secured agreements with companies which were developing vaccines, such as Moderna. [KEEP] <History> \c\cEarly into the programme, Israel provided Pfizer with medical information about its citizens as part of a deal for the country to receive a supply COVID-19 vaccines from the company. [KEEP] <History> \c\c [KEEP] The initial campaign for vaccinations focused on the elderly (people over the age of 60) and other patient groups with a high risk of severe illness in the case of infection, such as those with preexisting conditions, as well as employees of the healthcare sector. [KEEP] After eight weeks, nearly 85% of health workers at a hospital in Jerusalem (Hadassah Hebrew University Medical Center) were vaccinated. [KEEP] <History> \c\cIsrael started its campaign on 19 December 2020, with prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu being the first person in the country to receive the vaccine, getting injected on live TV to encourage other Israelis to get vaccinated. [KEEP] In less than two weeks, over 10% of Israelis received their first dose. [KEEP] <History> \c\cMass vaccination in Israel has produced evidence that the Pfizer vaccine works to stop transmission of the virus, including asymptomatic infections. [KEEP] The vaccination programme has also curbed deaths in the country. [KEEP] <History> \c\cAs of early February 2021, at least 90% of Israelis over the age of 60 received at least one dose of the Pfizer vaccine, and there was a 41% drop in confirmed infections in the country compared with the previous month. [KEEP] By late February, at least 4.8 million Israelis received at least one dose. [KEEP] This mass vaccination led to a drop in severe COVID-19 cases. [KEEP] Israel passed a law allowing government workers to identify and contact those who have not been vaccinated, in order to convince them to do so. [KEEP] <History> \c\cTo access certain locations such as gyms, hotels, and theatres, immunized residents show a green pass (also known as a "green badge"), which was officially introduced by the Israeli Ministry of Health on February 21. [KEEP] The green pass indicates the holder is immunized against COVID-19, either by vaccination or previous infection. [KEEP] People who have received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine are eligible to receive this certificate of vaccination. [KEEP] It expires after six months. [KEEP] <History> \c\cAs of March 2021, Israel has the highest vaccinated population per capita in the world. [KEEP] About 60% of residents in Israel received at least one dose of COVID-19 vaccine by March, and certain public places reopened access for those who were vaccinated. [KEEP] Only about 100,000 residents over the age of 50 remained unvaccinated. [KEEP] By March, at least 50% of the Israeli population had received both doses of the Pfizer vaccine. [KEEP] <History> \c\cThe perceived success of Israel's vaccination programme has been credited to the centralized systems its health maintenance organizations maintained, especially with regard to managing the personal health data of Israelis. [KEEP] They were able to coordinate national vaccination drives, contacting residents directly using a database of contact information such as phone numbers and emails. [KEEP] Every Israeli citizen must register with one of the country's four HMOs. [ADD] <History> \c\cOn 10 November 2021, the Israeli Government approved the use of COVID-19 vaccine shots for children between the ages of 5 and 11 years. [ADD] Israeli epidemiologists and health authorities have identified vaccine hesitancy among parents as an obstacle to getting children vaccinated. [KEEP] The country expanded the availability to all Israelis over the age of 12, after five months since their second shot. [KEEP] On 29 August 2021, Israel's coronavirus czar announced that Israelis who had not received a booster shot within six months of their second dose would lose access to the country's green pass vaccine passport. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\cIsraeli [KEEP] authorities faced problems with distributing their supply of COVID-19 vaccines early into vaccination drives. [KEEP] This included trouble with scheduling appointments, loosely interpreted eligibility early on which led to supply problems, and lack of sufficient distribution to less-populated villages and Arab-Israeli communities. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\cDuring the first quarter of 2021, Israel had to address a moderate amount of vaccine hesitancy in its general population, and also address more intense pockets of vaccine hesitancy among young adults and religious/cultural minority groups. [KEEP] The challenges were addressed via a mix of messaging, incentives, extensions to the initial vaccine delivery system, and other measures. [KEEP] Many of the measures addressed the general population, while others were targeted at subgroups with below-average vaccination rates. [KEEP] Once the early adopters had been vaccinated, it took hard, creative work to increase population coverage from 40 to 60% and beyond. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\cDistribution of vaccines to Palestinians has not been as thorough as to Israeli citizens. [KEEP] In early March, the supply of COVID-19 vaccines was not sufficient to cover all of its healthcare workers. [KEEP] Until March, when Israel began vaccinating Palestinian laborers with the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, the Palestinian Authority received only enough doses for about 6,000 people. [KEEP] Gaza has a population of about 2 million, by comparison. [KEEP] United Nations officials called for more support for vaccinating Palestinians, and praised Israel's assistance in this regard, while Amnesty International expressed concern that Israel had not done more for Palestinians with regard to the COVID-19 pandemic. [KEEP] Some Israeli health officials urged the government to provide vaccinations to all Palestinians. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\cAccording to Business Insider, Israeli citizens of any origin as well as Palestinian residents in East Jerusalem were eligible for the vaccine, with people older than 60, healthcare workers, and the "especially vulnerable" being prioritized. [KEEP] However, an estimated five million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza (which are not under Israeli control) were not eligible as their healthcare is under the jurisdiction of the Palestinian Authority per the Oslo Accords. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\cBy late March, Israel vaccinated more than 100,000 Palestinian laborers. [KEEP] In June 2021, Israel announced it would give over 1 million soon-to-expire Pfizer vaccines to the Palestinian Authority in exchange for a later reimbursement of a similar amount of vaccines which the Palestinian Authority expects to receive from Pfizer in the first quarter of 2022. [KEEP] In June 18, 100,000 of these doses had already been transferred to the West Bank's Palestinian Health Ministry. [KEEP] However, the Palestinian Authority soon pulled out of the exchange deal, saying the doses expired too fast. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\cAs of March 2021, Haredi Jews and Arab-Israelis had a lower rate of vaccination, compared to other sections of the population in Israel. [KEEP] These demographics were also comparatively more likely to be hesitant or skeptical about taking the vaccine. [KEEP] Haredi Jews are about 12% of Israel's population. [KEEP] <Distribution issues> \c\c [KEEP]
[KEEP] Just before 11:00 am GMT on 14 November 2021, a taxi exploded in the car park outside the main entrance of the Liverpool Women's Hospital in Liverpool, England. [KEEP] The passenger was killed and the driver of the taxi was injured. [KEEP] The explosion was later declared as a terrorist incident. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cOn [KEEP] 14 November 2021, at approximately 10:59 am GMT, an explosion occurred inside a taxi in the car park in front of the main entrance of the Liverpool Women's Hospital. [KEEP] The explosion was caused by an improvised explosive device which was carried by the taxi's passenger, a man of Middle Eastern origin not known to MI5, who was killed in the incident probably having constructed the device himself. [KEEP] The taxi driver was admitted to hospital and described as "shaken and injured"—including an ear needing to be sewn back on—but released the following day. [KEEP] <Incident> \c\cMerseyside Police attended the scene, along with fire and ambulance crews; they were accompanied by Military Logistics and the Bomb Squad. [KEEP] <Incident> \c\cThe bomber's motivation for the attack was not immediately known, however, one theory emerged that he was intending to walk to the cathedral and detonate his device as the congregation left. [ADD] Police said he had links to both areas of Liverpool that had been raided. [KEEP] Early reports suggested that on arrival he locked the doors of his vehicle on his passenger before it went up in flames, although a Counterterrorism spokesman noted that officers had not yet spoken to Perry as of Sunday evening. [KEEP] <Investigation> \c\cThe police made three arrests under the Terrorism Act, and although they had not at that point declared the explosion to be a terrorist incident, they said the investigation was being run by counter terrorism officers, "out of caution". [KEEP] Robert Wright of The Financial Times said that any determination that the incident is considered terrorism would be made by the Counter Terrorism Command of the Metropolitan Police. [KEEP] <Investigation> \c\cLiverpool Police armed units raided a property in the Sefton Park area, although the BBC noted that they had not "confirmed whether the two incidents are related". [KEEP] Three men aged 29, 26, and 21 were arrested in the Kensington area of Liverpool under the Terrorism Act. [KEEP] Police later stated the arrests were a direct response to the attack. [KEEP] The arrests were made on Boaler Street, which is within walking distance of the hospital [KEEP] A fourth man was arrested. [KEEP] and a number of houses in the Sefton Park area had been evacuated. [KEEP] The Independent noted that this was a "usual precaution... where explosive materials are suspected or found". [KEEP] A controlled explosion was carried out in the middle of Sefton Park, "a few hundred metres" from Rut;and avenue. [KEEP] <Investigation> \c\cThe Independent questioned whether there was a "connection between the timing of the incident and the fact that it occurred on Remembrance Sunday, with the associated minute’s silence usually observed at 11am." [KEEP] The paper noted that the hospital is a short distance from Liverpool Cathedral, where the remembrance service was taking place attended by thousands of veterans and military personnel with a subsequent parade. [KEEP] On this, the police stated <Investigation - Response> \c\cThe Mayor of Liverpool, Joanne Anderson, made a statement, while Prime Minister Boris Johnson congratulated Perry, stating that "it does look as though the taxi driver in question did behave with incredible presence of mind and bravery". [KEEP] The shadow Health Secretary Jonathan Ashworth apologised on Monday evening having passed his condolences on to the family of the dead man without mentioning David Perry. [KEEP] He explained that a misreading of the news had led him to understand that the dead man had been an innocent member of the public. [KEEP] <Investigation - Response> \c\cOn 15 November 2021 the police declared the explosion a terrorist incident, and the UK terror threat level was raised from substantial to severe. [KEEP] MI5 joined the investigation on the same day of the incident in a support role for the local police, while COBRA met on Monday morning. [KEEP] The Telegraph reported that the perpetrator was unknown to MI5. [KEEP] <Investigation - Response> \c\cThe event was reported internationally, including by CNN and The New York Times and the Washington Post. [KEEP] <Investigation - Response> \c\c
[ADD] A final result is expected on election night at 10pm (UTC+13:00). [KEEP] In September 2019 Pohiva died, and Pohiva Tuʻiʻonetoa was elected as Prime Minister with the support of the nobles, independent MPs, and 5 former members of the DPFI. [KEEP] His cabinet included three nobles, who had previously been excluded under Pohiva. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cIn December 2020 Democratic party leader Semisi Sika submitted a motion of no-confidence in Prime Minister Tuʻiʻonetoa. [KEEP] The motion was backed by Deputy Prime Minister Sione Vuna Fa'otusia, who subsequently resigned from Cabinet. [KEEP] The Legislative Assembly rejected the no-confidence motion 13-9 on 12 January 2021. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe Legislative Assembly of Tonga has up to 30 members, of which 17 are directly elected by first-past-the-post voting from single-member constituencies. [KEEP] The island of Tongatapu has ten constituencies, Vavaʻu three, Haʻapai two and ʻEua and Niuatoputapu/Niuafoʻou one each. [KEEP] Nine seats are held by members of the nobility who elect representatives amongst themselves. [KEEP] The Cabinet formed by a Prime Minister may include up to four members not elected to the Assembly, who then automatically become members of the legislature. [KEEP] <Electoral system> \c\cParliament was dissolved on 16 September. [KEEP] 75 candidates, including 12 women, registered to contest the election. [KEEP] One candidate, Sione Fonua, later withdrew, while a second one died, leaving 73 candidates in total. [KEEP] Despite a week-long lockdown due to a COVID-19 case, the election was not delayed. [KEEP] "} <Campaign> \c\c
