[KEEP] The 2021 Solomon Islands unrest is a series of ongoing demonstrations and violent riots in the Solomon Islands, which began on 24 November 2021. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The Solomon Islands had historically been in a state of ethnic conflict until 2003, when Australia deployed a peacekeeping mission. [KEEP] In 2019, the central government under Prime Minister Manasseh Sogavare withdrew recognition of the Republic of China (Taiwan) and established relations with the mainland People's Republic of China. [KEEP] Malaita Province, however, continued to be supported by Taiwan and the United States, the latter sending US$25 million of aid to the island in 2020. [KEEP] The premier of Malaita Province, Daniel Suidani, also held an independence referendum in 2020 which the national government has dismissed as illegitimate. [KEEP] <Background> \c\c [KEEP] The protests were initially peaceful, but turned violent on 24 November 2021 after buildings adjoining the Solomon Islands Parliament Building were burnt down. [KEEP] Violence escalated as Honiara's Chinatown was looted. [KEEP] Police fired upon protesters with tear gas. [KEEP] <Events> \c\cMost of the protesters came from Malaita province. [KEEP] <Events> \c\cAustralia responded to the unrest by deploying Australian Federal Police and Australian Defence Force personnel following a request from the Sogavare government under the Australia-Solomon Islands Bilateral Security Treaty. [KEEP] The Australian Government stated this deployment was to support the Solomon Islands Police Force to maintain order and protect vital infrastructure and would take no position on the internal issues of the Solomon Islands. [KEEP] Papua New Guinea agreed to send 34 peacekeepers to help staunch the violence. [KEEP] <Events> \c\cAs Australian police and soldiers deployed to secure the port, airport and other critical infrastructure, mobs once again torched buildings and looted the smouldering rubble of shops in the usually sleepy Solomons Island seaside capital of Honiara. [KEEP] Thousands of people -- some brandishing axes and knives -- rampaged through the city's Chinatown, Point Cruz and business districts, according to AFP correspondents on the scene. [KEEP] Crowds voiced their anger on Friday 26 November by setting fire to at least one building near Sogavare's home, before police fired warning shots to drive the mob back toward the centre of Honiara, AFP reporters witnessed. [KEEP] <Events> \c\cIn Chinatown, a large warehouse was set alight, causing an explosion that sent scores of people fleeing from the scene in panic. [KEEP] A tobacco warehouse was also set alight as smoke from previous days fires cast parts of the devastated city of 80,000 people in an acrid haze. [KEEP] The overrun Royal Solomon Islands Police Force said Friday they had made just two arrests, despite two police stations being among the many buildings burned. [KEEP] <Reactions - Domestic> \c\cPrime Minister Manasseh Sogavare warned the rioters would "face consequences", and resisted calls to resign, saying that if he would be removed, "it will be on the floor of Parliament". [KEEP] He also accused the protesters of being "politically motivated" and, during an interview with the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, blamed "foreign powers" for the unrest. [KEEP] <Reactions - Domestic> \c\cThe premier of Malaita Province, Daniel Suidani, criticized the Government's choices but also condemned the violence on the part of the protesters. [KEEP] The premier of Guadalcanal also strongly denounced the riots. [KEEP] <Reactions - Domestic> \c\cMatthew Wale, the Opposition Leader, said Sogavare should step down, blaming him for escalating the violence. [KEEP] <Reactions - International> \c\cThe government of the People's Republic of China expressed "concern about the attacks" and support for the Solomon Islands Government's attempts to "restore order and stability quickly". [KEEP] Deputy Director of the Chinese Foreign Ministry Zhao Lijian has recently stated "Facts have proven that the establishment of diplomatic relations between China and the Solomon Islands is in line with the fundamental and long-term development of the Solomon Islands." [KEEP] And also stating that, "Any attempt to undermine the normal development of China-Solomon Islands relations would be futile." [KEEP] <Reactions - International> \c\c
[KEEP] The 2021—2022 European windstorm season is the seventh instance of seasonal European windstorm naming in Europe. [KEEP] This is the third season in which the Netherlands will participate, alongside the meteorological agencies of Ireland and the United Kingdom (Western Group). [KEEP] The new season's storm names were released on 1 September 2021. [KEEP] Storms that occur up until 31 August 2022 will be included in this season. [KEEP] The Portuguese, Spanish, French  and Belgian meteorological agencies will again collaborate too, joined by the Luxembourguish meteorological agency (South-western Group). [KEEP] This is the first season when Greece, Israel and Cyprus (Eastern Mediterranean group) name storms which affect their areas. [KEEP] This is also the first season for Italy, Slovenia, Croatia, Montenegro, North Macedonia and Malta (Central Mediterranean Group). [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cIn 2015, the Met Office and Met Éireann announced a pilot project to name storm warnings as part of the "Name our Storms" project for wind storms and asked the public for suggestions. [KEEP] The meteorological offices produced a full list of names for 2015–2016 through to 2017–2018, common to both the United Kingdom and Ireland, with the Netherlands taking part from 2019 onwards. [KEEP] Names in the United Kingdom will be based on the National Severe Weather Warning Service, when a storm is assessed to have the potential for an Amber (\'be prepared\') or Red (\'take action (danger to life)\') warning. [KEEP] <Background and naming> \c\cThere are two main naming lists: one created by the national meteorological agencies of the United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands, and another created by the equivalent agencies from France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium and Luxembourg. [KEEP] Additionally, former Atlantic hurricanes will retain their names as assigned by the National Hurricane Center of the United States. [KEEP] <Background and naming> \c\cAlso, some of these storms may be of tropical origins. [KEEP] For example, ex-Hurricane Lorenzo of 2019 made landfall in Ireland and the United Kingdom. [KEEP] All details on tropical storms and hurricanes can be found on the National Hurricane Centre. [KEEP] <Background and naming> \c\cFrom the Autumn of 2021 the names issued by other meteorological services will also be included on the charts of the Berlin Wetterkarte and Free University of Berlin using the prefix "int." [KEEP] under the EUMETNET umbrella. [KEEP] <Background and naming> \c\c [KEEP] The following names were chosen for the 2021–2022 season in the United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cThis will be the fifth year in which the meteorological agencies of France, Spain and Portugal will be naming storms that affect their areas. [KEEP] This naming scheme partially overlaps that used by the United Kingdom, Ireland and the Netherlands, as storms named by the other group of agencies will be used reciprocally. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cThis will be the first year in which the meteorological agencies of Greece, Israel and Cyprus will be naming storms that affect their areas. [KEEP] This naming scheme partially overlaps that used by the France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium and Luxembourg, as storms named by the other group of agencies will be used reciprocally. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cThis will be the first year in which the meteorological agencies of Italy, Slovenia, Croatia, Montenegro, North Macedonia and Malta will be naming storms that affect their areas. [KEEP] Storms named by the other group of agencies will be used reciprocally. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cAll storms named by meteorological organisation in Europe from there respected forecasting areas. [KEEP] As well as, Atlantic hurricanes and storms that transitioned into a European windstorm and retained its name as assigned by the National Hurricane Center in Miami, Florida: [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cA depression formed on October 4 in the western Mediterranean and was named Christian by the Free University of Berlin. [KEEP] It was named Storm Athina by Hellenic National Meteorological Service on October 6 and intensified when it arrived in southern Italy on October 8. [KEEP] The system then passed into the Ionian Sea before dissipating on the 9th. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cIn central Italy, Athina caused record rainfall in Liguria with 496 mm in Savona in just 6 hours, breaking the record of 472 mm of November 2011. [KEEP] The main roads of the island of Corfu turned into rivers, the basements were flooded, power outages occurred, small landslides occurred and firefighter interventions were required with the storm front rains preceding the system. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cStorm [KEEP] Ballos has been named by Hellenic National Meteorological Service on 13 October, heavy rain and floods in Athens (Αθήνα) on October 15 and some of the islands have been reported. [KEEP] Heavy rain is predicted for 15. [KEEP] October in Eastern Macedonia and Thrace and a red alert with heavy rain and severe thunderstorms in North Aegean islands (meteoalarm). [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cA storm, named Hendrik by the Free University of Berlin on October 16, developed over the northern Atlantic Ocean. [KEEP] Another developing low South of Ireland was called Aurore by Meteo France on 20 October. [KEEP] Passing over the South of England the following night, Aurore generated very strong south-westerly winds and heavy rains from Brittany to the Grand Est in France, then central Europe as it merged with Hendrik over western Europe. [KEEP] An orange alert for wind has been issued by meteorological services in western Europe, and even red for parts of southern and eastern Germany. [KEEP] The system reached northern Russia on October 22 and disappeared in northern Siberia the next day. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cAurore/Hendrik brought widespread gusts of 100 to 120 km/h (62 to 75 mph; 54 to 65 kn) from northern France to eastern Germany and beyond, reaching speeds of 175 km/h (109 mph; 94 kn; 49 m/s) in Fecamp in Normandy. [KEEP] Fallen trees distrupted train service in several countries. [KEEP] Two tornadoes touched down in the Netherlands, in Brittany (France), 3 possible tornadoes have been reported in Plozévet, Riec-sur-Belon and  Kernascléden. [KEEP] and in Germany, another touched down near Kiel <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cFour people have been killed in Poland. [KEEP] Each one death were reported in Germany. [KEEP] and the United Kingdom. [KEEP] Around 250,000 clients lost electricity in France and 275,000 in the Czech Republic. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\c [KEEP] Cyclone Apollo was a Mediterranean tropical-like cyclone that affected many countries on the Mediterranean coast, especially Italy and Libya. [KEEP] The storm killed at least 5 people and left 2 others missing due to flooding from the cyclone, in the countries of Tunisia, Algeria, Malta, and Italy, where the worst of the effects have been felt, especially on the island of Sicily. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cAround 22 October 2021, an area of organized thunderstorms formed near the Balearic Islands, with the disturbance becoming more organized and developing an area of low pressure around 24 October. [KEEP] On the next day, the low started to develop a low-level circulation center, and moved into the Tyrrhenian Sea. [KEEP] On 28 October, the system organized even further and intensified, which prompted forecast offices in Europe to name the low. [KEEP] Italy's "Servizio Meteorologico" named the storm Apollo (which was then adopted by the Free University of Berlin). [KEEP] On 29 October 2021, a ship in the Mediterranean Sea passed through Apollo and measured a peak wind speed of 104 km/h (65 mph; 56 kn)  and a pressure of 999.4 mb (29.51 inHg), indicating that Apollo is still strengthening. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cThen, on 2 November, it dissipated off the coast of Turkey. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cHeavy rain from the cyclone and its precursor caused heavy rainfall and flooding in Tunisia, Algeria, Southern Italy, and Malta, killing 5 people and leaving 2 other people missing. [KEEP] The flooding was especially severe in the provinces of Catania and Siracusa, in Eastern Sicily. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cOn [KEEP] November 5, the Spanish Meteorological Agency (AEMET) started tracking a low near the Balearic Islands and named it Blas. [KEEP] An orange alert has been issued for these islands, for coastal phenomena and rain. [KEEP] The north of Catalonia was declared an Orange Zone, as strong winds blew inland from the Spanish Navarre and Aragon. [KEEP] Météo-France has also issued a yellow alert for Aude and Pyrénées-Orientales for wind, as well as Corsica for rain. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\c [KEEP] As the system stalled between Sardinia and the Balearic Islands on November 8, AEMET predicted a strengthening for the next two days and maintained its alerts. [KEEP] After striking the islands again, the storm then slowly weakened while drifting back Southeastward. [KEEP] On 14 November, the cyclone turned northward, moving over Sardinia and Corsica, before curving back southwestward on 15 November and moving over Sardinia again, while restrengthening in the process. [KEEP] On 16 November, Blas turned eastward once again, passing just south of Sardinia and moving towards Italy, before dissipating over the Tyrrhenian Sea on 18 November. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cOn [KEEP] November 6, gusts of 75 km/h (47 mph; 40 kn) were recorded at Es Mercadal and 95 km/h (59 mph; 51 kn) at the lighthouse of Capdepera in the Balearic Islands where waves of 8 m (26 ft) hit the coast. [KEEP] Menorca was cut off from the world after the closure of the ports of Mahón and Ciutadella. [KEEP] On November 9 and 10, Blas again brought high winds and heavy rain to the Balearic Islands, causing at least 36 incidents, mostly flooding, landslides and blackouts. [KEEP] A crew member had to be rescued after his sailboat's mast broke, leaving the boat adrift 80 km (50 mi) West of Soller. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cOn [KEEP] November 6, a waterspout was reported in Melilla, a Spanish enclave on the coast of Morocco. [KEEP] In France, gusts of 140 km/h (87 mph; 76 kn) were noted on November7 at Cap Béar, as well as 111 km/h (69 mph; 60 kn) in Leucate and 100 km/h (62 mph; 54 kn) in Lézignan-Corbières. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\c [KEEP] The storm caused severe weather on the Algerian coast with exceptional rainfall. [KEEP] On November 9, a building collapsed in Algiers following torrential rains on the city, causing the deaths of three people. [KEEP] On November 11, the heavy rain continuing on Algiers caused another landslide on houses in the Raïs Hamidou neighborhood, causing the deaths of three other persons. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\cFrom November 8 to 11, convective bands associated with the storm caused 3 deaths in Sicily. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\c [KEEP] Storm Arwen was named by the Met Office on 25 November 2021. [KEEP] <Background and naming - Western Group (United Kingdom, Ireland, and the Netherlands)> \c\c [KEEP] Red warnings for wind have been issued for north-eastern parts of the UK, as well as extensive orange and yellow warnings for much of Scotland, Northern Ireland, Wales and most of England. [KEEP] Dangerous waves have also been forecasted, with likely disruption to ferry services. [KEEP] <Background and naming - South-western Group (France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium and Luxembourg)> \c\cOn 23–24 September, a storm named "Tim" by the Free University of Berlin (FUB), caused the death of two people in Germany and Poland. [KEEP] <Background and naming - South-western Group (France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium and Luxembourg)> \c\cIn early November 2021, the remnants of Atlantic Tropical Storm Wanda were absorbed into the cold front of a mid-latitude storm, called "Stephane" by the FUB, moving towards the United Kingdom and Ireland. [KEEP] On 9 November, Stephane affected the Northern European Countries and caused heavy snowfall and rainfall. [KEEP] <Background and naming - South-western Group (France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium and Luxembourg)> \c\cOn 19 November, a storm called "Volker" by FUB moved across Poland killing one and injuring two. [KEEP] One person remains missing. [KEEP] <Background and naming - South-western Group (France, Spain, Portugal, Belgium and Luxembourg)> \c\c [KEEP]
[KEEP] On November 30, 2021, a gunman opened fire on students at Oxford High School in the Detroit exurb of Oxford Township, Michigan, killing three students and injuring eight others, including one teacher. [KEEP] The suspected shooter is a 15-year-old sophomore student who is in custody. [RM] <Summary> \c\cAccording to the parent of a student who stayed home on November 30, threats of a mass shooting occurring at Oxford High School were already present before the incident occurred. [RM] Earlier that month, in an act of vandalism, a deer head had been thrown off the school roof, prompting school administrators to notify parents that they had been investigating rumors of a threat against the school but found none. [KEEP] Some students were evacuated to a nearby Meijer store. [KEEP] <Shooting> \c\cAt 12:55 p.m. EST, police arrived at the school after receiving around 100 911 calls. [KEEP] The shooter was arrested unharmed. [KEEP] At a news conference, Oakland County undersheriff Michael McCabe said the gunman "gave up without any problems." [KEEP] <Shooting> \c\cThree students were killed, and eight other people were injured, including a teacher. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\cOn the evening of November 30, Undersheriff McCabe said two of the wounded people were in surgery, in unknown condition, while the remaining six were in stable condition. [KEEP] A 9 mm SIG Sauer SP2022 semiautomatic handgun was recovered from the suspect; Oakland County Sheriff Michael Bouchard said the suspect's father had purchased the gun four days prior to the shooting. [KEEP] Based on recovered shell casings found in the school, authorities believe around 15 to 20 shots were fired. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\cPresident Joe Biden and Representative Elissa Slotkin, whose district includes Oxford High School, both expressed their condolences over the shooting. [KEEP] Governor Gretchen Whitmer said in a statement that she was "devastated for the students, staff, and families" of the school, calling gun violence a "public health crisis". [KEEP] <Responses> \c\c
[KEEP] The 2021 Semeru eruption began on 4 December on the Indonesian island of Java in the East Java province. [KEEP] Fourteen people have been killed, at least 102 more are wounded, while 10 are unaccounted for. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cSemeru is one of the most active volcanoes in Indonesia. [KEEP] At 3,676 meters in elevation, it is the highest volcano on the island. [KEEP] The volcano is part of a chain of volcanic mountains stretching from northern Sumatra to the Lesser Sunda Islands. [KEEP] Volcanism in Indonesia is mainly associated with the offshore subduction of the Indo-Australian Plate beneath the Sunda Plate. [KEEP] The oldest record of an eruption was from 1818. [KEEP] Since then, major eruptions have occurred in 1941, 1942, 1945, 1946, 1947, 1950, 1951, 1952, 1953, 1954, 1955 – 1957, 1958, 1959, 1960, 1977, and 1978-1989. [KEEP] A minor eruption occurred in January 2021 with no casualties reported. [KEEP] The December 4 eruption is part of a series of explosive eruptions on the volcano beginning in 2014. [KEEP] Recent eruptions on the volcano have been accompanied by pyroclastic flows, eruption columns, and debris avalanches. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe eruption began at 14:50 local time, ejecting a cloud of volcanic ash 40,000 feet (12,000 m) into the air. [KEEP] The eruption is thought to have begun when a lava dome at the summit crater collapsed due to intense precipitation. [KEEP] The collapsed dome triggered a pyroclastic flow that traveled down the slopes of the volcano. [KEEP] <Eruption> \c\cIn the Malang Regency, six sub districts were affected by ashfall. [KEEP] Eight villages and two sub districts in the Lumajang Regency were also affected. [KEEP] The destruction of the Gladak Perak Bridge sealed road vehicle access to villages in the area. [KEEP] Power interruptions and blackouts were triggered, affecting at least 30,253 people. [KEEP] In the Pronojiwo District of East Java, at least 30 homes were destroyed by lahars. [KEEP] Many village homes and vehicles in East Java were buried under heavy volcanic ash. [KEEP] An estimated 300 families were evacuated. [KEEP] <Impact> \c\cOn [KEEP] December 5, volcanic ash fell in the Pronojiwo District of Lumajang, forcing many evacuees, residents and aid officials to flee. [KEEP] It was reported that a smaller eruption had occurred. [KEEP] The small eruption caused panic at nearby villages. [KEEP] Some 28 schools in two districts; six in Candipuro and 22 in Pronojiwo were heavily damaged by ashfall. [ADD] At least 11 villages in Lumajang were submerged in ash reaching up the roofs of homes. [ADD] Many vehicles were also submerged. [ADD] Kampung Renteng, a village in the Candipuro District, heavily affected by ash. [ADD] At another village, ash had destroyed every home. [KEEP] Four burn victims were taken to the intensive care unit for their serious injuries. [KEEP] A total of 38 people were treated at the Penanggal Health Center. [KEEP] Another 10 miners at a sand mine in Renteng Village were trapped and an initial attempt to rescue the miners was unsuccessful. [KEEP] A subsequent report indicated differently. [KEEP] According to the Indonesian National Board for Disaster Management (BNPB), ten miners thought to be missing at a sand mine in Lumajang were rescued. [KEEP] However, some number of sand miners are still unaccounted for. [KEEP] <Impact - Casualties> \c\cA second death was confirmed on the morning of December 5 at the Dr. Haryoto Hospital due to severe burns. [KEEP] The total death toll was later revised to 14, with many of the victims dead from burns. [KEEP] Two of the fatalities were from the Supiturang and Sumberwuluh villages respectively. [KEEP] Five other victims were from the Curah Kobokan village. [KEEP] Five bodies are undergoing the identification process at the Bhayangkara Hospital. [KEEP] The number of burn victims was also updated to 89 from the early morning figure of 57. [KEEP] <Impact - Casualties> \c\cLocal authorities have urged residents to keep a distance of at least 5 km away from the main summit crater as there are concerns of large pyroclastic flows. [KEEP] The head of the BNPB had warned of increased volcanic activity and the presence of pyroclastic flows in the volcano. [KEEP] The head also said ashfall were occurring in some villages hence residents have been urged to evacuate. [KEEP] Residents were also told to keep clear from rivers originating from Semeru as they are transporting volcanic debris. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cBy Sunday, December 5, at least 5,205 people were affected, with 1,300 residents in Lumajang displaced. [KEEP] The displaced residents and took refuge in multiple locations. [KEEP] In the Pronojiwo District, some 305 people resided in schools and village halls. [KEEP] 409 people were displaced in the Candipuro District, and 188 in Pasirian. [KEEP] Some of the evacuees later moved to other homes or buildings. [KEEP] A rescue operation to locate several miners unaccounted for on the afternoon of the eruption is said to begin once activity on the volcano has decreased. [KEEP] The Deputy Regent of Lumajang said that rescue and recovery efforts could not be carried out the night before due to difficult access to the affected areas. [KEEP] The BNPB provided meals ready-to-eat packs, blankets, mattresses, masks and refugee tents in an effort to assist the displaced residents. [KEEP] Medical supplies, water and instant food were also supplied. [KEEP] It is estimated that 1,14 billion Indonesian rupiah was utilised in providing aid. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cOperations at the Yogyakarta International Airport, Adisumarmo International Airport and Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport were unaffected by the eruption as no volcanic ash were observed. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cIndonesian President Joko Widodo would visit the Lumajang Regency to lead the BNPB in the post-eruption recovery efforts on December 5. [KEEP] Meanwhile, Khofifah Indar Parawansa, the Governor of East Java, relocated her office to the Lumajang Regency to aid in the evacuation process of residents in the danger zone. [KEEP] <Response> \c\c
[KEEP] On 4 December 2021, a unit of 21 Para Special Forces, the special forces unit of the Indian Army, killed six civilians near Oting village of Mon district in Nagaland, India. [KEEP] Eight more civilians and a soldier were killed in subsequent violence. [KEEP] According to the Indian army, the killings resulted from a "case of mistaken identity" in a failed ambush. [KEEP] A Special Investigation Team (SIT) was formed to probe the incident. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe incident sparked public outrage across the state in the following days. [KEEP] The killings were widely condemned with many calling to repeal and revoke the Armed Forces Special Powers Act (AFSPA). [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cOn the evening of 4 December 2021 at around 4:00–5:00 p.m. [KEEP] IST, a unit of the 21 Para Special Forces of Indian Army ambushed a vehicle—carrying civilians from Oting village who were returning from a coal mine at Tiru—and opened fire. [KEEP] Six people died, and two received serious injuries. [KEEP] <Incidents - Ambush> \c\cIndian Army claims to have been the victim of an intelligence failure; they had suspected the vehicle to contain Naga insurgents. [KEEP] They further allege to have opened fire only when instructions to stop the vehicle were not paid heed to. [KEEP] <Incidents - Ambush> \c\cUpon hearing gunshots, as neighboring villagers arrived at the spot, a fresh round of violence broke out. [KEEP] Villagers claim that the forces were unwilling to hand over the bodies and trying to take them to their base camp. [KEEP] Three army vehicles were torched and in retaliatory firing, seven civilians were killed alongside a soldier. [KEEP] Another twelve civilians were seriously injured, while eight more sustained minor injuries. [KEEP] <Incidents - Retrieval of bodies> \c\c [KEEP] Indian [KEEP] Army claims to have opened fire under compulsion, as multiple infantrymen were injured in the melee. [KEEP] <Incidents - Retrieval of bodies> \c\cPublic protests were organised across Nagaland on 5 December 2021. [KEEP] More than two hundred people attacked and vandalised the army camp of Assam Rifles in Mon Town during which one more civilian was killed. [KEEP] <Incidents - Public protest> \c\c [KEEP] The following day, the Government of Nagaland imposed Section 144 in Mon District restricting public assembly and movement as well as suspending mobile internet and bulk SMS services. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\c [KEEP] The Eastern Nagaland People’s Organisation (ENPO) which represents six tribes withdrew from the ongoing annual Hornbill Festival at Kisama near Kohima. [KEEP] The Nagas hoisted black flags on all its Morungs at the festival while the Konyaks decided to abstain its cultural troupe from participating at the festival which was followed by the rest of the other Naga cultural troupes on 5 December. [KEEP] A two minutes silence was also observed at the venue on the same day. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\cLater that evening of 5 December, the people of Kohima observed a power blackout for 30 minutes to mourn the death of the civilians. [KEEP] The candlelight marches were organised in Kohima, Dimapur and other towns on the same day. [KEEP] A six-hour shutdown was also called by Naga Students\' Federation. [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\cThe incident sparked public outrage in Nagaland and was widely condemned with many calling to repeal and revoke the Armed Forces Special Powers Act (AFSPA). [KEEP] <Aftermath> \c\cOn [KEEP] 7 December, the Government of Nagaland announced that it would suspend all activities at Hornbill Festival and seek for the repeal of the Armed Forces Special Powers Act. [RM]  [ADD] 6 December, the Nagaland Police had registered a First information report against the 21 Para Special Forces, bringing charges of first degree murder. [RM] Instead, the army unit killed the coal mine workers in the similarly described vehicle. [RM] The army had received an input regarding the movement of the cadre of National Socialist Council of Nagaland (Khaplang-Yung Aung) (NSCN (K-YA)). <Investigation> \c\cThe Special Investigation Team (SIT) was formed and tasked to complete the investigation in a month. [ADD] A Special Investigation Team (SIT) was tasked to complete the investigation in a month. [RM] According to The Hindu, the killings were the result of an intelligence failure. <Investigation> \c\cThe Nagaland Police registered a case against the 21 Para Special Forces. [RM] <Investigation> \c\cThe National Human Rights Commission of India sent notices to the Central and the State governments.
[KEEP] The COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom is part of the worldwide pandemic of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19). [KEEP] The virus reached the UK in late January 2020. [KEEP] As of 6 December 2021, there had been 10,523,316 confirmed cases, the most in Europe and fourth highest number worldwide,  and 165,721 deaths among people who had recently tested positive. [KEEP] The UK has the world's 7th highest death toll and 28th highest death rate by population. [KEEP] In Europe, the UK has the second-highest death toll after Russia, and the 20th highest death rate. [KEEP] There has been some disparity between the outbreak's severity in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland – health-care in the UK is a devolved matter. [KEEP] Each constituent country has its own publicly-funded healthcare system operated by devolved governments. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe virus was known to have spread to the UK by early 2020. [KEEP] The country's response included a public information campaign and certain expansions to government powers, but was otherwise slow to introduce preventative measures, increase testing or prepare for an outbreak. [KEEP] From March 2020 onwards, the government introduced restrictions across the UK on aspects of life such as people's freedom of movement, education, and leisure activities. [KEEP] Police were empowered to enforce the measures, and the Coronavirus Act 2020 gave all four governments emergency powers not used since the Second World War. [KEEP] These restrictions were eased and tightened periodically, and there was some variance in restrictions between the four countries of the UK and more localised rules were also introduced. [KEEP] In the early days of the pandemic, the health services worked to raise hospital capacity and set up temporary critical care hospitals, but faced shortages of personal protective equipment. [KEEP] In late 2020, a new more infectious variant of the virus emerged in the UK, causing another wave in infections over the winter that was deadlier than the first. [KEEP] The country's vaccination programme was the first to start in December 2020 and was in early 2021 one of the fastest in the world. [KEEP] The highly transmissible Delta variant arrived in the UK and drove a third wave of infections in mid-2021 that increased into the autumn, although high vaccination rates led to a substantially lower mortality rate than previous waves. [KEEP] In late 2021, the Omicron variant arrived in the UK and drove a further increase in cases. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cIn addition to the major strain on the UK's healthcare service and a substantial fall in life expectancy, the pandemic has had a severe impact on the UK's economy, caused major disruptions to education and had far-reaching impacts on society. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cOn 12 January 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) confirmed that a novel coronavirus was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019. [KEEP] The case fatality ratio for COVID-19 has been much lower than SARS of 2003, but the transmission has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cGenetic sequencing has traced most COVID-19 cases in the United Kingdom to imported cases from Italy, France, and Spain, rather than directly from China. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThough later reporting indicated that there may have been some cases dating from late 2019, COVID-19 was confirmed to be spreading in the UK by the end of January 2020 with the first confirmed deaths in March. [KEEP] The country was initially relatively slow in implementing restrictions. [KEEP] Subsequent epidemiological analysis showed that over 1000 lineages of SARS-CoV-2 entered the UK in early 2020 from international travellers, mostly from outbreaks elsewhere in Europe, leading to numerous clusters that overwhelmed contact tracing efforts. [KEEP] A legally enforced Stay at Home Order, or lockdown, was introduced on 23 March. [KEEP] Restrictions were steadily eased across the UK in late spring and early summer that year. [KEEP] The UK's epidemic in early 2020 was at the time one of the largest and deadliest worldwide. [KEEP] <History> \c\cBy the Autumn, COVID-19 cases were again rising. [KEEP] This lead to the creation of new regulations along with the introduction of localised restrictions. [KEEP] Larger lockdowns took place in all of Wales, England and Northern Ireland later that season. [KEEP] A new variant of the virus is thought to have originated in Kent around September 2020. [KEEP] Once restrictions were lifted, the novel variant rapidly spread across the UK. [KEEP] Its increased transmissibility contributed to a continued increase in daily infections. [KEEP] The healthcare system had come under severe strain by late December which led to further restrictions being introduced across all of the UK. [KEEP] <History> \c\c [KEEP] The first COVID-19 vaccine was approved and began being deployed across the UK in early December, 15 million vaccine doses had been given to predominantly those most vulnerable to the virus by mid-February. [KEEP] 6 months later more than 75% of adults in the UK were fully vaccinated against COVID-19. [KEEP] Quarantine rules for incoming travellers were introduced in late January. [KEEP] Restrictions began to ease from late February onwards and almost all had ended in Great Britain by August. [KEEP] A third wave of daily infections began in July 2021 due to the arrival and rapid spread of the highly transmissible SARS-CoV-2 Delta variant. [KEEP] However, mass vaccination continued to keep deaths and hospitalisations at much lower levels than in previous waves. [KEEP] Infection rates remained high and hospitalisations and deaths rose into the autumn. [RM] The SARS-CoV-2 Omicron variant was confirmed to have arrived and begun spreading in the community in early December, driving a further increase in cases. [ADD] The SARS-CoV-2 Omicron variant was confirmed to have arrived and begun spreading in the community in early December, driving a further increase in cases that surpassed previous records. [KEEP] <History> \c\c [KEEP] The COVID-19 pandemic led to the largest fall in life expectancy in England since records began in 1981. [KEEP] On average, British COVID-19 victims lost around a decade of life; the last time deaths rose so sharply in the UK was during World War II. [KEEP] In 2020, the disease was the leading cause of death among men, and second leading cause among women. [KEEP] Research suggests over 1 million people in the UK have had Long COVID, with the majority reporting substantial impacts on day to day life. [KEEP] The pandemic's major impact on the country's healthcare system, leading to long waiting lists for medical procedures and ambulances, also led to an indirect increase in deaths from other conditions. [KEEP] The lockdown also had a major mental health impact. [KEEP] <History> \c\cIn August 2021, a report from Age UK found that 27% of people over 60 could not walk as far and 25% were living in more physical pain earlier this year compared to the start of the pandemic. [KEEP] 54% of older people felt less confident attending a hospital appointment, and 37% of older people felt less confident going to a GP surgery. [KEEP] <History> \c\c [KEEP] The pandemic was widely disruptive to the economy of the United Kingdom, with most sectors and workforces adversely affected. [KEEP] Some temporary shutdowns became permanent; some people who were furloughed were later made redundant. [KEEP] The economic disruption has had a significant impact on people's mental health—with particular damage to the mental health of foreign-born men whose work hours have been reduced/eliminated. [KEEP] <History> \c\c [KEEP] The pandemic has had far-reaching consequences in the country that go beyond the spread of the disease itself and efforts to quarantine it, including political, cultural, and social implications. [KEEP] <Responses - Government response> \c\cSophie Grégoire Trudeau, the wife of Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, tested positive for COVID-19 upon her return from WE Day events in the UK; on 12 March 2020 the Trudeau family entered two weeks of self-isolation. [KEEP] The first patient in Mauritius was a 59-year-old man who returned from the United Kingdom on 7 March 2020. [KEEP] When he arrived in Mauritius, the Mauritian had no symptoms. [KEEP] Other cases of the novel coronavirus resulting from travel to the UK were subsequently reported in India and Nigeria. [KEEP] <Responses - Government response> \c\cOn 16 June 2020, it was widely reported in British media that New Zealand's first COVID-19 cases in 24 days were diagnosed in two British women, both of whom had travelled from the UK and were given special permission to visit a dying parent. [KEEP] The women had entered the country on 7 June, after first flying into Doha and Brisbane. [KEEP] <Responses - Government response> \c\cA 2021 study suggested that the SARS-CoV-2 Alpha variant which was first detected in Kent is thought to have began its spread to many countries internationally from flights originating in London in late 2020. [KEEP] <Responses - Government response> \c\cReports from the Medical Research Council's Centre for Global Infectious Disease Analysis at Imperial College, London have been providing mathematically calculated estimates of cases and case fatality rates. [KEEP] In February 2020, the team at Imperial College, led by epidemiologist Neil Ferguson, estimated about two-thirds of cases in travellers from China were not detected and that some of these may have begun "chains of transmission within the countries they entered". [KEEP] They forecast that the new type of coronavirus could infect up to 60% of the UK's population, in the worst-case scenario. [KEEP] <Impacts - Health and life expectancy> \c\cIn a paper on 16 March, the Imperial College team provided detailed forecasts of the potential impacts of the epidemic in the UK and US. [KEEP] It detailed the potential outcomes of an array of \'non-pharmaceutical interventions\'. [KEEP] Two potential overall strategies outlined were: mitigation, in which the aim is to reduce the health impact of the epidemic but not to stop transmission completely; and suppression, where the aim is to reduce transmission rates to a point where case numbers fall. [KEEP] Until this point, government actions had been based on a strategy of mitigation, but the modelling predicted that while this would reduce deaths by approximately 2/3, it would still lead to approximately 250,000 deaths from the disease and the health systems becoming overwhelmed. [KEEP] On 16 March, the Prime Minister announced changes to government advice, extending self-isolation to whole households, advising social distancing particularly for vulnerable groups, and indicating that further measures were likely to be required in the future. [KEEP] A paper on 30 March by the Imperial College group estimated that the lockdown would reduce the number of dead from 510,000 to less than 20,000. [KEEP] This paper and others relied on data from European countries including the UK to estimate that the combined non-pharmaceutical interventions reduced the reproduction number of the virus by 67-87%, enough to stop infections from growing. [KEEP] However, followup work concluded that the effectiveness of interventions was lower in later waves of infections. [KEEP] <Impacts - Health and life expectancy> \c\cIn April 2020, biostatistician Professor Sheila Bird said the delay in the reporting of deaths from the virus meant there was a risk of underestimating the steepness of the rising epidemic trend. [KEEP] <Impacts - Economic> \c\cIn December 2021 scientists from the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine predicted that Omicron could cause from 25,000 to 75,000 deaths in England over the five months to April unless there are more stringent restrictions. [KEEP] Omicron will probably be the dominant  variant by the end December. [KEEP] <Impacts - Social> \c\c
[KEEP] A by-election for the House of Commons constituency of North Shropshire, in the West Midlands, was held on 16 December 2021. [KEEP] It was triggered by the resignation of the Conservative Member of Parliament (MP) Owen Paterson on 4 November 2021. [KEEP] In a massive upset, the Liberal Democrats candidate Helen Morgan won the election with a 34.1% swing. [RM] The swing was the 7th largest in United Kingdom by-election history. <Summary> \c\cNorth [ADD] The swing was the 7th largest in United Kingdom by-election history, and the constituency had been held by the Conservatives for nearly 200 years. [KEEP] Shropshire is the third-largest constituency by area in the West Midlands region. [KEEP] It contains five small towns: Wem, Whitchurch, Ellesmere, Oswestry and Market Drayton. [KEEP] Sixty per cent of constituents who turned out voted to leave the European Union in the 2016 EU referendum. [KEEP] <Background - Constituency> \c\c [KEEP] The last time a by-election was held in the area was the 1904 Oswestry by-election, in which there was a Liberal gain from Conservative. [KEEP] <Background - Constituency> \c\cOn [KEEP] 4 November 2021, Owen Paterson resigned as MP for the constituency. [KEEP] In October, the Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards found that he had breached paid advocacy rules in relation to two companies which employed him as a paid consultant. [KEEP] The Commons Standards Committee considered the commissioners\' findings and recommended that Paterson be suspended from parliament for 30 days. [KEEP] In line with the established process, on 3 November a motion was proposed in the Commons inviting MPs to approve the punishment. [KEEP] If the suspension had been approved, a recall petition would have been triggered in the constituency. [KEEP] <Background - Reason> \c\cPaterson denied any wrongdoing. [KEEP] An amendment to the motion was put forward by Conservative backbencher [KEEP] Andrea Leadsom to postpone consideration of Paterson's suspension and to set up a new committee to investigate the disciplinary process for MPs. [KEEP] The government of Boris Johnson supported the amendment and issued a three-line whip. [KEEP] The amendment was passed. [KEEP] The outcome caused outrage among opposition MPs, and an angry public reaction to press reports. [KEEP] As a result, on 4 November, the government reversed its position and announced that a vote would still take place on whether Paterson should be suspended. [KEEP] Following that decision, Paterson announced his intention to resign from parliament. [KEEP] <Background - Reason> \c\cHe was appointed as Crown Steward and Bailiff of the Manor of Northstead on 5 November, the process by which an MP's resignation is effected. [KEEP] The writ of election was moved by Conservative Chief Whip Mark Spencer on 9 November. [KEEP] The by-election took place on 16 December. [KEEP] <Background - Reason> \c\cThere were 14 candidates in the by-election. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cOn 4 November, Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the Green Party had discussions about possibly standing aside in the by-election and backing a joint independent "anti-sleaze" candidate. [KEEP] This had previously happened in the seat of Tatton at the 1997 general election where independent candidate Martin Bell beat Neil Hamilton. [KEEP] Bell was approached by the Liberal Democrats ahead of the by-election in North Shropshire, but declined to stand. [KEEP] Labour, and subsequently the Liberal Democrats, announced that they would be standing their own candidates. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cOn [KEEP] 6 November, Reform UK announced their candidate as Kirsty Walmsley, who was previously a councillor on Shropshire Council for the Conservative Party, which her father Keith Barrow led on the Council. [KEEP] Walmsley said, "I would never had  [sic] stood against Owen Paterson. [KEEP] He is a man of integrity who had worked hard for North Shropshire." [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cOn [KEEP] 13 November, the Conservatives picked their candidate, Dr Neil Shastri-Hurst, from a three-person shortlist. [KEEP] Shastri-Hurst is a barrister, former British Army Medical Officer and honorary NHS consultant. [KEEP] His links to the constituency relate to his time training at Robert Jones and Agnes Hunt Orthopaedic Hospital near Oswestry and a period stationed at the Tern Hill barracks near Market Drayton. [KEEP] Also on the shortlist were local Shropshire Councillor for Worfield (in Ludlow constituency), Richard Marshall and Birmingham City Councillor Charlotte Hodivala. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\c [KEEP] The Shropshire Star reported Labour's shortlist for the candidacy included David Hallam (previously Herefordshire and Shropshire MEP), Kuldip Sahota (former Telford & Wrekin Council leader, who actually did not apply) and Graeme Currie (Labour candidate for North Shropshire at the 2019 general election). [KEEP] On 14 November, the Labour Party announced their candidate to be Ben Wood from Oswestry. [KEEP] Graeme Currie, the Labour candidate in the seat in the 2019 general election, was blocked from the party's shortlist of candidates and said he would resign from the party in response. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\c [KEEP] The Shropshire Star reported on 11 November that the Liberal Democrats had approached Martin Bell to stand as their candidate. [KEEP] Bell reportedly declined citing age and the size of the Conservative majority. [KEEP] Former Ludlow MP Matthew Green and Shropshire County Councillor Alex Wagner were also reported as potential candidates. [KEEP] On 16 November, the Liberal Democrats announced that Helen Morgan, who contested the seat in the 2019 general election, had been re-selected. [KEEP] Morgan is a chartered accountant who was born and raised in the rural West Midlands and has lived in North Shropshire since 2014. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\c [KEEP] The Green candidate was Duncan Kerr, who stood in the constituency for the party in the 2015 and 2017 general elections, but not in 2019. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cYolande Kenward stood on an anti-corruption platform as an independent, although she was shown on the ballot paper with no label. [KEEP] The other independent, Suzie Akers-Smith, is a independent councillor on Cheshire East Council and the local authority's Cycling and Walking Champion. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cDrew Galdron, under the name Boris Been-Bunged, a Boris Johnson impersonator, stood for the Rejoin EU Party. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cMonaco-based Russell Dean, a consultant for a yacht broker who grew up in Shropshire, stood for The Party Party. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cHard eurosceptic minor party candidates were: UKIP's Andrea Allen, a former modern languages teacher and the party's parish councillor and chair of the Whitchurch Town Twinning Association; the Reclaim Party's Martin Daubney who represented the West Midlands in the European Parliament between 2019 and 2020 while a member of the Brexit Party; and Heritage's James Elliot, an electrical contractor.\t\t\t <Candidates> \c\c [KEEP] The Monster Raving Loony party fielded its party leader Alan "Howling Laud" Hope. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\c [KEEP] The anti-lockdown Freedom Alliance fielded Earl Jesse as its candidate. [KEEP] <Candidates> \c\cAn editorial in The Guardian newspaper suggested that tactical voting for the Liberal Democrats be employed by the electorate to try to reduce the Conservative majority in the seat, saying "Labour voters ought to set aside their tribal loyalty and back the Lib Dem candidate". [KEEP] <Candidates - Endorsements> \c\cSarah Biffen, the widow of John Biffen, the former Conservative MP for the area, endorsed the Conservative candidate, Shastri-Hurst, comparing his background in the NHS and the Army with that of her late husband, a former cabinet minister who represented the area now covered by the North Shropshire constituency from 1961 until 1997. [KEEP] <Candidates - Endorsements> \c\cWill Hutton, former editor of The Observer, endorsed the Liberal Democrats and called on Labour and Green Party supporters to "put aside their prime party affiliation and back the Lib Dem candidate". [KEEP] Martin Fletcher, former associate editor and foreign editor of The Times, endorsed the Liberal Democrats, specifically calling on Conservative voters to back Morgan with the aim of ending Boris Johnson's leadership of the Conservative Party. [KEEP] <Candidates - Endorsements> \c\cSeveral[which?] candidates are running on an anti-corruption ticket; others are using it in their campaign material, including Labour's. [KEEP] Several local issues have also featured in the campaign, including local funding. [KEEP] Katy Balls in The Spectator analysed the effect that the variety of problems currently facing the government, and impacting Boris Johnson's popularity (which include tax rises, English Channel migrant crossings and the controversy surrounding the resignation of Paterson, the former MP of the constituency), might have on the election result. [KEEP] She said that a Lib Dem source commented that "Peppa Pig has come up more than sleaze" and that local issues such as the ambulance services, and questions over the Tory candidate being based in Birmingham were being raised by electors. [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\c [KEEP] The Financial Times reported that Labour strategists regarded North Shropshire inhospitable for their party and not worth spending resources on. [KEEP] One Labour strategist suggests the Liberal Democrats stood a better chance in the seat, saying: "the Lib Dems have focused on Shropshire North and they\'ll probably end up a good second there. [KEEP] They came second in the recent local elections — from their perspective it makes sense for them to concentrate their resources there." [KEEP] Labour finished second in the constituency at the 2019 United Kingdom general election. [KEEP] Ian Dunt, writing in the i, suggested that despite standing a candidate "[Labour] seems to be standing aside for Davey so the Lib Dems can monopolise the anti-government vote" as part of an informal Labour-Lib Dem pact, where one party stands aside to give the other a higher chance of beating the Conservative candidate. [KEEP] The Guardian reported that Labour's Shadow Minister for International Development Yasmin Qureshi "effectively acknowledged the party had deliberately left the field clear for the Lib Dems", after she told Times Radio that "Labour are never going to win North Shropshire. [KEEP] The Lib Dems do have an opportunity to do so." [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\cIn the wake of the Downing Street Christmas party controversy which broke on 7 December, The Guardian reported that opinion in the constituency was divided, and voter apathy had risen. [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\cA poll of postal voters by the Liberal Democrats, reported on 2 December, put them in second place, with both the Conservative and Labour vote shares falling relative to the 2019 general election. [KEEP] A polling analyst has said that these results should be treated "with a pinch of salt" because the polling methodology was not published. [KEEP] On 11 December The Observer reported that an internal memo to Liberal Democrat staff stated that the Conservatives were only one percentage point ahead of the Liberal Democrats. [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\cIn response to comments by the Conservative Home Secretary, Priti Patel, about the expulsion of migrants crossing the English Channel in small boats, the Liberal Democrat candidate, Helen Morgan, compared Patel with Hitler's propaganda chief Joseph Goebbels. [KEEP] Morgan later apologised for the "insensitive tweet which I have taken down". [KEEP] According to the Shropshire Star, Morgan had already apologised a few days earlier for comments from 2020 in which she "appeared to liken Channel migrants to Jews held at Auschwitz". [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\cDuring the campaign, a sitting Conservative Councillor in the constituency, Anthony Allen, announced that he was defecting from the Conservative Party, saying they "were not Conservative enough", and joined the Reclaim Party. [KEEP] A second sitting Conservative councillor defected to Reform UK. [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\cLocal newspaper the Shropshire Star reported on 8 December that bookmakers are divided over whether the Conservative or the Liberal Democrat candidate are the favourite to win the by-election, following controversy over a reported Christmas party at 10 Downing Street that may have broken the Covid-19 lockdown rules in place at the time. [KEEP] The newspaper stated that, other than the Liberal Democrats and the Conservatives, "No other party has been seen as a likely challenger to the seat". [KEEP] By 11 December The Independent reported that the Liberal Democrats were favourites with every major bookmaker. [KEEP] They also reported that the SARS-CoV-2 Omicron variant, and poor weather conditions may affect the turnout. [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\cOn 13 December it was reported that Reform Party candidate Kirsty Walmsley had tested positive for Coronavirus, and would therefore miss out on the last few days of the campaign as well as the vote count. [KEEP] <Campaign> \c\c
[KEEP] It is thought that a hole in the hull caused the engine room to flood, leaving the vessel vulnerable to wave action. [KEEP] At least 85 people died during the accident. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe Francia, a 12-metre (39 ft) -long wooden vessel, was a cargo ship that had illegally taken on 130 passengers for a journey from Antanambe (which is not registered as an official port) to Soanierana Ivongo, a journey of some 100 kilometres (62 mi). [KEEP] Including crew, 138 people were onboard. [KEEP] The vessel sank late on 20 December 2021 after its engine was flooded, leaving it exposed to the action of waves. [KEEP] The flooding was caused by a hole in the ship's hull. [KEEP] <Wreck> \c\cMadagascan police minister Serge Gellé was flown to the site of the shipwreck on 21 December. [KEEP] His helicopter crashed and he was one of two surviving passengers (the other was Chief Warrant Officer Jimmy Laitsara). [KEEP] The survivors separately reached land at Mahambo. [KEEP] Gellé used a seat from the helicopter as a flotation device during his twelve-hour overnight swim to safety. [KEEP] Gellé swam to within 500 metres (1,600 ft) of the shore but the waves prevented him from reaching land. [KEEP] He was spotted by a fisherman, whose canoe was too small to accommodate them both. [KEEP] The fisherman returned two hours later with a larger canoe and brought Gellé to dry land. [KEEP] The body of one of the helicopter's occupants, a police colonel, was later recovered; the pilot remains missing. [KEEP] <Aftermath - Helicopter crash> \c\cA separate helicopter carried the prime minister, Christian Ntsay, and minister of national defence, General Léon Richard Rakotonirina, to the site of the shipwreck. [KEEP] <Aftermath - Helicopter crash> \c\cA force of Madagascan gendarmes was sent to the site and an investigation into the sinking started by the Madagascan government. [KEEP] Three vessels from the Madagascan navy and maritime agency assisted in the search for survivors. [KEEP] By 22 December, 64 bodies had been recovered, with around 24 people missing and around 50 survivors rescued. [KEEP] The following day the Madagascan Maritime and Port Agency announced that the confirmed death toll had increased to 85, with three persons missing. [KEEP] <Aftermath - Responses> \c\cMadagascan president Andry Rajoelina paid tribute to those who died in the shipwreck and helicopter crash. [KEEP] The graveyard of Soanierana-Ivongo was too small to accommodate all the bodies recovered so some were sent to nearby villages for burial." [KEEP] } <Aftermath - Responses> \c\c
[KEEP] The COVID-19 pandemic in South Australia is part of the ongoing worldwide pandemic of the coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cOn 11 March, the SA state government announced its A$350 million economic stimulus measures. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn 15 March, a public health emergency was declared in South Australia. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn 22 March, a "major emergency" was declared, giving the police power to enforce self-isolation rules. [KEEP] People arriving in the state were required to sign a declaration that they would self-isolate for 14 days and provide an address to the police, with penalties for failure to comply. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] 27 March, a direction was made under the Emergency Management Act 2004 to prohibit gatherings of more than 10 people, and a limit of 1 person per four square metres. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn 8 November the SA government announced that in the state budget it would double it's coronavirus economic stimulus package to AU$4 billion. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] 16 November, "a number of significant restrictions" were reintroduced after an outbreak of coronavirus in the northern suburbs of Adelaide. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] 17 November, a six-day lockdown from midnight that day was announced. [KEEP] Afterwards there was to be another eight days of "significant restrictions" according to Police Commissioner Grant Stevens. [KEEP] On 21 November, Premier Steven Marshall announced that the state's "circuit breaker" restrictions would be ending three days earlier on 21 November after authorities discovered that one of the positive cases at the Woodville Pizza Bar coronavirus hotspot had misled contact tracers by concealing the fact that he worked at the shop. [KEEP] As part of the easing of "circuit breaker restrictions", groups of 50 people were allowed to attend private functions and funerals, ten people to attend private functions, and 100 people allowed to attend restaurants and pubs. [KEEP] <Timeline - Woodville outbreak> \c\cOn 12 February 2021, the World Solar Challenge (SWC) for that year was cancelled by the SA Government. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 5 March 2021, the first Australian received the Oxford-AstraZeneca vaccine. [KEEP] A doctor in regional South Australia, she was dosed at Murray Bridge Hospital. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 30 April, South Australia's first COVID-19 mass vaccination hub opened at Adelaide Showground. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cIn mid-June, sniffer dogs were deployed on a trial basis at Adelaide Airport to detect people with COVID-19 infections. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\c [KEEP] Due to a growing cluster in Bondi, Sydney, on 23 June South Australia "immediately" reinstated a hard border with NSW. [KEEP] No one who had been in NSW in the past 14 days was allowed entry to SA. [KEEP] A border buffer of 100 km was in place. [KEEP] Exemption were available for residents returning to SA, essential travellers, and special cases. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 28 June, from midnight, SA pre-emptively re-introduced a number of restrictions for at least 7 days: <Timeline - 2021> \c\cmasks mandatory in high-risk settings <Timeline - 2021> \c\caged care homes, <Timeline - 2021> \c\chospitals and other "personal care settings" [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cindoor entertainment venues <Timeline - 2021> \c\cnot required, but highly recommended on public transport <Timeline - 2021> \c\cIn licensed premises: [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cno "communal consumption" <Timeline - 2021> \c\cno buffets <Timeline - 2021> \c\crestrictions on sheisha venues <Timeline - 2021> \c\cSome restriction on singing. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn 11 July, a 72-year-old woman with thrombosis with thrombocytopenia syndrome (TTS) died in Royal Adelaide Hospital. [KEEP] She was vaccinated with AstraZeneca on 24 June, then admitted on 5 July. [KEEP] The restrictions were due to be reviewed on 23 July. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\c [KEEP] one [KEEP] person per four square metres <Timeline - 2021> \c\cprivate gatherings capped at 10 <Timeline - 2021> \c\cMasks required for: <Timeline - 2021> \c\chigh-risk settings <Timeline - 2021> \c\cpublic transport <Timeline - 2021> \c\cshared indoor spaces <Timeline - 2021> \c\cEvents requiring COVID management plans were cancelled. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn 20 July, from 6pm, South Australia went into lockdown for 7 days. [KEEP] This was after a 5 case cluster of the Delta variant emerged linked to Modbury Hospital. [KEEP] By this date, approximately 3,000 people were in quarantine at home. [KEEP] The only reasons to leave home were: <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\cessential work <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\ccare for someone <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\cpurchase essential goods-food, <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\cexercise <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\conly with people from the same household <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\cwithin 2.5 kilometres of home <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\c90 minutes per day maximum <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\chealthcare (including vaccination and COVID testing) [KEEP] <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\c [KEEP] The lockdown led to panic buying, and the cancellations of AVCon, the Royal Adelaide Show, the Adelaide Beer and Barbeque Festival, Winter Reds wine festival and the Illuminate Adelaide arts festival. [KEEP] The reopening of the Gawler railway line, originally set for November 2021, was also delayed to early 2022. [KEEP] <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\c [KEEP] The lockdown ended on 27 July. [KEEP] <Timeline - Lockdown> \c\cOn [KEEP] 23 November, after the state hit 80% vaccination coverage for 16 and older, it opened its borders to the rest of the country, including New South Wales, Victoria and the ACT. [KEEP] This signalled a change from an elimination strategy to a suppression strategy in controlling the virus. [KEEP] <Timeline - Suppression Phase> \c\cOn [KEEP] 1 December, the state recorded its first two cases of community transmission since the borders opened, two men aged in their 50s. [KEEP] The next day on 2 December, it recorded another 18 new cases, 16 linked to a high school reunion in Norwood, Adelaide. [KEEP] The cases included former premier Jay Weatherill. [KEEP] <Timeline - Suppression Phase> \c\cOn [KEEP] December 10, the Omicron variant was detected in two interstate travellers that came to South Australia. [KEEP] As a result, there were changes to the rules; travellers coming to SA from New South Wales and Victoria were now required to be tested on day 6 as well as on arrival. [KEEP] Several high-risk exposure sites were listed, where anyone who entered had to quarantine for 14 days. [KEEP] These restrictions were eased on December 14 and 15 respectively. [ADD] <Timeline - Omicron Variant> \c\cOn [ADD] December 26, after a week of exponentially rising case numbers, with over 80 percent believed to be caused by the Omicron variant, the government introduced new restrictions. [ADD] These included home gathering caps reduced from 30 to 10 people, and hospitality venues would have to reduce capacity to 25% indoors and 50% outdoors. [ADD] Citizens were asked to reduce travel around the state, as health authorities were concerned about the variants ability to overwhelm the health system. \c\c [KEEP] The Royal Adelaide Show for 2020 was announced as cancelled in April 2020. [KEEP] The 2021 event was also cancelled in response to border closures, the Delta variant, and the Modbury cluster. [KEEP] <Event cancellations> \c\cAVCon, Adelaide's main anime and gaming convention held annually in July at the Adelaide Convention Centre, did not go ahead in 2020 or 2021. [KEEP] The 2021 event, scheduled to be held at Morphettville Racecourse, was cancelled in response to the Modbury cluster.[citation needed] <Event cancellations> \c\cRiverland Field Day in Barmera was cancelled in 2020 and 2021. [KEEP] <Event cancellations> \c\cAdelaide's New Year's Eve fireworks at the end of 2020 were cancelled. [KEEP] <Event cancellations> \c\c [KEEP] The World Solar Challenge (WSC) was cancelled on 12 February 2021 by the SA Government. [KEEP] The next WSC should take place in October 2023. [KEEP] <Event cancellations> \c\c [KEEP] The Tour Down Under bicycle race was cancelled in both 2021 and 2022. [KEEP] <Event cancellations> \c\cOzAsia [KEEP] Festival was cancelled in 2020. [KEEP] In 2021 it went ahead from 21 October to 7 November, though some shows were cancelled due to COVID-19. [KEEP] <Event cancellations> \c\cCOVID-19 cumulative cases in South Australia <Statistics> \c\cCOVID-19 daily cases in South Australia <Statistics> \c\c
[KEEP] Beginning on 24 December 2021, record rainfall across the northeastern Brazilian state Bahia has resulted in severe floods. [KEEP] At least 20 people were killed, while 280 were injured and more than 35,000 were displaced. [KEEP] In a tweet, Rui Costa, the Governor of Bahia, has declared the floods to be "the worst disaster that has ever occurred in the history of Bahia". [KEEP] 72 municipalities of Bahia have declared a state of emergency. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cTotal rainfall at the state capital Salvador during December has exceeded 250 millimetres (9.8 inches) on 24 December, five times the historic average. [KEEP] On 26 December, the Bahia state government and Brazilian federal government, along with cooperation from other state governments, have mounted a joint rescue operation to victims at the affected areas. [KEEP] Two dams have collapsed between 25 and 26 December, at Jussiape and Itambe respectively. [ADD] The town of Vitória da
[KEEP] Cyberwarfare is a part of Iran's "soft war" military strategy. [KEEP] Being both a victim and wager of cyberwarfare, Iran is considered an emerging military power in the field. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cSince November 2010, an organization called "The Cyber Defense Command" (Persian: قرارگاه دفاع سایبری; Gharargah-e Defa-e Saiberi) has been operating in Iran under the supervision of the country's "Passive Civil Defense Organization" (Persian: سازمان پدافند غیرعامل; Sazeman-e Padafand-e Gheyr-e Amel) which is itself a subdivision of the Joint Staff of Iranian Armed Forces. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAccording to a 2014 report by Institute for National Security Studies, Iran is "one of the most active players in the international cyber arena". [KEEP] In 2013, a Revolutionary Guards general stated that Iran has "the 4th biggest cyber power among the world's cyber armies." [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAccording to a 2021 report by a cyber-security company, "Iran is running two surveillance operations in cyber-space, targeting more than 1,000 dissidents". [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cIranian cyber defense system - digital fortress part of national information network (national internet) - is developed for thwarting and attacks and  engage attackers. [KEEP] <NIN> \c\cIn June 2010, Iran was the victim of a cyber-attack when its nuclear facility in Natanz was infiltrated by the cyber-worm \'Stuxnet\'. [KEEP] Tehran's atomic programme back by at least two years." [KEEP] The worm spread beyond the plant to allegedly infect over 60,000 computers, but the government of Iran indicates it caused no significant damage. [KEEP] Iran crowdsourced solutions to the worm and is purportedly now better positioned in terms of cyber warfare technology. [KEEP] No government has claimed responsibility for the worm. [KEEP] The cyber-worm was also used against North Korea.[citation needed] <Attacks against Iran> \c\cIn October 2013, media reported Mojtaba Ahmadi, who served as commander of the "Cyber War Headquarters" was found dead wounded by bullets in Karaj. [KEEP] <Attacks against Iran - Events> \c\c November 2018: The Iranian telecommunication minister Mohammad-Javad Azari Jahromi accuses Israel of a failed cyberattack on its telecommunications infrastructure, and vows to respond with legal action. [KEEP] <Attacks against Iran - Events> \c\cIranian fuel 2021 cyberstrike <Attacks against Iran - Events> \c\c [KEEP] The Iranian government has been accused by western analysts of its own cyber-attacks against the United States, Israel and Persian Gulf Arab countries, but deny this, including specific allegations of 2012 involvement in hacking into American banks. [KEEP] The conflict between Iran and the United States has been called "history's first known cyber-war" by Michael Joseph Gross mid-2013. [KEEP] <Attacks by Iran> \c\c August 2014: An IDF official told press in that Iran has launched numerous significant attacks against Israel's Internet infrastructure. [KEEP] <Attacks by Iran - Events> \c\c 31 March 2015: There was a massive power outage for 12 hours in 44 of 81 provinces of Turkey, holding 40 million people. [KEEP] Istanbul and Ankara were among the places suffering blackout. [KEEP] According to Observer.com, Iranian hackers, possibly Iranian Cyber Army, were behind the power outage. [KEEP] <Attacks by Iran - Events> \c\c June 2017: The Daily Telegraph reported that intelligence officials concluded that Iran was responsible for a cyberattack on the British Parliament lasting 12 hours that compromised around 90 email accounts of MPs. [KEEP] The motive for the attack is unknown but experts suggested that the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps could be using cyberwarfare to undermine the Iran nuclear deal. [ADD] The website's content was replaced with a threat to target the Shimon Peres Negev Nuclear Research Center, and an apparent reference to Qasem Soleimani who was assassinated exactly two years earlier in Baghdad, Iraq. [KEEP] <Suspended Iranian accounts> \c\c [