[KEEP] The 2021—22 Russo-Ukrainian crisis is an ongoing military confrontation and international crisis between Russia and Ukraine that started in late October 2021. [KEEP] The crisis has caused international tension, also involving the United States, NATO, the European Union and the Commonwealth of Independent States. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe aggravation of Russian-Ukrainian relations occurred in late October – early November and was provoked by the first combat use of the Ukrainian Bayraktar TB2 UAV against the DPR formations. [KEEP] The message about the use of UAVs appeared almost simultaneously with the news about the occupation of the village of Staromarievka on the contact line of the parties, in which 37 Russian citizens who received passports under the simplified program live. [KEEP] According to OSCE observers, the ceasefire regime began to be violated twice as often as in 2020 (during the period from the evening of 29 October to the evening of 31 October, the ceasefire regime in the Donetsk region was violated 988 times, and in Luhansk — 471). [KEEP] OSCE SMM observers reported on the movement of military equipment of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, as well as repeated attempts to muffle the signal of its UAVs, which are used to monitor the terrain. [KEEP] At the same time, publications appeared in the Western media that Russia was again pulling troops to the Ukrainian border. [KEEP] Satellite photos of Russian armoured vehicles were cited as evidence. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn [KEEP] 2–3 November, the head of the CIA, William Burns, came to Moscow and met with senior Russian intelligence officials there. [KEEP] According to CNN, the purpose of the trip was to convey to the Kremlin Joe Biden's concern about the situation on the border with Ukraine. [KEEP] Sources of the TV channel reported that after the trip, Burns spoke by phone with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky to ease tensions between Moscow and Kyiv. [KEEP] For the same purpose, a high-ranking official of the US State Department was sent to Ukraine on 4 November. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe military aggravation was accompanied by aggravation in the Ukrainian political field. [KEEP] On 2 November, Dmytro Yarosh, the former leader of the Right Sector organization, was appointed adviser to the Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine Valery Zaluzhny. [KEEP] On 4 November, a new defence minister was approved — former Deputy Prime Minister – Minister for the Reintegration of Temporarily Occupied Territories Oleksii Reznikov, who participated in the meetings of the Trilateral Contact Group on behalf of Ukraine. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cIn November 2021, the Russian Defense Ministry described the deployment of the U.S. warships to the Black Sea as a "threat to regional security and strategic stability." [KEEP] The ministry said in a statement, "The real goal behind the U.S. activities in the Black Sea region is exploring the theatre of operations in case Kyiv attempts to settle the conflict in the southeast by force." [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn [KEEP] 13 November, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky announced that Russia has again amassed 100,000 troops in the border area. [KEEP] In early November, reports of Russian military buildups prompted U.S. officials to warn the EU that Russia could be planning a potential invasion of Ukraine. [KEEP] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov denied allegations that Russia is preparing for a possible invasion of Ukraine. [KEEP] He accused Ukraine of "planning aggressive actions against Donbass." [KEEP] Peskov urged NATO to stop "concentrating a military fist" near Russia's borders and to stop arming Ukraine with modern weapons. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn [KEEP] 16 November, NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg called on the West to send Russia "a clear signal calling for reducing tension, avoiding any escalation in and around Ukraine." [KEEP] Stoltenberg added that the alliance records an "unusual concentration" of Russian forces near the Ukrainian border. [KEEP] On 15 November, Acting German Foreign Minister Heiko Maas and French Foreign Minister Jean-Yves Le Drian expressed concern in a joint communique about "the movements of Russian forces and military equipment near Ukraine," calling on both sides to "show restraint." [KEEP] At the same time, Pentagon Press Secretary John Kirby confirmed that the United States continues to observe "unusual military activity" of the Russian Federation near the borders of Ukraine, and the head of the State Department Antony Blinken discussed reports of "Russian military activity" in the area with Jean-Yves Le Drian. [KEEP] It was reported that the United States is discussing sanctions with European allies in case of further Russian invasion <Diplomatic response> \c\cBack in early November, Ukrainian intelligence stated that information about the transfer of additional Russian troops to the Ukrainian borders was nothing more than "an element of psychological pressure." [KEEP] However, a week later, the Office of the President of Ukraine recognized that the Russian Federation was strengthening "specific groups of troops" near the border. [KEEP] Ukrainian Foreign Minister Dmytro Kuleba urged Paris and Berlin to prepare for a possible military scenario of Russia's actions in the Ukrainian direction. [KEEP] <Diplomatic response> \c\cAgainst this background, Ukraine has sharply intensified diplomatic efforts. [KEEP] On 15 November, Volodymyr Zelensky and the head of the European Council Charles Michel discussed "the security situation along the borders of Ukraine." [KEEP] On the same day, Dmytro Kuleba held talks on the same issues in Brussels. [KEEP] The new head of the Defense Ministry, Oleksii Rezikov, went to Washington, where on 18 November he met with US Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin. [KEEP] On 16 November, British Defense Minister Ben Wallace visited Kyiv. [KEEP] According to the tabloid Daily Mirror, a consolidated rapid response unit of about 600 fighters has been formed in the UK for transfer to Ukraine. [KEEP] <Diplomatic response> \c\cOn [KEEP] 28 December, U.S. and Russia announced bilateral talks would take place in Geneva on 10 January 2022, to discuss concerns about their respective military activity and to confront rising tensions over Ukraine. [KEEP] The talks would be led by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister, Sergei Ryabkov and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State, Wendy Sherman. [KEEP] <Security talks (January 2022)> \c\cIn addition to the Geneva talks, it was announced that Russia would hold talks with NATO in Brussels on 12 January 2022. [KEEP] On 13 January 2022, a broader meeting involving the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) would take place in Vienna. [KEEP] <Security talks (January 2022)> \c\cOn [KEEP] 21 November, the head of the Main Intelligence Directorate of the Ministry of Defense of Ukraine, Kyrylo Budanov, reported that Russia allegedly concentrated more than 92,000 troops and Iskander short-range ballistic missile systems near the Ukrainian borders. [KEEP] Budanov said that Russia is behind the protests against vaccination against COVID-19 in Kyiv and other protest rallies in Ukraine – this is a preparation for a large-scale military invasion. [KEEP] According to Budanov, Russia needs the protests so that the Ukrainian population does not resist it during the military operation, believing that the Ukrainian authorities have betrayed it: "They want to organize rallies and protests to show that people are against the government," he said in an interview with Military Times. [KEEP] "They are trying to prove that our government is betraying the people." [KEEP] According to the head of Ukrainian intelligence, Russia is trying to get the Ukrainians to change power themselves, and if it doesn\'t work out, "the army will step in." [KEEP] According to Budanov, active actions should be expected in late January – early February 2022. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cMoscow, in turn, accuses Ukraine of aggressive actions. [KEEP] The official representative of the Russian Foreign Ministry, Maria Zakharova, said on 25 November that the Ukrainian authorities are escalating tensions in the Donbas and are conducting offensive actions there in some areas: "The hotheads of the Kiev regime, apparently feeling complete impunity, advocate a forceful solution to the internal Ukrainian crisis. [KEEP] The situation in the conflict zone is escalating. [KEEP] Information continues to be received about the use of weapons prohibited by the Minsk Package of Measures, which are supplied to Ukraine by NATO countries." [KEEP] She believes that by doing so, the Ukrainian leadership is trying to "divert attention from the degradation of the socio-economic and political situation in the country ... and switch this attention to some temporary threats from outside." [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cHarsh statements from Kyiv and Moscow sound against the background of a deadlock on all existing negotiating platforms. [KEEP] There are no contacts within the Normandy Format and are not expected at any level: there will be no summit, the foreign ministers have not yet been able to coordinate a meeting, and political advisers have not communicated since September. [KEEP] In the Trilateral Contact Group, negotiations are reduced to discussing whether Russia is a party to the conflict. [KEEP] On 15 November, Vladimir Putin signed a decree on providing humanitarian support to the population of certain areas of the Donetsk and Luhansk regions of Ukraine. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cOn [KEEP] 1 December, Russia accused Ukraine of deploying half its army – about 125,000 troops – in Donbas to confront pro-Russian separatists. [KEEP] On 3 December, President Putin criticized Ukraine for using a Turkish-made Bayraktar TB2 drone against pro-Russian separatists in Donbas, saying the move violated the Minsk peace agreements. [KEEP] On 3 December, the Minister of Defense of Ukraine Olexii Reznikov, speaking to the deputies of the Verkhovna Rada, said: "There is a possibility of a large-scale escalation on the part of Russia. [KEEP] The most likely time to achieve readiness for escalation will be the end of January." [KEEP] Additional Russian forces were reported to have moved into Crimea reinforcing Russian naval and ground units already deployed there. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cOn [KEEP] 9 December, Russia accused Ukraine of moving heavy artillery towards the front line where separatists are fighting with Ukrainian forces. [KEEP] Chief of the Russian General Staff, Valery Gerasimov, stated that [NATO's] "Deliveries of helicopters, unmanned aerial vehicles and aeroplanes to Ukraine are pushing the Ukrainian authorities to take sharp and dangerous steps. [KEEP] Any provocations of the Ukrainian authorities by way of a forced settlement of the problems of Donbass will be suppressed." [KEEP] On 31 December 2021, after a phone call between US President Biden and Russian president Putin, Putin declared that if the US sanctioned them it would be "a fatal mistake." [ADD] <Military escalation> \c\cOn 10 January 2022, the Ukrainian government announced that it had arrested an alleged Russian military intelligence agent who was attempting to recruit others to conduct attacks in the Ukrainian city of Odessa.
[KEEP] The 2021—22 Russo-Ukrainian crisis is an ongoing military confrontation and international crisis between Russia and Ukraine that started in late October 2021. [KEEP] The crisis has caused international tension, also involving the United States, NATO, the European Union and the Commonwealth of Independent States. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe aggravation of Russian-Ukrainian relations occurred in late October – early November and was provoked by the first combat use of the Ukrainian Bayraktar TB2 UAV against the DPR formations. [KEEP] The message about the use of UAVs appeared almost simultaneously with the news about the occupation of the village of Staromarievka on the contact line of the parties, in which 37 Russian citizens who received passports under the simplified program live. [KEEP] According to OSCE observers, the ceasefire regime began to be violated twice as often as in 2020 (during the period from the evening of 29 October to the evening of 31 October, the ceasefire regime in the Donetsk region was violated 988 times, and in Luhansk — 471). [KEEP] OSCE SMM observers reported on the movement of military equipment of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, as well as repeated attempts to muffle the signal of its UAVs, which are used to monitor the terrain. [KEEP] At the same time, publications appeared in the Western media that Russia was again pulling troops to the Ukrainian border. [KEEP] Satellite photos of Russian armoured vehicles were cited as evidence. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn [KEEP] 2–3 November, the head of the CIA, William Burns, came to Moscow and met with senior Russian intelligence officials there. [KEEP] According to CNN, the purpose of the trip was to convey to the Kremlin Joe Biden's concern about the situation on the border with Ukraine. [KEEP] Sources of the TV channel reported that after the trip, Burns spoke by phone with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky to ease tensions between Moscow and Kyiv. [KEEP] For the same purpose, a high-ranking official of the US State Department was sent to Ukraine on 4 November. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cThe military aggravation was accompanied by aggravation in the Ukrainian political field. [KEEP] On November 2, Dmytro Yarosh, the former leader of the Right Sector organization, was appointed adviser to the Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces of Ukraine Valery Zaluzhny. [KEEP] On 4 November, a new defence minister was approved — former Deputy Prime Minister – Minister for the Reintegration of Temporarily Occupied Territories Oleksii Reznikov, who participated in the meetings of the Trilateral Contact Group on behalf of Ukraine. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cIn November 2021, the Russian Defense Ministry described the deployment of the U.S. warships to the Black Sea as a "threat to regional security and strategic stability." [KEEP] The ministry said in a statement, "The real goal behind the U.S. activities in the Black Sea region is exploring the theatre of operations in case Kyiv attempts to settle the conflict in the southeast by force." [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn [KEEP] 13 November, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky announced that Russia has again amassed 100,000 troops in the border area. [KEEP] In early November, reports of Russian military buildups prompted U.S. officials to warn the EU that Russia could be planning a potential invasion of Ukraine. [KEEP] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov denied allegations that Russia is preparing for a possible invasion of Ukraine. [KEEP] He accused Ukraine of "planning aggressive actions against Donbass." [KEEP] Peskov urged NATO to stop "concentrating a military fist" near Russia's borders and to stop arming Ukraine with modern weapons. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn [KEEP] 16 November, NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg called on the West to send Russia "a clear signal calling for reducing tension, avoiding any escalation in and around Ukraine." [KEEP] Stoltenberg added that the alliance records an "unusual concentration" of Russian forces near the Ukrainian border. [KEEP] On 15 November, Acting German Foreign Minister Heiko Maas and French Foreign Minister Jean-Yves Le Drian expressed concern in a joint communique about "the movements of Russian forces and military equipment near Ukraine," calling on both sides to "show restraint." [KEEP] At the same time, Pentagon Press Secretary John Kirby confirmed that the United States continues to observe "unusual military activity" of the Russian Federation near the borders of Ukraine, and the head of the State Department Antony Blinken discussed reports of "Russian military activity" in the area with Jean-Yves Le Drian. [KEEP] It was reported that the United States is discussing sanctions with European allies in case of further Russian invasion <Diplomatic response> \c\cBack in early November, Ukrainian intelligence stated that information about the transfer of additional Russian troops to the Ukrainian borders was nothing more than "an element of psychological pressure." [KEEP] However, a week later, the Office of the President of Ukraine recognized that the Russian Federation was strengthening "specific groups of troops" near the border. [KEEP] Ukrainian Foreign Minister Dmytro Kuleba urged Paris and Berlin to prepare for a possible military scenario of Russia's actions in the Ukrainian direction. [KEEP] <Diplomatic response> \c\cAgainst this background, Ukraine has sharply intensified diplomatic efforts. [KEEP] On 15 November, Volodymyr Zelensky and the head of the European Council Charles Michel discussed "the security situation along the borders of Ukraine." [KEEP] On the same day, Dmytro Kuleba held talks on the same issues in Brussels. [KEEP] The new head of the Defense Ministry, Oleksii Rezikov, went to Washington, where on 18 November he met with US Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin. [KEEP] On 16 November, British Defense Minister Ben Wallace visited Kyiv. [KEEP] According to the tabloid Daily Mirror, a consolidated rapid response unit of about 600 fighters has been formed in the UK for transfer to Ukraine. [KEEP] <Diplomatic response> \c\cOn [KEEP] 28 December, U.S. and Russia announced bilateral talks would take place in Geneva on 10 January 2022, to discuss concerns about their respective military activity and to confront rising tensions over Ukraine. [KEEP] The talks (′′the extraordinary meeting of the Strategic Stability Dialogue") were led by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister, Sergei Ryabkov, and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State, Wendy Sherman. [KEEP] <Security talks (January 2022)> \c\c [KEEP] The Geneva meeting was followed by a meeting of the NATO–Russia Council in Brussels on 12 January 2022 that brought together all 30 NATO Allies and Russia to discuss, according to the official statement issued by NATO, ′′the situation in and around Ukraine, and the implications for European security′′; the Russian minisrty of defence′ statement following the meeting said, "[Russia] brought Russian assessments of the current state in the field of euro-security, and also gave explanations on the military aspects of the Russian draft agreement on security guarantees. [KEEP] <Security talks (January 2022)> \c\cOn \c\c [ADD] The talks were judged by Russia to be unsuccessful. [KEEP] Budanov said that Russia is behind the protests against vaccination against COVID-19 in Kyiv and other protest rallies in Ukraine – this is a preparation for a large-scale military invasion. [KEEP] According to Budanov, Russia needs the protests so that the Ukrainian population does not resist it during the military operation, believing that the Ukrainian authorities have betrayed it: "They want to organize rallies and protests to show that people are against the government," he said in an interview with Military Times. [KEEP] "They are trying to prove that our government is betraying the people." [KEEP] According to the head of Ukrainian intelligence, Russia is trying to get the Ukrainians to change power themselves, and if it doesn\'t work out, "the army will step in." [KEEP] According to Budanov, active actions should be expected in late January – early February 2022. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cMoscow, in turn, accuses Ukraine of aggressive actions. [KEEP] The official representative of the Russian Foreign Ministry, Maria Zakharova, said on 25 November that the Ukrainian authorities are escalating tensions in the Donbas and are conducting offensive actions there in some areas: "The hotheads of the Kiev regime, apparently feeling complete impunity, advocate a forceful solution to the internal Ukrainian crisis. [KEEP] The situation in the conflict zone is escalating. [KEEP] Information continues to be received about the use of weapons prohibited by the Minsk Package of Measures, which are supplied to Ukraine by NATO countries." [KEEP] She believes that by doing so, the Ukrainian leadership is trying to "divert attention from the degradation of the socio-economic and political situation in the country ... and switch this attention to some temporary threats from outside." [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cHarsh statements from Kyiv and Moscow sound against the background of a deadlock on all existing negotiating platforms. [KEEP] There are no contacts within the Normandy Format and are not expected at any level: there will be no summit, the foreign ministers have not yet been able to coordinate a meeting, and political advisers have not communicated since September. [KEEP] In the Trilateral Contact Group, negotiations are reduced to discussing whether Russia is a party to the conflict. [KEEP] On 15 November, Vladimir Putin signed a decree on providing humanitarian support to the population of certain areas of the Donetsk and Luhansk regions of Ukraine. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cOn [KEEP] 1 December, Russia accused Ukraine of deploying half its army – about 125,000 troops – in Donbas to confront pro-Russian separatists. [KEEP] On 3 December, President Putin criticized Ukraine for using a Turkish-made Bayraktar TB2 drone against pro-Russian separatists in Donbas, saying the move violated the Minsk peace agreements. [KEEP] On 3 December, the Minister of Defense of Ukraine Olexii Reznikov, speaking to the deputies of the Verkhovna Rada, said: "There is a possibility of a large-scale escalation on the part of Russia. [KEEP] The most likely time to achieve readiness for escalation will be the end of January." [KEEP] Additional Russian forces were reported to have moved into Crimea reinforcing Russian naval and ground units already deployed there. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cOn [KEEP] 9 December, Russia accused Ukraine of moving heavy artillery towards the front line where separatists are fighting with Ukrainian forces. [KEEP] Chief of the Russian General Staff, Valery Gerasimov, stated that [NATO's] "Deliveries of helicopters, unmanned aerial vehicles and aeroplanes to Ukraine are pushing the Ukrainian authorities to take sharp and dangerous steps. [KEEP] Any provocations of the Ukrainian authorities by way of a forced settlement of the problems of Donbass will be suppressed." [KEEP] On 31 December 2021, after a phone call between US President Biden and Russian president Putin, Putin declared that if the US sanctioned them it would be "a fatal mistake." [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\cOn 10 January 2022, the Ukrainian government announced that it had arrested an alleged Russian military intelligence agent who was attempting to recruit others to conduct attacks in the Ukrainian city of Odessa. [KEEP] <Military escalation> \c\c
[KEEP] The 2022 Australian Open is a scheduled Grand Slam tennis tournament that is scheduled to take place at Melbourne Park, from 17–30 January 2022. [KEEP] It will be the 110th edition of the Australian Open, the 54th in the Open Era, and the first Grand Slam of the year. [KEEP] The tournament will consist of events for professional players in singles, doubles and mixed doubles. [KEEP] Junior and wheelchair players will compete in singles and doubles tournaments. [KEEP] As in previous years, the tournament's main sponsor is Kia. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cNovak Djokovic and Naomi Osaka are the defending champions in Men's Singles and Women's Singles, respectively. [KEEP] Djokovic may be unable to defend the title because his Australian visa was refused by the Australian Border Force upon entering the country on 5 January 2022. [KEEP] Similarly, Renata Voráčová was deported on 8 January 2022 after her visa was cancelled on 7 January 2022. [KEEP] Djokovic appealed the visa refusal and the Federal Circuit and Family Court ruled in favour of Djokovic, ordered his release from detention and directed the federal government to pay his legal expenses. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe 2022 Australian Open is the 110th edition of the tournament, held at Melbourne Park in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia. [KEEP] <Tournament> \c\cThe tournament is run by the International Tennis Federation (ITF) and is part of the 2022 ATP Tour and the 2022 WTA Tour calendars under the Grand Slam category. [KEEP] The tournament consists of both men's and women's singles and doubles draws as well as the mixed doubles events. [KEEP] There are singles and doubles events for both boys and girls (players under 18), which are part of the Grade A category of tournaments. [KEEP] The junior competitions will be returned after a year of absence. [KEEP] There are also singles, doubles and quad events for men's and women's wheelchair tennis players as part of the NEC tour under the Grand Slam category. [KEEP] <Tournament> \c\cThe tournament is played on hard courts and will take place across a series of 25 courts, including the four main show courts of Rod Laver Arena, John Cain Arena, Margaret Court Arena and 1573 Arena. [KEEP] It is also the debut of Kia Arena, which now makes five main tennis arenas. [KEEP] <Tournament> \c\cBelow is a series of tables for each of the competitions showing the ranking points offered for each event. [KEEP] <Point distribution and prize money - Point distribution> \c\c [KEEP] The Australian Open total prize money for 2022 increased by 4.5% to a tournament record A$75,000,000. [KEEP] <Point distribution and prize money - Wheelchair points> \c\c1Qualifiers prize money was also the Round of 128 prize money. [KEEP] <Point distribution and prize money - Junior points> \c\c*per team <Point distribution and prize money - Prize money> \c\cOn 4 January 2022, defending champion Novak Djokovic announced that he could compete in the Australian Open after he had been granted medical exemption from mandatory COVID-19 vaccination by Tennis Australia and the health department of the state of Victoria, after a blind review of his application. [KEEP] However, the Australian Minister for Home Affairs, Karen Andrews, stated that regardless of Tennis Australia and Victoria's decision, Australia's "border requirements" would be still enforced by the federal government, that unvaccinated individuals entering Australia "must provide acceptable proof that they cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons". [KEEP] <Point distribution and prize money - Prize money> \c\cOn 5 January, Djokovic was detained by the Australian Border Force upon arriving in Australia as his visa did not meet the country's entry requirements for unvaccinated travellers. [KEEP] His lawyers requested an injunction against deportation in order to appeal the visa refusal; this allowed Djokovic to remain confined in a detention hotel pending the outcome of the appeal. [KEEP] On 10 January, the Federal Circuit and Family Court ruled in favour of Djokovic, ordered his release from detention and directed the federal government to pay his legal expenses. [KEEP] The reason for the ruling was that when Djokovic was in immigration holding before his visa was cancelled, Australian officials reneged on an agreement to give Djokovic sufficient time to contact his lawyers and tennis authorities before his official interview; this led the Australian government to concede that they treated Djokovic unreasonably. [KEEP] <COVID-19 vaccination and visa controversies> \c\cTwenty-five other players and staff had applied for a medical exemption and a handful of applications had been granted. [KEEP] Among those, two people with the same type of visa and exemption as Djokovic had reportedly been allowed into the country. [KEEP] Player Renata Voráčová, who was one of those granted an exemption, was allowed into the country and participated in a warm-up tournament but was subsequently detained in the same hotel as Djokovic and deported on 8 January 2022. [KEEP] A tennis official with an exemption was also allowed entry but left the country voluntarily. [KEEP] <COVID-19 vaccination and visa controversies> \c\cPublic opinion in Australia of an unvaccinated athlete being permitted entry while many Australians remain stranded overseas due to the pandemic, in order to participate in an event that spectators cannot attend unless fully vaccinated, has been overwhelmingly negative. [ADD] <COVID-19 vaccination and visa controversies> \c\cOn 14 January 2022, Alex Hawke, the Australian Minister for Immigration, Citizenship, Migrant Services and Multicultural Affairs, exercised his ministerial powers under the Migration Act to cancel Djokovic's visa, citing "health and good order grounds, on the basis that it was in the public interest to do so".
[KEEP] On January 15, 2022, an armed gunman took multiple people hostage at Congregation Beth Israel, a Jewish synagogue in Colleyville, Texas, United States. [RM] After more than 12 hours, the four hostages were freed. [ADD] After more than 12 hours, the four hostages were freed and the attacker is dead. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cCongregation [KEEP] Beth Israel is a Reform Judaism synagogue located in Colleyville, Texas, a suburb in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex. [KEEP] The synagogue was opened in 1999 with 25 families and a religious school with 75 children. [KEEP] The synagogue's Rabbi is Charlie Cytron-Walker, who is originally from Lansing, Michigan. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cAt 10:41 a.m., a gunman entered the Congregation Beth Israel and began taking hostages. [KEEP] The assailant entered by posing as a homeless man in need of shelter. [KEEP] Reports of hostages being taken at Congregation Beth Israel came in around 11:30 a.m. via a tweet from the Colleyville Police Department. [KEEP] The police said the SWAT team was on the scene. [KEEP] Police efforts were later assisted by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the Texas Department of Public Safety. [KEEP] Law enforcement evacuated neighborhoods in the vicinity of the crime scene. [KEEP] <Hostage crisis> \c\cA livestream of the synagogue's services showed the ongoing situation, including the taking of hostages. [KEEP] Four hostages, including Charlie Cytron-Walker, the synagogue's rabbi, were taken during the middle of a bar mitzvah. [KEEP] In it, the hostage taker could be seen speaking to authorities, who attempted to negotiate with him. [KEEP] The man, who was armed, could be heard saying "If anyone tries to enter this building, I’m telling you...everyone will die." [KEEP] and "I\'m going to die. [KEEP] Don\'t cry about me..." One member of the synagogue, who was listening to the synagogue's livestream, stated that she heard him speak using anti-Israel epithets. [KEEP] <Hostage crisis> \c\cShortly after 5:00 p.m., the Colleyville Police Department released a statement that one of the hostages was released safely and was not in need of medical attention. [KEEP] At 9:21 p.m., James Hartley of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported hearing "what sounds like gunshots and a much louder bang, possibly a flash grenade" from the synagogue. [KEEP] After more than 12 hours of the synagogue being under siege, Texas Governor Greg Abbott put out a statement via Twitter reading "Prayers answered. [KEEP] All hostages are out alive and safe." [KEEP] <Hostage crisis> \c\cMultiple news agencies reported that the assailant has claimed to be the brother of Aafia Siddiqui, a Pakistani national who in 2010 was convicted of the attempted murder of a United States Army captain while in Afghan custody. [KEEP] However, a former lawyer for her only biological brother, Muhammad, said that he had no involvement with the attack. [KEEP] Law enforcement has not identified the assailant. [KEEP] The hostage taker demanded to have Siddiqui released as part of his negotiations. [KEEP] <Negotiations> \c\c [KEEP] The assailant had Rabbi Cytron-Walker call a New York City–based rabbi to pass along his demand that Aafia Siddiqui be released. [ADD] Congresswoman Beth Van Duyne told reporters with the Fort Worth Star-Telegram that the attacker is confirmed to be dead. \c\c [KEEP] The White House stated that they[clarification needed] were actively monitoring the situation. [KEEP] Yair Lapid, the Alternate Prime Minister of Israel, said that Livia Link, the Israeli Consulate General located in Houston, Texas was on her way to the scene and that the Israeli government was in contact with American law enforcement. [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\c [KEEP] The attorney who currently represents Aafia Siddiqui said "she has absolutely no involvement with [the hostage crisis]." [KEEP] The attorney stated that "We strongly condemn the hostage-taking at Congregation Beth Israel in Colleyville" and "We implore the hostage taker to immediately release all hostages and turn himself in." [KEEP] <Reactions> \c\c
[KEEP] A large eruption of Hunga Tonga, a volcanic island in Tonga in the Pacific Ocean, occurred on 15 January 2022. [KEEP] The eruption caused tsunamis in Tonga, Fiji and American Samoa; tsunami warnings were issued in Fiji, Samoa, Vanuatu, New Zealand, Australia, Japan, the United States, Canada, Chile and Ecuador. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cAfter being relatively inactive since 2014, the Hunga Tonga volcano erupted on 20 December 2021, sending particulates into the stratosphere, and a large plume of ash was visible from Nukuʻalofa, the capital city of Tonga, about 70 kilometres (43 mi) from the volcano. [KEEP] The Volcanic Ash Advisory Center (VAAC) in Wellington, New Zealand, issued an advisory notice to airlines. [KEEP] Explosions were heard up to 170 kilometres (110 mi) away. [KEEP] This initial eruption ended at 02:00 on 21 December. [KEEP] Volcanic activity continued, and on 25 December, the island had increased in size on satellite imagery. [KEEP] As activity on the island decreased, it was declared dormant on 11 January 2022. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cA large eruption began on 14 January sending clouds of ash 20 kilometres (12 mi) into the atmosphere. [KEEP] The government of Tonga issued a tsunami warning to residents. [KEEP] Tongan geologists near the volcano observed explosions and a 5-kilometre (3.1 mi) wide ash column. [KEEP] <Eruptions> \c\c [KEEP] The following day, a significantly larger eruption occurred at approximately 17:00 (04:00 UTC). [KEEP] The VAAC again issued an advisory notice to airlines. [KEEP] Ash from the eruption made landfall on the main island of Tongatapu, blotting out the sun. [KEEP] Loud explosions were heard 40 miles (65 km) away in Nukuʻalofa, and small stones and ash rained down from the sky. [KEEP] Many residents in Tonga were stuck in traffic while attempting to flee to higher ground. [KEEP] The explosion was heard as far away as Samoa, roughly 520 miles (840 km) away. [KEEP] Residents in Fiji described the sounds of thunder. [KEEP] Booms were heard in the North Island of New Zealand and as far away as the east coast of Australia. [KEEP] From space, a very wide eruption column and shockwaves were captured propagating across the Pacific by satellites. [KEEP] The pressure wave was measured by weather stations throughout New Zealand at a maximum amplitude of about 7 hPa. [KEEP] The pressure wave was also recorded by weather stations in Australia. [KEEP] The United States Geological Survey registered the eruption at a surface-wave magnitude of 5.8. [KEEP] A pressure fluctuation of 2.5 hPa was measured in Switzerland. [KEEP] <Eruptions> \c\cPreliminary observations showed that the eruption column ejected a large amount of volcanic material into the stratosphere. [KEEP] The eruption has potential to cause a temporary climate effect. [KEEP] A scientist from the University of Auckland described it as a one-in-1000-year event. [KEEP] <Eruptions> \c\cLittle information is yet available on the extent of damage and casualties from Tonga due to communication issues. [KEEP] Video footage showing waves hitting coastal areas in Tonga was reported by Sky News. [KEEP] Atata, a small island off the capital city was reportedly submerged and rescue operations are being carried out. [KEEP] There are some reports of residents in Tonga struggling to breathe as a result of the ash. [KEEP] The Tonga government has not confirmed any casualties from the eruption and tsunami. [ADD] <Impact> \c\cThe tsunami claimed the lives of two women in Peru when a 2-meter wave struck them at Naylamp beach, Lambayeque. [ADD] The two women were in a truck along with a driver; the husband of one of the woman. [ADD] When the wave struck, the male occupant escaped. [ADD] The bodies of the female victims were taken to a morgue. [KEEP] According to a resident in the Tongan capital, a series of initial smaller explosions were heard. [KEEP] It was followed by a tsunami approximately 15 minutes later. [KEEP] The first wave was said to be the largest. [KEEP] A long white wave was observed out at sea approaching the coast. [KEEP] Three waves reportedly struck the coast. [KEEP] In the wake of the tsunami King Tupou VI was evacuated and traffic jams formed as locals fled to high ground. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Oceania> \c\cIn [KEEP] Fiji, a tidal gauge in Suva recorded a wave measuring 20 centimetres (8 in) at 17:40 local time. [KEEP] Some tsunami activity was also reported in the Lau Islands. [KEEP] The islands of Moce, Moala, Kadavu and Taveuni were struck by low-level tsunami that triggered flooding. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Oceania> \c\cIn American Samoa, a tsunami measuring 0.61 metres (2 ft) was recorded by tide gauges. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Oceania> \c\c"Destructive" tsunami waves of 1–2.5 metres (3 ft 3 in – 8 ft 2 in) were observed in several islands in Vanuatu. [KEEP] The Vanuatu Meteorology & Geo-hazards Department said tsunami activity is expected to persist for the night of 15 January 2022. [KEEP] Waves up to 0.8 metres (2.6 ft) in height were recorded in Hanalei, Hawaii. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Oceania> \c\c [KEEP] The tsunami sank several boats and ripped others off their moorings at a marina in Tutukaka in New Zealand. [KEEP] The waves took boats out into the bay and smashed some together. [KEEP] Debris from boats and polystyrene was reported. [KEEP] Civil Defence Northland said that damage at the marina was "serious". [KEEP] According to Hauraki Gulf Weather, the tsunami struck on 16 January at between 01.05 and 01.10 local time on Great Barrier Island with a height of 1.33 meters. [KEEP] The tsunami caused flooding at Mahinepua Bay where a campsite was located but all 50 individuals at the site were safe. [KEEP] There were no casualties reported in New Zealand. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Oceania> \c\cIn Australia, the Bureau of Meteorology said tsunami waves were observed on the shores along the east coast of Australia. [KEEP] Maximum tsunami waves of 1.27 m (4.2 ft) was recorded at Norfolk Island, 1.10 m (3.6 ft) at Lord Howe Island, 0.82 m (2.7 ft) at the Gold Coast, Queensland, 0.77 m (2.5 ft) at Twofold Bay, New South Wales and 0.50 m (1.6 ft) at Hobart, Tasmania. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Oceania> \c\cIn Kominato, Amami, Kagoshima, Japan, a 1.2-metre (3 ft 11 in) tsunami was reported at 23:55 JST. [KEEP] At Tosashimizu, Kōchi, the tsunami was 0.9 metres (2 ft 11 in) in height. [KEEP] A tsunami measuring 0.9 metres (2 ft 11 in) was also reported in Chichijima Futami. [KEEP] On the Tohoku coast, a 0.7-metre (2 ft 4 in) wave struck at 00:38 local time, 16 January. [KEEP] In the Sendai Port, the tsunami measured 0.9 metres (2 ft 11 in) at 00:08. [KEEP] In Iwate Prefecture, a 1.1-metre  tsunami was recorded at 02:26 on January 16. [KEEP] Tsunami waves of less than a meter was reported along the Hokkaido Pacific coast. [KEEP] This was the nation's first tsunami warning since the 2016 Fukushima earthquake. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Asia> \c\cSignificant tsunami waves were reported hitting the Santa Cruz Harbor in California during Saturday morning. [KEEP] Strong currents in Half Moon Bay were reported in a tweet by the official San Mateo-Santa Cruz Fire Department account. [KEEP] Waves up to 0.37 metres (1.2 ft) in height were recorded in Nikolski, Alaska. [KEEP] On the Mexican coasts of the states of Guerrero, Colima and Baja California Peninsula, sea level rise was reported with waves of 0.30 metres (1 ft) to 0.61 metres (2 ft). [KEEP] The NWS reported a minor tsunami surge measuring 0.76 m (2.5 ft) in Port San Luis. [KEEP] Small waves were observed at Seal Beach. [KEEP] At San Gregorio, California, four fishermen were swept out to sea by the tsunami. [KEEP] Two of the men were injured and received medical treatment while another two were rescued and unhurt. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Americas> \c\cAlong the coast of Peru, the tsunami was damaging. [KEEP] Restaurants and boats in Lagunillas beach and San Andrés District were damaged by waves. [KEEP] Damage to piers and some homes occurred in the capital Lima. [KEEP] In some areas, boat owners dragged their boats onto shore to prevent the waves from damaging them. [KEEP] Some material damage was confirmed on the beaches. [KEEP] A wave measuring 0.68 m was recorded in the port of Callao, 0.72 m in Marcona District and 0.65 m in Paita. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Americas> \c\cIn northern Chile, waves of up to 2 meters struck the coastline. [KEEP] Videos and images on social media from the Los Ríos Region showed the tsunami damaging piers, carrying boats and hitting beaches. [KEEP] Coastal evacuation notices were issued in 14 of the 16 regions in Chile. [KEEP] A "Red alert" level was issued to more than 6,400 km of ts coastline. [KEEP] The Chilean National Office for Emergency (ONEMI) said that tsunami activity can persist overnight so those affected have to sustain on their emergency supplies and aid. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Americas> \c\cMinor tsunamis related to the eruption were measured as far away as the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea, with NOAA reporting a maximum rise of 0.18 m (0.59 ft) in Puerto Rico. [KEEP] <Tsunami - Americas> \c\cA tsunami warning was issued on 14 January in Tonga after an eruption was observed. [KEEP] Volcanic activity decreased following that eruption and the warning was lifted in the early morning of 15 January. [KEEP] A 30-centimetre wave was observed during the first tsunami warning. [KEEP] Another warning was issued to the whole of Tonga on the evening of 15 January following another large eruption. [KEEP] Warning sirens blared in Nukuʻalofa while authorities urged residents to flee to higher ground. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cThe Mineral Resources Department in Fiji issued advisories to people living around the coastal areas to stay away from the shores. [KEEP] Evacuations were made on the Lau Islands after wave activity was observed in the sea. [KEEP] Fiji's Acting Prime Minister Aiyaz Sayed-Khaiyum urged the public to stay indoors and cover household water tanks in the event of rain due to the risk of sulfuric acid generated from the eruption. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cTsunami warnings were also issued to American Samoa by the Pacific Tsunami Warning Center (PTWC). [KEEP] The PTWC considered the tsunami "hazardous" and warned that changes in sea level, as well as strong currents could pose a risk along the coast. [KEEP] Samoa later issued a tsunami advisory. [KEEP] The PTWC later cancelled the tsunami warning for American Samoa. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cThe National Emergency Management Agency of New Zealand told residents to expect "strong and unusual currents and unpredictable surges" along the north and east coast of North Island, as well as the Chatham Islands. [KEEP] The agency added that the currents have the potential to injure and drown people. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cA tsunami warning was issued by the Bureau of Meteorology in Australia, with a land warning issued for Norfolk Island and Lord Howe Island, and a marine warning for the east coast of Australia, Tasmania and Macquarie Island. [KEEP] On January 16, at 06:55 local time, tsunami warnings were issued to New South Wales, Queensland, Victoria, and Tasmania for strong and dangerous currents. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cThe Japan Meteorological Agency informed residents that a slight disturbance in the sea could occur without any damage. [KEEP] The tsunami would not pose a threat to Japanese coastline. [KEEP] Officials from the JMA said that sea level rise of no more than 20 centimetres (7.9 in) can be expected for 24 hours from 9:00 p.m. [KEEP] Japan Standard Time. [KEEP] A tsunami warning was issued in the Amami Islands and Tokara Islands by the JMA with forecasted waves of up to 3 metres (9.8 ft). [KEEP] Additional warnings were issued to the east and southeast coast for waves of up to 1 metre (3 ft 3 in). [KEEP] A warning and evacuation order was issued to Iwate Prefecture, and evacuation orders were also issued to six other prefectures. [KEEP] The Fire and Disaster Management Agency (FDMA) said that 210,000 residents living in the seven prefectures were evacuated. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cThe National Tsunami Warning Center issued a tsunami advisory along the West Coast of the United States and British Columbia, Canada. [KEEP] The advisory contained all U.S. areas along the West Coast from Southern California to Alaska. [KEEP] Tsunami waves measuring 1–2 feet (0.30–0.61 m) are expected to hit the shores as early as 7:30 a.m. [KEEP] Pacific Standard Time (UTC−8) along the Central Coast. [KEEP] San Francisco was expected to receive waves at 8:10. [KEEP] The highest tsunami waves are expected one to two hours after the arrival of the first waves. [KEEP] A tsunami advisory was put in place for the entirety of Hawaii. [KEEP] Advisories in Canada were issued along the North and Central coasts of British Columbia, along with the Haida Gwaii archipelago and Vancouver Island. [KEEP] No evacuation issue was ordered, but people were urged to avoid beaches and marinas. [KEEP] The warning level was low due to the height of reported waves, as they were below the 91 centimetres (36 in) threshold which would warrant an upgrade. [KEEP] Chile also issued a warning for a "minor tsunami" for most of its coastal area including the island of Rapa Nui, evacuation was declared for other 12 regions. [KEEP] <Response> \c\cRescue operations are underway at Atata Island, located off the main Tonga island near Nukuʻalofa after the small island was reportedly submerged by the tsunami. [KEEP] <Rescue> \c\cNew Zealand's Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern said officials in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs are discussing the provision of aid to Tonga. [KEEP] She has described the events in Tonga as "hugely concerning". [KEEP] <Assistance> \c\c
[KEEP] The attack was termed by the SOHR as the largest attack committed by the Islamic State since it lost it's last key Syrian territory in 2019. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The first wave of the attack occurred late at night on 20 January, when Islamic State forces launched a car bomb attack targeting the prison whilst Islamic State ground fighters began to open fire on the prison with heavy weapons. [KEEP] <Timeline - January 20> \c\c [KEEP] The attack triggered a prison riot where the prisoners successfully managed to obtain weaponry from the armoury and then began a full blown attack on the prison staff. [KEEP] The prison was subsequently occupied by armed prisoners and several prisoners managed to escape. [KEEP] <Timeline - January 20> \c\cClashes continued into the next day, by which Islamic State fighters had spread to the Al-Zouhour area of Al-Hasakah city as well as solidified control of the Ghuwayran prison. [KEEP] In an effort to support Kurdish forces fighting in the city, forces of the International Coalition had dispatched military aircraft to the area. [KEEP] <Timeline - January 21> \c\cSDF forces also announced that they had managed to track down and arrest 89 of the prisoners that had escaped the prison. [KEEP] It was also reported that the electricity to several parts of Al-Hasakah city had been cut off due to the clashes. [ADD] During the clashes, it was reported that U.S fighter jets had conducted 2 airstrikes on Islamic State held buildings in the city. \c\c [KEEP] The SOHR reported that clashes continued between Islamic State and Kurdish forces over control of the prison and its surrounding areas." [KEEP] } <Timeline - January 21> \c\c
[KEEP] Singapore is currently the most-vaccinated country in the world, with more than 88% of its total population (and more than 91% of its eligible populace) having completed their vaccination regimen. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe Singapore Government invested more than one billion Singapore dollars to sign advanced purchase agreements and made early down payments on promising vaccine candidates, such as Pfizer BioNTech, Moderna and CoronaVac. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 5 October 2020, the Singapore Government appointed a 14-member Expert Committee on COVID-19 Vaccination, which was to advise and assess on the efficacy and safety of COVID-19 vaccines for use in Singapore. [KEEP] On 24 December 2020, the Expert Committee submitted its recommendations on the overall vaccination strategy of Singapore to the government. [KEEP] In its recommendations, they highlighted that two groups of people had to be priortised for vaccination: people who are at high risk of infection, the frontline healthcare workers; and people who are vulnerable of severe diseases and complications from infections, the elderly. [KEEP] The Committee continued to advise on the use of vaccines as the pandemic continues. [KEEP] It recommended booster shots for people above 60 of age as evidence of declining effacy of vaccination over time emerged, and updated recommendations for those with mild skin reactions after first dosage to continue their vaccination programme. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 14 December 2020, Singapore became the first Asian country to approve Pfizer-BioNTech's coronavirus vaccine. [KEEP] The first shipment of the vaccine arrived seven days later on 21 December. [KEEP] <Background - Expert Committee on COVID-19 Vaccination> \c\cSingapore also received its first shipment of Sinovac Biotech's CoronaVac vaccine, on 22 December 2020. [KEEP] However, the vaccine was not authorised for use by the Health Sciences Authority (HSA). [KEEP] On 2 June 2021, MOH approved the Sinovac vaccine for used in private healthcare settings so people, who are not suitable to take the mRNA vaccines, can take the Sinovac vaccine. [KEEP] However, since the China-made vaccine is not part of the national programme, those who choose to receive it will not be eligible for the Vaccine Injury Financial Assistance Programme (VIFAP) should they develop any adverse reactions. [KEEP] <Background - 2020> \c\cOn 30 December 2020, Singapore became the first country in Asia to start its COVID-19 vaccination campaign. [KEEP] The vaccine is free for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. [KEEP] Health workers, other frontline workers and seniors were the first inoculated with the vaccine jointly developed by BioNTech and Pfizer. [KEEP] <Background - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] 3 February 2021, Singapore also became the first country in Asia to approve Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine, jointly developed by the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), the Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority (BARDA), and Moderna. [KEEP] <Background - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] 18 May, the Health Ministry announced that those who register for COVID-19 vaccination from 19 May onwards will have their second dose scheduled six to eight weeks after the first, instead of three to four weeks later. [KEEP] This change in strategy was aimed to have 400,000 more people in Singapore to be given at least one vaccine dose by end-July so that virtually all eligible Singapore residents will get at least one dose by early August. [KEEP] However, as vaccine supplies continue to arrive as planned and most of the population who are willing to take the vaccine will have received their first dose by the second half of July, MOH announced on 29 June that the interval between the first and second doses of the COVID-19 vaccine would revert to four weeks. [KEEP] This was part of the efforts to ensure that more of the population will be fully vaccinated earlier. [KEEP] On 9 July, it was announced that the interval between doses of the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine would be further shortened to 3 weeks. [KEEP] It was further added that those who had previously taken a vaccine not approved under the National Vaccination Programme would be advised to take 2 doses of the approved ones. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\c [KEEP] The Health Sciences Authority (HSA) also approved the use of the Pfizer-BioNTech coronavirus vaccine for children aged 12 to 15; previously, it was given only to those aged 16 years and above. [KEEP] It was granted interim authorization by the HSA under the Pandemic Special Access Route in December 2020. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn 24 June, the Health Ministry concluded a purchase agreement with Novavax for its non-mRNA COVID-19 vaccine, with shipments expected to arrive in Singapore before the end of 2021. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn 28 July, IHH Healthcare Singapore obtained approval to import the Sinopharm BIBP vaccine (BBIBP-CorV) via the special access route (SAR). [KEEP] The SAR was set up on 31 May to allow individuals to choose vaccines not under the national inoculation program. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn 2 August, Senior Minister of State for Health Janil Puthucheary announced in Parliament that those who suffered allergic reactions after receiving the first dose of an mRNA COVID-19 vaccine will be invited to receive the Sinovac CoronaVac vaccine and will be deemed as fully vaccinated individuals. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 6 August, the Health Ministry announced it shall recognize all COVID-19 vaccines listed under the Emergency Use Listing (EUL) by the World Health Organization (WHO) starting from 10 August 2021. [KEEP] This means that Singapore recognizes all individuals that have been inoculated with a WHO-approved vaccine as fully vaccinated individuals and shall be accorded vaccination-differentiated safe management measures and travel concessions. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn 20 September, an additional 101,000 doses of the Sinovac vaccine was delivered. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 23 October, the Health Sciences Authority (HSA) granted interim authorization under the Pandemic Special Access Route for the CoronaVac vaccine under a three-dose regime, following which it was included in the National Vaccination Programme. [KEEP] Those who are ineligible to take either of the approved mRNA vaccines would be invited for this vaccine and eligible for the Vaccine Injury Financial Assistance Programme (VIFAP). [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 10 December, the Health Sciences Authority approved the use of the Pfizer-BioNTech coronavirus vaccine for children aged 5 to 11 with the first shots to be given by end-2021. [KEEP] At the same time, Pfizer-BioNTech coronavirus vaccine is approved for full registration. [KEEP] The first shipment of the paediatric vaccine arrived seven days later on 22 December with the first shots given on 27 December. [KEEP] <Background - 2021> \c\cSingapore started the rolling out of booster shots for senior citizens above 60 years of age from 14 September 2021. [KEEP] Subsequently, from 4 October, it will start giving booster shots for the eligible population above 50 years of age, followed by individuals above 30 years of age from 9 October. [KEEP] The eligible population should have their second dose taken before 6 months. [KEEP] From 24 November, eligible population who completed their second dose before 5 months can get booster shots for all age groups. [KEEP] On 10 December, the use of booster shots is extended to individuals above 18 years of age starting from 14 December. [ADD] From 14 March 2022, children aged 12 to 17 will need to get a booster shot within 270 days of receiving their second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. [KEEP] The issuance of this special sticker will be limited to travelers who have been vaccinated with a COVID-19 vaccine under the Emergency Use Listing (EUL) by the World Health Organization (WHO) and the presentation of a valid English-language vaccination certificate. [KEEP] <Background - Booster shots> \c\cOn 24 September 2021, Malaysian National Recovery Council chairman Muhyiddin Yassin confirmed that Malaysia and Singapore would recognise each other's vaccination certificates  in order to facilitate travel between the two countries." [KEEP] } <Recognition of vaccine certificates> \c\c
[KEEP] On 25 January 2022, militants stormed a security post belonging to Pakistani military in a remote area of Dasht, Kech District in Balochistan killing at least ten security personnel and injuring three others. [KEEP] The clash lasted for few hours in which militants also suffered several casualties. [KEEP] Additionally, the militants also seized weapons that were present in the security post. [KEEP] Locals in the area also confirmed that an attack on the security post took place and that the militants suffered heavy casualties in the attack. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cPakistani law enforcement agencies say that one militant was killed and several other militants were injured when the militants attacked the security post. [KEEP] Three militants responsible for the attack were also arrested by the law enforcement agencies during a search operation in the vicinity of the security post. [RM] No group has taken responsibility for the attack on security post. [SUB] No group has taken responsibility for the attack on security post initially. [RM] Gohram Baloch, the spokesperson of the banned Balochistan Liberation Front (BLF) has claimed responsibility for the attack. [ADD] After several times,Gohram Baloch, the spokesperson of the banned Balochistan Liberation Front (BLF) has claimed responsibility for the attack. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c
