[KEEP] A coup d\'état was attempted in Guinea-Bissau on 1 February 2022. [RM] At least one person is said to have been killed. [ADD] President Umaro Sissoco Embalo said that "many" members of the security forces had been killed in a "failed attack against democracy." [KEEP] The Portugal’s foreign affairs minister, Augusto Santos Silva, said that the president of Guinea-Bissau was at his residence but it was unclear if an attack on the government of Guinea-Bissau was over. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c [KEEP] The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) called for peace in Guinea Bissau. [KEEP] ECOWAS said in a statement, "ECOWAS condemns the coup attempt and holds the military responsible for the physical integrity of President Umaro Sissoco Embalo and members of his government." [KEEP] The statement concluded, " ECOWAS asks the military to return to their barracks and maintain a republican posture" The African Union also condemned the \'attempted coup\'. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\c
[KEEP] On 2 February 2022, over 60 civilians were killed in a massacre in Djugu territory, Ituri Province, Democratic Republic of the Congo. [RM] <Summary> \c\cDuring the early hours of 2 February 2022, CODECO insurgents carried out a massacre of over 60 residents of Plaine Savo. It is a camp for internally displaced people in Ituri Province in the northeast of the Democratic Republic of the Congo in which around 4,000 people live. [ADD] <Summary> \c\cDuring the early hours of 2 February 2022, CODECO insurgents armed with machetes and "edged weapons" carried out a massacre of over 60 residents of Plaine Savo, a camp for internally displaced people in Ituri Province in the northeast of the Democratic Republic of the Congo in which around 4,000 people live.
[KEEP] Whaling in Iceland began with spear-drift hunting as early as the 12th century, and continued in a vestigial form until the late 19th century, when other countries introduced modern commercial practices. [KEEP] Today, Iceland is one of a handful of countries that formally object[clarification needed] to an ongoing moratorium established by the International Whaling Commission in 1986, and that still maintain a whaling fleet. [KEEP] One company remains concentrated on hunting fin whales, largely for export to Japan, while the only other one previously hunted minke whales for domestic consumption until 2020, as the meat was popular with tourists. [KEEP] In 2018, Icelandic whalers were accused of slaughtering a blue whale. [KEEP] Whaling has been temporarily paused in Iceland since 2019 as coronavirus restrictions, competition from subsidized Japanese whaling, and increasing domestic whale watching tourism have hampered the industry. [KEEP] It is uncertain if commercial whaling will resume in 2022. [ADD] In 2022, Iceland announced that they would halt commercial whaling by 2024. [ADD] https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/2/4/iceland-to-end-whaling-as-demand-dwindles
[KEEP] The Jihadist insurgency in Burkina Faso (French: Insurrection djihadiste au Burkina Faso) is an ongoing war and civil conflict between the Government of Burkina Faso and Islamist rebels. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe war have been interpreted as being the Burkinabè theatre of the insurgency in the Maghreb. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cBlaise Compaoré, president of Burkina Faso from 1987 to 2014, treated Islamists somewhat better than French colonial officials did. [KEEP] Compaore's Mauritanian advisor, Moustapha Ould Limam Chafi and General Gilbert Diendéré both contacted several Islamist leaders in order to free hostages held by these groups. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cBurkina [KEEP] Faso acted as a mediator during the Mali War between rebels and the government. [KEEP] Burkina Faso led an intervention into the country in 2013. [KEEP] However, in November 2014, Compaoré was overthrown, marking the end of his rule and creating a scenario of instability. [KEEP] <Background> \c\cOn 23 [KEEP] August 2015, the insurgency in the Maghreb spread to Burkina Faso, beginning with a attack on a gendarmerie by alleged Boko Haram members. [KEEP] Between August 2015 and October 2016, seven different posts were attacked across the country, slaying 15 and injuring 11. [KEEP] On 9 October, three gendarmes, one rebel, and one civilian were slain during a battle in Samorougan, Hauts-Bassins. [KEEP] On 31 May 2016, three police officers were shot dead in Intangom. [KEEP] On 1 September 2016, a team of two to four jihadists murdered a customs officer and a civilian in Markoye, injuring three others. [KEEP] Two days later, Sahrawi terrorist Adnane Abou Walid Al-Sahraoui accepted responsibility for the attack. [KEEP] <Timeline> \c\cOn [KEEP] 15 January 2016, terrorists attacked the capital city of Ouagadougou, killing 30 people. [KEEP] Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and Al-Mourabitoune both took responsibility. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015–2016> \c\cIn 2016, the amount of attacks spiked after a new group was founded : Ansarul Islam, led by imam Ibrahim Malam Dicko. [KEEP] The group is particularly active at the border territories of Mali and Burkina Faso. [KEEP] A large proportion of attacks have been focused on Soum province. [KEEP] On 16 December, Ansarul Islam killed dozens of people in the attack on Nassoumbou. [KEEP] On the first of January 2017,  an Imam and defect from Asarul Islam was assassinated in Tongomayel. [KEEP] Two months later, a teacher was murdered in the village of Kourfayel, Soum province. [KEEP] On 22 March, the leader of Ansarul Islam, Harouna Dicko, was shot dead in Pétéga by security forces. [KEEP] By this point, a total of 70 people, the majority of them soldiers, gendarmes and police officers, had been killed in a series of 20 attacks. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2015–2016> \c\cBetween 27 March – 10 April 2017, the governments of Mali, France, and Burkina Faso launched a joint operation name "Operation Panga," composed of 1,300 soldiers from the three countries, in Fhero forest, near the Burkina Faso-Mali border, considered a sanctuary for Ansarul Islam. [KEEP] On 5 April, Jama\'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin detonated an improvised explosive device on a French military vehicle, injuring two people. [KEEP] An allied detachment found them during a searching operation, but were attacked by the armed Islamist group again, slaying a soldier. [KEEP] During the ensuing twelve days of searching, two jihadists were killed, 8 taken prisoner, and up to 200 suspects arrested. [KEEP] The French forces quickly returned to the offensive, leading several successful raids against military targets. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2017> \c\cOn 27 [KEEP] May, in Pétéga, a retired policeman was assassinated by a group of armed men, but one of them was killed during the operation. [KEEP] On the night between 2 and 3 June, at least five people, including a couple and their child, were murdered in targeted attacks across Soum province. [KEEP] On 9 June, military forces rounded up 74 villagers in the town of Djibo accused of collaborating with Ansarul Islam. [KEEP] Several of the villagers were tortured, two fatally. [KEEP] On 12 July, a shootout between authorities and jihadists took place, with no casualties. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2017> \c\c [KEEP] The head of Ansarul Islam, Ibrahim Malam Dicko was killed in June 2017. [KEEP] The group announced a new leader, Jafar Dicko. [KEEP] On the night of 24 to 25 July, five members of Ansarul Islam were assassinated in the villages of Ndidja, Sibé and Neyba, Soum province, possibly by the new leadership. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2017> \c\cOn 14 August 2017, a pair of armed men entered a restaurant in Ouagadougou, murdering 18 people before they were shot dead by Burkinabè authorities. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2017> \c\cOn 17 August, a Burkinabè army vehicle rolled over an explosive in Touronata, killing three people and injuring two more. [KEEP] This is the first such incident in the country's history. [KEEP] On 15 September, three men, including an imam and the local village chief, were slain by armed men in Soum province. [KEEP] On 23 September, seven soldiers were killed in a mine explosion. [KEEP] Three days later, two gendarmes were killed in an ambush by jihadists. [KEEP] On 9 November, the Burkina Faso Armed Forces successfully  neutralized 12 jihadists in the village of Ariel. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2017> \c\cOn [KEEP] 2 March 2018, Jama\'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin attacked the French embassy in Ouagadougou as well as the general staff of the Burkinabè army. [KEEP] Eight soldiers and eight attackers were killed, and a further 61 soldiers and 24 civilians were injured . [KEEP] <Timeline - 2017> \c\cIn 2018, the insurgency expanded to the east of the country. [KEEP] The jihadists launched three attacks on 13 June : in Tindangou, against a police checkpoint, and on the police station and gendarmerie brigade of Comin-Yanga. [KEEP] During the last attack security forces managed to shoot an assailant. [KEEP] On 12 August, six people were killed by rebels in a bomb attack in Boungou, near Fada N\'Gourma. [KEEP] On the night of 27–28 August, eight soldiers died after an explosive device detonated near Pama. [KEEP] On the night of 14–15 September, Jihadists murdered nine people in the villages of Diabiga and Kompiembiga including a religious leader. [KEEP] A few weeks later, rebels kidnapped three employees in a gold mine – an Indian, a South-African and a Burkinabé, slaying three gendarmes in the process. [KEEP] On 4 October, six soldiers died after their military convoy ran over an explosive device. [KEEP] That night, an army of forty Islamists launched an attack against local gendarmes in Inata. [KEEP] The following day, six policemen died in a mine bombing near Sollé. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\cIn early October, the Armed Forces of Burkina Faso unrolled a major military operation in the country's East, supported by French forces. [KEEP] On 3 December, gendarmes successfully repelled an ambush at Bougui, ten kilometres from Fada N\'Gourma, killing six assailants and injuring another. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\cOn 1 January 2019, armed men murdered six people in the village of Yirgou, Barsalogho department. [KEEP] The villagers, mostly ethnic Mossis, (who form 52% of Burkina Faso's population) responded by massacring the Fulani members of the town, in what is now known as the Yirgou massacre [fr]. [KEEP] 72 people died and over 6,000 were displaced during the incident. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2018> \c\cOn [KEEP] 10 January, a group of 36 jihadists slew twelve civilians in Gasseliki. [KEEP] 17 days later, ten more civilians were killed in Sikiré, near Arbinda. [KEEP] On 28 January, four Burkinabé soldiers were killed and five others wounded in Nassoumbou. [KEEP] From 3–4 February, jihadists are reported to have massacred 14 civilians in  Kaïn, 80 kilometres from Ouahigouya. [KEEP] On 4 February, the army reportedly neutralized 146 jihadists in the departments of Kaïn, Banh and Bomborokuy. [KEEP] Human Rights Watch alleged that the military had carried out several summary executions in the process. [KEEP] The Burkinabé Movement for Human and Peoples\' Rights reported that no evidence was found of an attack carried out by terrorists in Kain on that date, and that about sixty civilians were executed without trial by the soldiers. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cOn 15 February, the Centre-Est region experienced its first attack. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cAccording to Human Rights Watch, between mid-2018 to February 2019, at least 42 people were murdered by jihadists and a minimum of 116 mostly Fulani civilians were killed by military forces without trial. [KEEP] From 31 March to 2 April, ethnic clashes between Fulani, Kurumbas, and Mossis killed 62 people in Arbinda. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cIn 2019, Jihadist groups began to start a persecution campaign against Christians. [KEEP] The campaign began on 28 April 2019, when six people, including a pastor, were killed by a group of 10 to 20 people inside a Protestant church in Silgadji. [KEEP] On 12 May, six more people, including one priest, died in a Catholic church in Dablo after it was raided by Islamists. [KEEP] The next day, a Catholic procession was targeted near Kayon and Singa-Rimaïbé, in Zimtanga department. [KEEP] Four people were murdered and a statue of the Virgin Mary was destroyed. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cOn the night of 9–10 May, French forces attacked a jihadist encampment near Gorom-Gorom, freeing four hostages — two French, one South-Korean and one American. [KEEP] Four jihadists and two French soldiers died. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cDespite this success, massacres have continued to grow more common. [KEEP] On 9 June 19 civilians died in an attack on Arbinda. [KEEP] On 18 June, armed men murdered 17–18 people in the village of Béléhédé. [KEEP] On 22 June 15 villagers in Sagho and Toekédogo, Barsalogho department, were killed, and on the night of 25–26 July, 22 other villagers died in a massacre in Dibilou, nearby the city of Kaya. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cAccording to the NGO, Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project, armed violence in Burkina Faso jumped by 174 % in 2019, with nearly 1,300 civilians dead and 860,000 deplaced. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cOn 4 January 2020, a bus carrying mainly middle school students blew up after it ran over an explosive device between Toéni and Tougan, resulting in fourteen deaths. [KEEP] On 20 January, jihadists attacked the villages of Nagraogo and Alamou, inside Barsalogho, Sanmatenga, and massacred 36 civilians. [KEEP] The day later, the Parliament of Burkina Faso adopted a law permitting the recruitment of civilian militias called Koglweogo to fight the jihadists. [KEEP] The idea was initially proposed by president Roch Marc [KEEP] Christian Kaboré in November 2019. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2019> \c\cOn 25 January, the village of Silgadji was attacked again, this time with a death toll of 39 civilians. [KEEP] Three days after, six soldiers were killed between Madjoari and Pama, in Kompienga province. [KEEP] On 12 February, two civilians were killed by jihadists in Tanwalbougou. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] Sunday, 16 February, a Protestant church in Pansi was attacked by armed jihadists, who murdered 24 people (including the pastor) and wounding 20 more. [KEEP] This was a week before five people (also including a pastor) were slain in a church in the neighbouring town of Sebba. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn [KEEP] 29 February, Sebba was attacked again, leaving ten policemen dead. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn 8 March, the Fulani villages of Barga-Peulh and Dinguila-Peulh, Barga department, were raided by pro-government militias, leaving forty civilians dead. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cIn October, around fifty refugees who had fled elsewhere tried to return to their home region, thinking that the violence had decreased. [KEEP] Their convoy was ambushed in the middle of the night, ten kilometers from Pissila. [KEEP] 25 male refugees, approximately half of the convoy, were murdered by the attackers. [KEEP] All women and children were spared. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cFrom 4–5 June, unknown militants massacred over 170 people in the villages of Solhan and Tadaryat. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2020> \c\cOn 20 August, jihadists killed 80 people in Gorgadji, including 59 civilians. [KEEP] On 14 November, the Jama\'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin attacked a gendarmerie in Soum province, killing 53 soldiers. [KEEP] On 21 November, an attack in Foubé resulted in nine soldiers dead and ten civilians killed. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cIn [KEEP] December, a group of civilians stopped a French convoy in Kaya Department, alleging that France was secretly working with the jihadists. [KEEP] In a separate incident during that month, Islamists killed 41 people in an ambush, including the popular vigilante leader Ladji Yoro. [KEEP] Yoro was a central figure in the Volunteers for the Defense of the Homeland, or VDP for short, a pro-government militia that has taken a leading role in the country's struggle against Islamists. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 15 January, at least 10 civilians were killed in an attack blamed on jihadists in northern Burkina Faso, in the village of Namssiguian in Bam province. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2021> \c\cOn [KEEP] 23 January, military officials overthrew Kabore's ruling government. [KEEP] Government failures to quell the Islamist insurgency has been described as a possible motive for the coup, which received unusual popularity. [KEEP] The junta's leader, Paul-Henri Sandaogo Damiba, is well-known for his widely popular military operations against Islamists. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2022> \c\cAllegations have arisen in the aftermath of the coup that the Patriotic Movement for Safeguard and Restoration may hire mercenaries from the Wagner Group in the future. [KEEP] Damiba had called earlier to hire Russian mercenaries against the Islamists, but was forbidden to do so by Kabore. [KEEP] <Timeline - 2022> \c\cOn 27 January, France confirmed that from 15 to 23 January 2022, more than sixty recorded jihadists had been "neutralized" in four separate incidents by Burkinabé soldiers working together with French units. [ADD] <Timeline - 2022> \c\cTen member of Ansarul Islam died during a battle with French forces on February 10 near Ouahigouya. [ADD] Four civilians died in the crossfire. [ADD] French authorities expressed regret for the civilian casualties, which they assured was accidental. [KEEP] In October 2019, 14 men had their turbans ripped off by government forces, then forced into a truck and executed. [KEEP] Fulanis have also been subject to violence by pro-government civilians, such as during the 2019 Yirgou massacre, in which hundreds of civilians were murdered by ethnic Mossis. [KEEP] <Humanitarian situation> \c\cIn 2020, a mass grave of over 180 civilians was found near Djibo, killed by government forces. [KEEP] Summary executions and war crimes by the military have become an ordinary incident in the town. [KEEP] In one separate incident, 10 civilians were killed in a market place in Petagoli, three of them Dogon foreigners from Mali. [KEEP] <Humanitarian situation> \c\cJihadists have also been guilty of human rights abuses. [KEEP] Villagers have been terrorized during their everyday lives, often prohibited from holding baptisms or marriages; the assassination of local elders has become a common occurrence. [KEEP] From April 2019 to January 2020, Human Rights Watch recorded the killing of at least 256 civilians in a series of 20 different attacks. [KEEP] <Humanitarian situation> \c\cIslamists have also targeted schools, the most famous example happening on 12 November 2018, when six Islamists broke into a primary school, mugged the principal, and attacked several students. [KEEP] This was one of the few local cases in which the people responsible for such an attack were arrested. [KEEP] Rebels have justified attacks on schools by painting them as French and Western-style indoctrination programs. [KEEP] Numerous schools have been shut down, leading to an estimated 300,000 children without access to education. [KEEP] <Humanitarian situation> \c\c
[KEEP] Operation Unifier, also known as Canadian Armed Forces Joint Task Force-Ukraine, is the Canadian Armed Forces contribution to the security of Ukraine in coordination with the Ukrainian Armed Forces. [KEEP] It also includes a small Swedish contingent. [KEEP] It was begun in light of fomentation by the of separatist sentiments in the Donetsk and Luhansk and Crimean regions of Ukraine after the 2014 Ukrainian revolution and the 2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe operation is part of Multinational Joint Commission, a larger body composed of the U.S., UK, Canada, Sweden, Poland, Lithuania and Denmark aimed at reforming Ukraine's military. [KEEP] The first Canadian troops to participate in the operation come from the 1st Battalion, Royal Canadian Regiment. [KEEP] The Canadian contribution of training is provided by about 200 Canadian soldiers, rotating every 6 months, increased to 260 in January 2022. [KEEP] As of November 2018 there have been 230 course sessions and more than 10,000 Ukrainian soldiers have been trained under Operation Unifier. [KEEP] Since 2018, a small Swedish contingent also operates within the framework. [KEEP] In December 2021, three Swedish officers were in Ukraine within the framework of Operation Unifier. [KEEP] <Synopsis> \c\cCanada made its first delivery of non-lethal military equipment to Ukraine on November 28, 2014. [KEEP] This equipment mainly included cold protective clothing and was delivered to Boryspil International Airport by the Royal Canadian Air Force (RCAF). [KEEP] On January 10, 2015, the first shipment of non-lethal military equipment to Ukraine by sea arrived at the port of Odessa. [KEEP] On April 14, 2015, Canada announced the deployment of a CAF task force, known as Joint Task Force Ukraine or Operation Unifier, with nearly 200 Canadian Armed Forces stationed in Ukraine until March 31, 2017. [KEEP] The military training mission officially began on 14 September 2015 at the International Center for Security and Peacekeeping in Starychi and the Ukrainian Ministry of Defense Demining Center in Kamianets-Podilskyi. [KEEP] <History> \c\cOn [ADD] February 13, 2022, the Canadian Armed Forces announced that the operation would be temporarily suspended due to the 2021–2022 Russo-Ukrainian crisis, with most of the units involved being sent to Poland. [ADD] Canada has assured Ukraine that the withdrawal is only temporary. <History> \c\cOn [KEEP] <History - Extensions> \c\cOn [KEEP] January 26, 2022, the Government of Canada announced the extension of Operation Unifier until the end of March 2025, and increased the complement of 200 by another 60. [KEEP] <History - Extensions> \c\cAccording to lobbyists from the NATO Association of Canada, Operation Unifier's broader mission includes: <Mission> \c\cHelping the development of the region <Mission> \c\cMaintaining [KEEP] Security <Mission> \c\cMaintaining Democracy <Mission> \c\cProviding Humanitarian Aid <Mission> \c\cPromoting economic stability and growth <Mission> \c\cLieutenant Colonel Jeffrey Troop (October 2019-28 April 2020) [KEEP] <Commanders> \c\cLieutenant Colonel Ryan Simpson (28 April 2020-) [KEEP] <Commanders> \c\cLieutenant Colonel Sarah Heer (since 6 October 2020) [KEEP] <Commanders> \c\cMembers of the Ukrainian diaspora in Canada positively welcomed the Canadian government's contribution to reform the Ukrainian military. [KEEP] A number of community appreciation events were held in Toronto, Edmonton and Winnipeg for CAF members who have served in Operation Unifier. [KEEP] On July 1, 2018, the Band of the Ceremonial Guard performed during its daily guard mounting ceremony on Parliament Hill, a Ukrainian military march known as "Shchob shabli ne braly, shchob Kuli mynaly" (Щоб шаблі не брали, щоб кулі минали) in front of members of the Ukrainian diaspora during the ceremony, as a sort of response to the operation. [KEEP] <Ukrainian diaspora response> \c\c
[KEEP] The Rule of Law Conditionality Regulation is a regulation of the European Union and Euratom, which allows the European Commission to adopt measures, including the suspension of payment of funds from the EU budget, to member states which violate the principles of rule of law enshrined in article 2 of the Treaty on European Union. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cDemocratic backsliding in Hungary and Poland has been a major concern for the European Union since the 2010s. [KEEP] In December 2017, the European Commission initiated article 7 suspension proceedings against Poland, and in September 2018, the European Parliament did the same against Hungary. [KEEP] The proceedings have since stalled, however, as a suspension of a member state under article 7 requires unanimity, excluding the member state concerned, and Hungary and Poland are widely expected to veto each other's suspension. [KEEP] <Legislative background> \c\cAs a solution to this problem, the European Commission proposed in May 2018 to link disbursements from the European Union's budget to adherence to rule of law standards by means of a regulation. [KEEP] The European Parliament adopted a position on the Commission's proposal in April 2019, but the Council was generally wary of confronting its members from Poland and Hungary. [KEEP] <Legislative background> \c\cThis changed during the adoption of the 2021–2027 Multiannual Financial Framework (MFF) and the Next Generation EU (NGEU) recovery package in the summer of 2020. [KEEP] At the July 2020 European Council summit, the heads of state and government of the EU member states agreed that these funds should be tied to a conditionality regime regarding the rule of law. [KEEP] Germany, holding the presidency of the Council, suggested a compromise on the rule of law conditionality regulation proposed by the Commission and European Parliament in September 2020. [KEEP] After trilogue meetings between the Council, the European Parliament, and the Commission, a legislative draft of the regulation was published on 5 November 2020. [KEEP] <Legislative background> \c\cAlthough the regulation could be adopted by the Council by a qualified majority, Hungary and Poland threatened to veto the Own Resources Decision, which defines how the MFF and NGEU are financed. [KEEP] At the European Council summit of 10 and 11 December 2020, the impasse was resolved by adopting a series of declarations on how the Rule of Law Conditionality Regulation should be adopted, implemented and interpreted. [KEEP] This paved the way for the adoption of the regulation by the Council on 14 December 2020 and by the European Parliament on 16 December 2020. [KEEP] <Legislative background> \c\c [KEEP] The regulation provides for the Commission to propose measures against a member state that violates the principles of the rule of law. [KEEP] These measures include the suspension of payments or commitments, and a prohibition on entering into new legal commitments. [KEEP] <Provisions> \c\cIn the context of the regulation, the rule of law is understood to refer to the values enshrined in article 2 of the Treaty on European Union, and include "the principles of legality implying a transparent, accountable, democratic and pluralistic law-making process; legal certainty; prohibition of arbitrariness of the executive powers; effective judicial protection, including access to justice, by independent and impartial courts, also as regards fundamental rights; separation of powers; and non-discrimination and equality before the law". [KEEP] <Provisions> \c\cArticle 4 of the regulation specifies that measures may only be taken if the violations of the rule of law "affect or seriously risk affecting the sound financial management of the Union budget or the protection of the financial interests of the Union in a sufficiently direct way". [KEEP] <Provisions> \c\c [KEEP] The declaratory statements adopted at the European Council summit of 10 and 11 December 2020 address how the European Council views the regulation should be implemented. [KEEP] The legal value of these declaratory statements is disputed. [KEEP] <Implementation> \c\cAccording to the European Council's declaratory statements, the Commission should not only develop guidelines for the application of the regulation, but also await the outcome of legal challenges to the regulation before implementing it. [KEEP] Furthermore, the Commission should only apply the regulation when there are no more efficient means to protect the Union's budget. [KEEP] <Implementation> \c\c [KEEP] The European Parliament adopted a resolution on 25 March 2021 in which it stressed "that the application of the Rule of Law Conditionality Regulation cannot be subject to the adoption of guidelines", urging "the Commission to avoid any further delay in its application" and "to keep Parliament regularly informed about all ongoing investigations into breaches of the principles of the rule of law which could affect, or seriously risk affecting, the sound financial management of the Union budget in a sufficiently direct way". [KEEP] The European Parliament threatened to take legal action against the Commission if it would not provide such information to the European Parliament by 1 June 2021. [KEEP] <Implementation> \c\cOn 10 June 2021, after the deadline had passed without the Commission providing the European Parliament with the necessary information, the European Parliament adopted another resolution, calling on the Commission to fulfil its obligations under the Rule of Law Conditionality Regulation within two weeks, and notifying the Commission that it would start preparations for legal action against the Commission for failure to act (article 265 TFEU). [KEEP] The European Commission rejected the ultimatum on 23 August 2021 with a five-page letter. [RM] <Implementation> \c\cOn 11 March 2021, Hungary and Poland separately launched legal proceedings with the Court of Justice of the European Union against the European Parliament and the Council for adopting the regulation, asking the court to annul the regulation as, according to Hungary and Poland, the regulation does not have an appropriate legal basis. The advocate general advised the Court to dismiss those challenges on 2 December 2021. [ADD] <Implementation> \c\cOn 11 March 2021, Hungary and Poland separately launched legal proceedings with the European Court of Justice against the European Parliament and the Council for adopting the regulation, asking the court to annul the regulation as, according to Hungary and Poland, the regulation does not have an appropriate legal basis and that it serves to circumvent the punitive mechanism built in the Article 7 of the Treaty on European Union. [KEEP] <Legal challenges> \c\c
[KEEP] Designated terrorist organisations in Australia are organisations that have been designated by the Australian government as terrorist organisations. [KEEP] A list of terrorist organisations was first created under the Security Legislation Amendment (Terrorism) Act 2002, as part of the fight against terrorism worldwide. [KEEP] <Summary> \c\cThe Security Legislation Amendment (Terrorism) Act 2002 was passed by the Australian Parliament, "enabling Australian governments to deal with organisations involved in terrorism", and inserted a range of terrorist organisation offences into the Criminal Code Act 1995 (Cth). [KEEP] For example, the Act made it an offence to materially support or be supported by a listed terrorist organisation. [KEEP] <History> \c\cThe list of designated terror organisations is maintained by the Attorney-General's Department. [KEEP] For listing as a terrorist organisation, an organisation may be found to be such by a court as part of a prosecution for a terrorist offence or the designation may be made by regulation upon the motion of the Attorney-General of Australia under Division 102 of the Criminal Code Act 1995. [KEEP] Listing, de-listing and re-listing follows a protocol that mainly involves the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation and the Attorney-General's Department. [KEEP] <Oversight and monitoring> \c\cUnder Division 103 of the Criminal Code Act 1995, it is illegal to finance terrorism. [ADD] Hamas was reinstated in 2022. \c\c [KEEP] The Base and the entirety of Hezbollah were added on 24 November 2021. [KEEP] <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\cAustralian anti-terrorism financing laws include: <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\cCriminal Code Act 1995 (Cth): <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 102.6 - getting funds to, from or for a terrorist organisation <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 102.7 - providing support to a terrorist organisation <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 103.1 - financing terrorism <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 103.2 - financing a terrorist, and <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 119.4(5) - giving or receiving goods and services to promote the commission of a foreign incursion offence. [KEEP] <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\cCharter of the United Nations Act 1945 (Cth): <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 20 - dealing with freezable assets, and <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\csection 21 - giving an asset to a proscribed person or entity. [KEEP] <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\cThese offences sanction persons and entities under Australian and international law. [KEEP] The responsibility of prosecuting these offences in Australia rests with the Australian Federal Police, State police forces and the Commonwealth Director of Public Prosecutions. [KEEP] <List of designated terrorist organisations> \c\c